He reported that originally had aches and fever, every joint in body hurt. Today when woke up all the pain was centralized in chest. Is currently in ER, and apparently a cardiac specialist is on his way for further evaluation. Did find EKG abnormalities. Has been taking more hydrocodone than normal due to the increased pain. Had a morphine shot this am at ER. Patient will keep this hospital abreast of outcome. A: Adverse reaction from recent PNEUMOVAX vaccine? See 3/8/12 associated information note. The patient was not pregnant. In 2007, the patient was originally vaccinated with a dose of VARIVAX (Merck), 1 shot (lot # and expiration date unspecified), subcutaneously. Concomitant therapies included lisinopril (manufacturer unknown), insulin, risperidone, unspecified birth control medicine and unspecified nasal spray. On an unspecified date, after receiving the vaccine, she began to experience itchiness and pain in her arms which had been afflicted with a severe case of psoriasis since childhood. The next day she noticed that the psoriasis had cleared largely from her arms, with pustule and plaque removal. Over time she noticed the psoriasis in her arms began to return, so she began to take VARIVAX (Merck) to clear flare ups and hoped to remove the psoriasis from the rest of her body. On an unknown date, she also experienced weight loss, and a faster metabolism which had helped her diabetes. No treatment was given for weight loss and faster metabolism. On an unspecified date, blood and urine studies were performed, but the results were not provided. After administered 10 shots of VARIVAX (Merck) (detail information concerning the dose and frequency unspecified) over the subsequent years, her psoriasis had been in remission and had not returned as a result of any normal triggers such as stress or diet. The patient had been sharing the results with her doctor. The outcome of weight loss and faster metabolism was not resolved (It was also reported that the events reappeared after reintroduction of VARIVAX (Merck)). The patient reported the events in hopes of having her results shared and that the product could be investigated for use in treating psoriasis and other inflammatory related issues and also wanted to submit her documentation. The patient also noted that after receiving GARDASIL, she experienced alleviation of her symptoms from Polycystic Ovarian Syndrome (capture into MARRS # 1601USA000100). Additional information has been requested.
LAB_DATA: On an unknown date, the patient experienced weight loss.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: This medically confirmed health authority report (initial receipt 21-Dec-2015) concerns a 47-year old male patient. The patient has a medical history of (left) Achilles tendon rupture seven weeks prior for which he received low molecular weight heparin for the prevention of thrombosis until 28-Nov-2015 and was an ongoing smoker at a rate of three cigarettes per day.  On 27-Nov-2015, the patient was vaccinated with Afluria 2015/2015 (influenza virus vaccine polyvalent, 0.5 ml dose, batch number: 098629703) via the intramuscular route. On 29-Nov-2015, the patient experienced pulmonary embolism (both sides), thrombosis of the lower right leg and acute dyspnea for which he was hospitalised from 29-Nov-2015 to 07-Dec-2015. The outcome was reported as not recovered. Reporter's Comments: Reporter's comments: The reporter assessed the events as serious (hospitalization) and possible in relation to the suspect drug.  The patient was hospitalised. Sender's Comments: Company comments: Seriousness criterion/criteria: hospitalization. Listedness: Unlisted. Assessment according to the CCSI for CSL Inactivated Influenza Virus Vaccine and the Afluria Product Information, pulmonary embolism, thrombosis of legs and acute dyspnoea are unlisted. Causality: Unrelated. Time to onset is 3 days following vaccination. However patient had history of Achilles tendon rupture seven weeks prior (probable immobility) and was a smoker. Both are risk factors for thrombosis and subsequent embolism. Unlikely pathomechanism linking Influenza vaccination to hypercoagulable state, hence causality is considered unrelated in presence of other more significant risks.
HISTORY: Smoker, 3 cigarettes/day; Achilles tendon rupture, seven weeks prior (left), Continuous thrombosis prevention with low molecular weight heparin

SYMPTOM_TEXT: This spontaneous report as received from a 61-year-old male patient, who was also a pharmacist and refers to himself. The patient's concurrent conditions, medical history and concomitant therapy were not reported. On an unknown date, the patient administered ZOSTAVAX (dose, lot#, expiration date and route of administration were not reported). The pharmacist stated that he did not wear gloves when he reconstituted the ZOSTAVAX. Sometimes after reconstituting, while he was trying to get the air out of the syringe, a small droplet formed at the end of the needle. Event though the droplet had no contact with his skin, it was possible that the droplet fell on the work surface. On 10-DEC-2015, pharmacist noticed the skin of outside edge of his left eye was itchy, not intense but was felt. He thought maybe he was contacting conjunctivitis, which did not develop. Another time, he felt a twinge at the same site of left eye (date unspecified). The patient stated that the night before the onset, he ate chili and was wondering if he somehow touched that area of his eye. Pharmacist stated all symptoms of the left eye resolved on approximately 14-DEC-2015. On 15-DEC-2015, he had itching on the left side of his lower ribs to the middle of back going around toward the front. He stated he had no rash, no papules, no shingles, only redness, which could have been from scratching. The patient mentioned he did yard work the day before and that could have been the cause. The outcome of itching on the left side of his lower ribs to the middle of back going around toward the front and redness was not reported. Causality assessment was not provided. Additional information has been requested.

Information has been received from a registered nurse referring to an 11 year old male patient with asthma and allergy to amoxicillin. On 21-DEC-2015 the patient was vaccinated with the first dose of GARDASIL 9 (lot # L020015 with expired date 16-AUG-2017, dose and route were unknown) along with MENACTRA and Tdap. Concomitant therapy also included albuterol sulfate inhaler (manufacturer unknown). The patient was observed for 10-15 minutes in the office following administration and he was doing fine with no issues so he was sent home. As the patient was leaving and walking out of the office with his mom, he fainted and hit his head on the ground. The reporter stated that fainting lasted less than a minute and the patient was conscious again. But the patient was very lethargic, was not responding on his own when the reporter asked what his name was and could not get up and walk on his own so the reporter and the patient's mom had to help him get up and they carried him back to exam room. The patient was laid down in the exam room. The patient was given GLUCOLA and some water because the patient did not eat anything this morning prior to receiving vaccines. The reporter checked the patient's blood sugar and pulse oximetry. Both of them were fine. The reporter noticed that the patient's respiration was little shallow and rough. But the patient was slowly coming back. In about 20 minutes, the patient was able to sit up by himself and able to respond to questions. The patient was asked to walk back and forth after he was fully sitting up and he was able to walk on his own without any problem. The patient's vital signs were checked and everything was good. So the patient was sent home. The patient's mother called the office back about 10 minutes after leaving the office to inform the patient was all better and was doing fine. The outcome of the event "head injury" was unknown. Additional information has been requested.
LAB_DATA: Blood sugar (21-DEC-2015): fine (unit not provided, normal); pulse oximetry (21-DEC-2015): fine (unit not provided, normal); vital signs (21-DEC-2015): good (normal)

Hello, My 9-week-old went in for his two month vaccines this past Friday, November 20. When I returned to work after his appointment I received a call from his doctor's office saying that the nurse mistakenly gave my son two injections of sterile water and no vaccines. After further questioning, it now appears that they were wrong and that my son received all vaccines except for the powdered Hib mix in that should have been added to his PENTACEL injection. I'm still trying to get written documentation and clarification from his doctor's office to determine exactly what he did and didn't receive - did he receive saline or did he receive all but Hib? And until he goes back in, he's still vulnerable to meningitis and, should be happen to develop a fever between now and the time he receives his Hib vaccines, he'll be admitted to the hospital and require a spinal tap to rule out meningitis all because of the negligence of the nurse. He was seen at the office.

Re VIVOTIF Berna EC Capsules- live oral vaccine for typhoid Ty21a: 59 year old man developed acute onset diplopia in all visual fields after taking the second of four oral doses of this attenuated vaccine. The diplopia was primarily vertical. Past medical history notable only for controlled hypertension, on metoprolol, diltiazem, and losartan. There was no history of prior neurological abnormalities, visual disturbances, head trauma, or intercurrent or recent illnesses. Neurology and neuro-ophthalmology consults were obtained. Neurological exam was normal apart from diplopia. Brain MRI was unremarkable. Blood tests were unremarkable. Diagnosis by neuro-ophthalmologist was fourth cranial nerve palsy. After two weeks the patient (a physician) self-prescribed a 6-day steroid taper. Diplopia began to slowly improve after this, although it is uncertain to what extent steroids contributed. After two months the diplopia was restricted to far right gaze, and by 3.5 months the diplopia had completely resolved. The temporal relationship to taking this oral vaccine strongly suggests an adverse immunological response to the medication.
HISTORY: No allergies. History of hypertension, well controlled on metoprolol, losartan, and diltiazem

This case was reported by a nurse via licensee and described the occurrence of headache in a 16-year-old female patient who received Influenza vaccine Quadrivalent. Co-suspect products included Meningococcal polysaccharide groups A, C, W-135, Y conjugate vaccine and Meningitis B vaccine. On 29th October 2015, the patient received Influenza vaccine Quadrivalent, the 2nd dose of Meningococcal polysaccharide groups A, C, W-135, Y conjugate vaccine and the 1st dose of Meningitis B vaccine. In 2015, less than a month after receiving Influenza vaccine Quadrivalent and Meningococcal polysaccharide groups A, C, W-135, Y conjugate vaccine, the patient experienced headache. In 2015, the outcome of the headache was recovered/resolved. The reporter considered the headache to be related to Influenza vaccine Quadrivalent and Meningococcal polysaccharide groups A, C, W-135, Y conjugate vaccine. Additional details were provided as follows: On Thursday, 29th October 2015, the patient received 1st dose of TRUMENBA and 2nd dose of Meningococcal polysaccharide groups A, C, W-135, Y conjugate vaccine in her left arm. On the same day, the patient received Influenza vaccine Quadrivalent in her right arm. The patient then complained of experiencing a bad headache for two and half days and this was reported by patient's mother at the office. The patient's mother began some sort of medication at home for the patient's headache but she did not say what the medication was. The sales representative of other manufacturer reported that he did not have any patient details including name, medical history and other details and added that the doctor's office will be happy to share other information. The reporter mentioned that the doctor did not know but he suspect that the adverse event was related to the vaccines. The doctor also did not know if it was combination of the vaccines or a single vaccine and they were actually calling to find out that and the reporter told them to call Medical Affairs to find the information. The sales representative called back to confirm the reporter of the adverse event and nurse as confirmed as reporter who had same address and contact as of doctor and added that he did not have the email address of the doctor. Limited information was available to the sales representative. It was unknown if the reporter considered the headache to be related to TRUMENBA. This case has been linked to case US2015GSK172261, reported by the same reporter.

This case was reported by a nurse via licensee and described the occurrence of injection site swelling in a 16-year-old female patient who received Meningococcal polysaccharide groups A, C, W-135, Y conjugate vaccine. Co-suspect products included Meningitis B vaccine and HPV vaccine. On 6th November 2015, the patient received Meningococcal polysaccharide groups A, C, W-135, Y conjugate vaccine, Meningitis B vaccine and HPV vaccine. On 6th November 2015, less than a day after receiving Meningococcal polysaccharide groups A, C, W-135, Y conjugate vaccine, the patient experienced injection site swelling and feeling unwell. On 7th November 2015, the patient experienced fever. In November 2015, the patient experienced injection site erythema, injection site warmth and injection site pain. The patient was treated with ibuprofen. On 8th November 2015, the outcome of the fever was recovered/resolved. On an unknown date, the outcome of the injection site swelling, feeling unwell, injection site erythema, injection site warmth and injection site pain were unknown. The reporter considered the injection site swelling, feeling unwell, fever, injection site erythema, injection site warmth and injection site pain to be related to Meningococcal polysaccharide groups A, C, W-135, Y conjugate vaccine. Additional details were provided as follows: On 6th November 2015, the patient received Meningococcal polysaccharide groups A, C, W-135, Y conjugate vaccine and TRUMENBA in her left arm as well as Human Papillomavirus 9 valent vaccine in her right arm. On the same day, the patient complained that she had swelling at the base of her shoulder and she was feeling sick. Over the weekend, i.e. on 7th November 2015, 1 day after receiving the vaccines, the patient experienced fever on and off till 8th November 2015. The patient then received Ibuprofen. A day before time of reporting, on 9th November 2015, the patient visited the office. In November 2015, less than a week after receiving the vaccines, according to the nurse the patient's shoulder look red, hot to touch and continued to complain of sharp pain and tenderness from the shoulder to the upper neck. The sales representative of other manufacturer did not have any patient details like her medication history and other details. The doctor did not know but they suspect that all the adverse events were related to the vaccines. The doctor did not know if it was the combination of the vaccines or a single vaccine and they were actually calling to find out that and the sales representative told them to call to find the information. The reporter was called back to confirm the reporter of the adverse event and nurse was confirmed to be the reporter who had same address and contact as of doctor. The reporter did not had email address of the doctor. The reporter had limited information regarding the patient. It was unknown if the reporter considered the injection site swelling, feeling unwell, fever, injection site erythema, injection site warmth  and injection site pain to be related to TRUMENBA and Human Papillomavirus 9 valent vaccine. This case has been linked to case US2015GSK172249, reported by the same reporter.

Came as walk-in to clinic on 10/23/2015 and per exam, no confluence or warmth of red sites. Diagnosed with cellulitis s/p PNEUMOVAX.
OTHER_MEDS: Acyclovir; Aspirin; Atorvastatin calcium; Cephalexin; Ibuprofen; Insulin; NOVOLIN; Glargine; Lisinopril; Metformin; Nystatin; Omeprazole; Sildenafil citrate; Sulfacetamide
CUR_ILL: Patient presented to clinic on 10/20/2015 with complaints of possible yeast infection on his genitals (complained of erythema and pruritus around penis) and reported right eye crusty that morning. Diagnosed with folliculitis and started on cephalexin 500mg TID x5 days.
HISTORY: History of cholecystectomy; Hypogonadism; Genital herpes simplex type 2; Diabetes mellitus; Hypertension; Hyperlipidemia; NKA

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Information has been received from a physician referring to an unspecified numbers of patients of unknown age and gender. There was no information about the patients' medical history and concurrent condition. On unknown dates, these patients were vaccinated with improperly stored doses of GARDASIL 9 (lot # L020015 with expiration date on 16-AUG-2017, dose and route unknown) (incorrect product storage). No adverse effects were reported. No product quality complaint was filed. Additional information has been requested.

This spontaneous report was received from an approximately 71 year old female consumer, reporting on herself. The patient's medical history and concurrent conditions were not reported. On an unspecified date in 2011, the patient was vaccinated with unidentified pneumococcal vaccine (manufacturer unknown) 1 shot, subcutaneous, (lot# and expiration date were not reported). Concomitant therapy was not reported. The consumer wanted to know the safety of pneumococcal vaccine (manufacturer unknown), as she was concerned about side effects, she stated that on an unknown date in 2011, she experienced peripheral swelling and pain in extremity, reported as "swelling and pain in her arm". The patient did not seek for medical attention. The outcome of peripheral swelling and pain in extremity was reported as recovered on an unspecified date. This is one of two reports received from the same reporter. Additional information is not expected since there is not contact details.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: This case was reported by a consumer via call center representative and described the occurrence of autoimmune disorder in a adult male patient who received ENGERIX B adult. Co-suspect products included ENGERIX B adult and ENGERIX B adult. In August 2013, the patient received the 1st dose of ENGERIX B adult. On an unknown date, the patient received the 2nd dose of ENGERIX B adult and the 3rd dose of ENGERIC B adult. On an unknown date, an unknown time after receiving ENGERIX B adult and ENGERIX B adult and 30 days after receiving ENGERIX B adult, the patient experienced autoimmune disorder (serious criteria GSK medically significant), gastritis, vitamin B12 deficiency, hair loss, itchy skin, rheumatic disorder, knee pain, neurological disorder nos, neck pain, pain in spine, connective tissue disorder, numbness in hand, pain in hand and spasticity. On an unknown date, the outcome of the autoimmune disorder, gastritis, vitamin B12 deficiency, hair loss, itchy skin, rheumatic disorder, knee pain, neurological disorder nos, neck pain, pain in spine, connective tissue disorder, numbness in hand, pain in hand and spasticity were unknown. The reporter considered the autoimmune disorder, gastritis, vitamin B12 deficiency, hair loss and itchy skin to be almost certainly related to ENGERIX B adult. The reporter considered the autoimmune disorder, gastritis, vitamin B12 deficiency, hair loss and itchy skin to be almost certainly related to ENGERIX B adult. The reporter considered the autoimmune disorder, gastritis, vitamin B12 deficiency, rheumatic disorder, knee pain, neurological disorder nos, neck pain, pain in spine, connective tissue disorder, numbness in hand, pain in hand and spasticity to be almost certainly related to ENGERIX B adult. Additional details were received as follows: In August 2013, the patient received 1st dose of ENGERIX B adult. After receiving 1st dose of ENGERIX B adult, the patient experienced hair loss and itching of skin. After receiving the 2nd dose of ENGERIX B adult, the patient experienced worsening of the hair loss and itching of skin. On an unknown date, 1 month after receiving 3rd dose of ENGERIX B adult, the patient experienced rheumatological disorders in his left knee and neurological disorders such as pain in his neck and spinal cord (symptoms similar to cancerous mellitus). In the winter of 2015, the rheumatological disorder spread to both knees and elbows. In July 2015, it was determined that the patient might have a connective tissue disorder in these joints. On an unknown date, patient underwent blood test and it was confirmed that the patient had an autoimmune disorder in the form of a B12 deficiency and gastritis. The patient also experienced numbness, shooting pain and spasticity in his hands. The patient believed that these events were caused by the autoimmune disorder. The patient had denied permission to contact their physician.
LAB_DATA: Blood test showed that the patient had autoimmune disorder in the form of vitamin B12 deficiency and gastritis.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Mid-lower LBP radiating down both legs. Numbness and paresthesias lower legs. Gait imbalance and weakness. Neurologist diagnosed Guillain Barre. On 10/31/14, patient presented to this primary care office with complaints that are listed on the VAERS form. She consulted her neurosurgeon and was referred to a neurologist/pain specialist. Dr. evaluated patient and diagnosed Guillain Barre likely related to the influenza vaccine received in this office on 10/7/14. It was our understanding that he had completed the VAERS form along with his diagnosis. Patient subsequently transferred to a primary care physician who practices within the same network as did the neurologist and neurosurgeon. Neurologist has since relocated, but patient's current records should be available through her current primary care physician, or through the former office of the neurologist listed on the VAERS form. Prior to her transfer to her current primary care physician, this office sent her entire record accumulated during the six months she was a patient here from 8/12/14 - 1/23/15. We have not heard  from her until her recent request for completion of the VAERS form which we were happy to do.
LAB_DATA: Available through the office of neurologist
HISTORY: DJD with cervical decompression 6/14 and lumbar decompression 9/14

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Initial unsolicited report received from a nurse on 04 November 2015. This case involves a female patient (age not reported) who was vaccinated with a dose of FLUZONE INTRADERMAL QUADRIVALENT (batch number, expiry date, dose, dose in series, route and site of administration were not reported) on an unknown date. The patient's  medical history and concomitant medications were not reported. On an unspecified date in 2014, following the vaccination, the patient had developed cellulitis of upper arm. The patient's laboratory data and corrective treatment was not reported. The outcome of event was not reported. Upon medical review, the case was considered as serious due to important medical event: cellulitis of upper arm. List of documents held by sender: none.

Received injection early Aug. 2015 immediately felt pain in left arm. For approx. 1 week (L) arm felt "dead" in AM and could not lift arm in morning. Pain/stiffness/loss in mobility/hurts to sleep on left side/experiencing continued pain, stiffness, headaches/effecting neck. Treatment Pilates, PT, chiropractor, massage. Pain continues/radiating pain at injection site too.
LAB_DATA: Blood tests; X-ray done; MRI pending

SYMPTOM_TEXT: This is a spontaneous report from the non-clinical study program. A 38-year-old female contactable consumer (unknown ethnicity) reported that received PREVNAR 13, at single dose, on 09Nov2015. Relevant medical history included type 2 diabetes mellitus. Concomitant medications were unknown. The patient experienced injection site reaction with itching immediately after injection on 09Nov2015. Treatment was received (antibiotic, antihistamine). The patient recovered from the adverse event. On 09Nov2015, the patient experienced also chills, vision problem, and nausea; while on 10Nov2015, she developed fever of 101 Fahrenheit, shortness of breath and cellulitis at injection site. Hospitalization was required. Diagnosis was cellulitis. Electrocardiogram (EKG) was performed. Treatment was received for the events (antibiotic for fever, chills, ZOFRAN for nausea and clindamycin, and ROCEPHIN for cellulitis at injection site). No treatment was received for vision problem. The patient recovered from these events. On an unspecified date, in Nov2015, the consumer reported that had chest pain and she was certain she was about to die. Clinical outcome and seriousness criteria of these events were unknown. Follow-up (23Dec2015): New information reported from the same contactable consumer includes: patient details, reaction data and case seriousness changed from non-serious to serious.
LAB_DATA: Body temperature, Fever of 101 Fahrenheit; Electrocardiogram

SYMPTOM_TEXT: On 9/30, DOH was notified by an out-of-state health services company that a nurse had reused syringes for multiple persons earlier that day at an employee influenza vaccination clinic where the health services company had been contracted. The nurse contracted by the health services company brought three multiple-dose vials of vaccine that were intended for another event (and stored in her personal fridge without temp monitoring). The nurse reported using two syringes she found among her supplies to administer vaccine to 67 employees of the business. She reported wiping the syringes with alcohol and using a new needle for each of the 67 persons. Only 2 multiple dose vials of vaccine (10 doses/vial) were used for 67 adult participants. Participants were offered blood-borne pathogen testing (hep B, hep C, HIV), hepatitis B vaccine, and flu vaccine.
LAB_DATA: Collected 10/5/15, Hep B Core AB, (-); Hep B Surf. AB, (-); Hep B Surf. AG, (-); HIV Ag/Ab, (-); Hep C AB, (-)

SYMPTOM_TEXT: This is a spontaneous report from a contactable consumer reporting for her sister. A 70-years-old female patient received the first dose of PREVNAR 13, via an unspecified route of administration on her left arm in Nov2015 at 0.5 ml, single. Medical history included ongoing tardive dyskinesia. Concomitant medication included clonazepam (unknown manufacturer) 2mg three times a day and clonidine (unknown manufacturer) three times a day both for tardive dyskinesia. The patient experienced redness that spread almost down to the bend of the patient arm, her arm was swollen, hot swollen, she could not walk/she was only functioning 26% in her walk/she had non ability to walk, she was dragging her right foot all on an unspecified date in 2015. On 28Nov2015 the reporter took the patient to the doctor who gave her anti-inflammatory and Cephalexin for redness that spread almost down to the bend of the patient arm, her arm was swollen, hot swollen. A couple of days later, the patient could not walk and she was so bad that the reporter had to take her to the emergency room and mentioned that patient was bad enough that they thought maybe she had a stroke because of the way she could not walk and she was dragging her right foot. So, they did a scan and all kind of blood works and all those test came back pathologically okay and further added that they could not rule out the vaccine. The reporter mentioned that the consumer had to use the walker and mentioned that at the patient's age doctor told reporter that patient should be functioning at 86% at her age in her walking ability and the patient was only functioning 26% in her walk and that was at the time when she was in the emergency room. The reporter wanted to know if this was usual or unusual because she knew little bit of redness around the injection site was not unusual but the patient's whole arm down to the bend of her arm to elbow was very red and swollen and on that day reporter took patient to the doctor. The reporter mentioned that the redness and everything has gone away and mentioned that the patient was still experiencing the non-ability to walk, she has to use a walker. The outcome of she was dragging her right foot was unknown.
LAB_DATA: Blood test, pathologically okay; Scan, pathologically okay

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Patient received a pneumonia vaccination in the left deltoid and flu vaccination in the right deltoid in the office on 12/21/15. She returned to the clinic 12/23/15 with complaints of redness to the left deltoid, with tenderness and warmth at the site. The patient was seen, evaluated, and treated for cellulitis of the left arm. She was given instructions to monitor the site for increased redness, tenderness, or swelling that would indicate the infection was getting worse. She verbalized understanding.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: JOINT PAIN IN NON-VACCINATED ARM. JOINT PAIN IN KNEES AND ANKLES THAT IS NOT IMPROVING. NO TREATMENT.

I first began having problems in early 2013. I noticed I was becoming light headed and couldn't focus. Felt like I was going to pass out while working out. Which had never happened before. I then began feeling very fatigued. I remember sitting at work one night and all the sudden my brain felt very weird. It felt like I had a rubber band type of pressure around my head. I felt very uneasy. It lasted for approximately one week. And then my brain went into overdrive. It felt extremely weird. I couldn't breathe and it felt like I was going to pass out. My heart was racing and my brain had a very weird physical sensation to it. I had racing thoughts, and my blood felt like it was very excited. This lasted for a very long time. It never really went away. I felt very ill. All the time as well. It was a state of constant panic. The sensations moved around my body. Sometimes I would have throat symptoms, then stomach, loss of coordination, etc. I was in and out of the hospital constantly. They ran blood test after blood test, MRI, etc and said everything was normal. I had sensitivity to sound and other scary symptoms. It lasted every single day. I remember going to the hospital and could not stop shaking, it was not a seizure but almost felt like it. More like convulsions. I also dealt with severe fatigue and dizziness and at times difficulty breathing. The doctors attributed all of my symptoms to panic disorder. But the reason why I was having anxiety is because of the way I my body was feeling. I felt so extremely sick all of the time. It has been a little over two years now. My symptoms have gotten better but I still deal with stuff every day. I deal with fatigue, dizziness, sense of sickness that comes and goes. Prior to Gardasil I had never felt like this. Not once in my life. I was a happy go lucky guy that had a bright future ahead of myself. But now, my life is destroyed. I am always sick. It's not because of stress or anxiety. Its because my body feels sick all the time. It's physical. No doctor has been able to give me any answers. And its hard for me to believe this has been cause my anxiety. I lost everything because of this, my job, marriage, friends, etc. I sit in my house and deal with my symptoms. I've been on antidepressants and other drugs which never helped. I don't have any solid evidence if Gardasil caused this. But it seems like it did because a few months after I received two Gardasil shots is when my health went down the drain.

HISTORY: History of allergic reactions to tetanus toxoid and erythromycin.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: This spontaneous report has been received from an oncology nurse via social media referring to her normal healthy 18 year old female daughter. Concurrent condition and medical history was not reported. On an unknown date the patient was vaccinated with a dose of GARDASIL (dose, frequency, route and lot# not reported) by the reporter. The reporter reported that the patient was injured by this vaccine and her life had changed. The patient had a severe adverse reaction to the GARDASIL (like anaphylaxis). The patient had a debilitating illness. Within hours of the vaccine she was gasping for air and had a severe rapid heart rate before going unconscious. The patient had respiratory distress. The patient was rushed to hospital and was treated. The doctors reassured the reporter no issue with her allergies or underlying autoimmune issues. The patient was suffering with hyper postural orthostatic tachycardia syndrome (POTS), severe brain fog and fatigue. Before vaccination, the patient was a great student popular good kid not a partier. The patient had been seriously ill for five months and was unable to leave for college. The reporter said that "it was really devastated my family". At the time of reporting, the outcome of respiratory distress and unconscious was unknown, the outcome of brain fog and POTS was not recovered. The reporter knew POTS was from the vaccine of GARDASIL. The causality between other events with GARDASIL was not reported. Additional information has been requested.

Information has been received from a registered nurse referring to a 4 month old male patient with no drug reactions/allergies. The patient's medical history included respiratory syncytial virus infection. On 22-DEC-2015 the patient was vaccinated with a dose of ROTATEQ (oral, lot# L035636, expiration date: 21-MAY-2017, dose was unknown). There was no concomitant medication. On 27-DEC-2015 the patient began to have diarrhea and vomiting. On 28-DEC-2015 the patient was taken to the emergency room at an unspecified hospital and received an unspecified amount of an unspecified type of intravenous fluid and failed an oral challenge with PEDIALYTE. The patient then began to have increased vomiting and bloody diarrhea. The patient was admitted on 28-DEC-2015 to the unspecified hospital and had an ultrasound performed which found intussusception. The intussusception was reduced with an air enema. The patient was currently recovering. The causality was not reported. Additional information has been requested.

About 5 minutes after receiving the Meningococcal and HPV vaccines injected into his left arm, and the Flu vaccine administered nasally, he began having a reaction. He was standing beside me as I was sitting in a chair at the desk making his follow-up appointment, when he knelt down, put his head down, and said his ears were ringing. He then said his vision was "funny, kinda like tunnel vision". As a RN myself, I knew he could possibly be close to fainting, so I had him immediately sit in the chair beside me. I noticed he started to sweat profusely on his forehead, so the receptionist went to get him a cold, wet towel and I put it on the back of his neck. The office's Social Worker happened to be there at the front desk, so she went to get him some apple juice. I had my son put his head down and lean forward a bit, to get blood flowing to is brain. He was extremely pale so I also asked for the Medical Assistant to check his blood pressure, which was very low at 100/49 (it had been 122/78 at the beginning of his appointment around 9:15 AM). Someone brought him a package of goldfish crackers, and some water (because he had drank all of the apple juice). After about 10 minutes, he appeared much better, his color came back and the ringing in his ears along with the tunnel vision had gone away. He said "I feel much better". I took him home and checked his blood pressure, which was 138/82. I then had him eat/drink a little and rest for the remainder of the day. He was supposed to return to school after his appointment, but I thought it best to keep him home.
LAB_DATA: No, just had his BP checked
HISTORY: No Known Allergies; Diagnoses: Autism/Asperger's Syndrome; ADD/ADHD Combined Type; Adjustment Disorder with Mixed Mood (Anxiety & Depression)

Parent continues with cool compresses to affected right arm. Parent reports that redness and swelling had increased more last evening, but has "greatly improved this morning". Child even using her arm more today.

Client was asked all required and necessary questions regarding past experience with vaccinations, allergies to eggs and/or vaccine components. Client stated no negative events occurred from vaccinations, the last vaccination being a TD. This was his first flu shot he was receiving to protect his 4 week old daughter. Flulaval  (Lot: AT3CC, NCD 19515-898-11), 0.5ml, was administered IM to right deltoid at 2:25pm. Fifteen minutes following vaccination with Flulaval client reports going into bathroom, feeling lightheaded, lowering himself to the floor and then vomited. He returned to office and then reported to another nurse that he had nearly passed out when he had a vaccination in the past. Vital signs were taken, 108/76, Pulse regular 80. Client appeared pale and was sat at table, provided a drink, and asked to remain in place for monitoring. At 3:30pm this client desired to leave with wife/baby reporting he felt better. His pulse was 80 regular. At time of event the Nursing Supervisor was informed and present for entire follow up monitoring. Client was advised at time of department from office to seek medical attention for further symptoms. A follow up telephone call was made to client at 4 pm, he was attempting to eat, but reports vomiting what he had eaten. This RN instructed patient to have wife drive him home, and to lay down.

Case number PHHY2015US170668, is an initial literature case report received on 24 Dec 2015. The author in the article discussed about acute respiratory infections (ARI) in children and adolescents with acute lymphoblastic leukemia. Patients (less than or equal to 18 years) who were newly diagnosed with acute lymphoblastic leukemia (ALL) and were enrolled on an ALL treatment protocol (total therapy XVI) between Oct 2007 and May 2011 were evaluated. The total therapy XVI therapy consisted of a 6-week remission induction, 8-week consolidation and 120-week continuation phase that included two 3-week periods of more intensive chemotherapy (reinduction I and reinduction II). This report refers to an 11-month-old female patient. Past medical history and concomitant medication was not reported. The patient started therapy with cytarabine (manufacturer: not reported) for acute lymphoblastic leukemia at an unknown dose and route from an unknown date. The patient received palivizumab (manufacturer: not reported) for immunoprophylaxis at an unknown dose and route on an unknown date. The patient was vaccinated with two doses of seasonal influenza vaccine (manufacturer and batch number: not reported) on unknown dates. It was reported that 10 days before developing illness, the patient had received palivizumab. Also it was reported that on an unknown date the patient received high dose of cytarabine for reinduction II chemotherapy. The patient was presented in the hospital with a 3-day history of progressively worsening cough, nasal congestion, fever, respiratory distress with profound neutropenia and lymphopenia for which the patient was hospitalized. Initial evaluation revealed the patient had bilateral peribronchial thickening and respiratory syncytial virus (RSV) was detected on a nasopharyngeal wash specimen by polymerase chain reaction (PCR). Treatment was started with aerosolized ribavirin in addition to oxygen support and broad spectrum antibiotic therapy. However, due to progressive respiratory deterioration and increasing fever, a chest x-ray was repeated on day 5 of hospitalization which demonstrated left lower lobe consolidation pneumonia suggestive of secondary bacterial infection. The patient's treatment regimen included vancomycin, meropenem, azithromycin, voriconazole, palivizumab and aerosolized ribavirin. On day 28 of hospitalization, the patient experienced respiratory and hemodynamic failure which required mechanical ventilation and vasopressor followed by extracorporeal mechanical oxygenation support. The patient died 2 months after onset of the RSV infection. The outcome of events respiratory syncytial virus infection, respiratory failure, circulatory failure and pneumonia bacterial was fatal and outcome of events lymphopenia and neutropenia was not reported. Action taken with palivizumab and cytarabine was unknown. The author stated that despite the low incidence of viral ARI in children with ALL, the associated morbidity, mortality and delay in chemotherapy remain clinically significant. Viral lower respiratory tract infection was especially associated with high morbidity requiring intensive care-level support. The author concluded that in spite of current advances in ALL cure rates, molecular diagnostic techniques, antiviral therapies and active and passive immune prevention approaches, respiratory viral infections remain a significant burden in children with ALL.
LAB_DATA: Chest X-ray, Abnormal, Significant, Left lower lobe consolidation pneumonia suggestive of secondary bacterial infection; Polymerase chain reaction, Abnormal, Significant, Respiratory syncytial virus was detected
HISTORY: Antibiotics; Mechanical ventilation, Extracorporeal mechanical oxygenation support

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Episode of limpness requiring a call to 911. The patient was seen here on Monday (01/04/2016) for a well check and received his DPT, Prevnar, Hib and Rotateq in the morning. According to mom he went home and had no fever but was more tired than usual. On 01/06/16 during a.m. feeding, he acutely vomited a large amount and had watery diarrhea. At that time he became extremely fussy and inconsolable for about 5 min then he went limp and was unarousable but was breathing shallowly. The parents called 911 and in the meantime tried to arouse the patient he did not arouse until mom says she put some ice on his legs. There estimation of the amount of time between the vomiting and the end of the episode was about 10 min. The EMTs came and did an EKG which they state was normal but they did not take him to the hospital. He had no fever last night and had no new movements during the limp episode. He has been well since the episode without any fever, vomiting, diarrhea. He has been feeding his normal.
Pt was incorrectly administered MMRV & Varicella simultaneously. No adverse reaction appreciated.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: She was in the shower with mom and all of a sudden fell backwards.  Mom picked her up and she kept falling again.  She was then stiff, eyes rolling to the side, had whole body shaking and stiffness.  Mom took her after the shower and watched her.  She remained unresponsive for about 10 minutes.  They called EMS.  They checked her blood sugar in the ambulance and it was 130.  She was drowsy for about 1 hour after the event.    They transported her to ED where she was evaluated and felt to be fine.  She was discharged home in good condition.
LAB_DATA: EEG and neurology consult ordered by MD on 1/7/2016

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Client became near syncopal complained of "not feeling good" and "headache" 2-5 minutes post vaccination. According to mother, client had not eaten yet that morning. Gave candy cane and water and carried to exam room and layed flat on exam table. applied cold/cool compress to neck and forehead. Client recovered within 15 minutes but still complained of headache. Was able to leave ambulatory with parent. Advised parent to make sure child ate as soon as possible. Called parent 3:50pm same date child ate and had no further incident up to that time. Advised parent to follow up with physician especially if episodes recurred.

At onset: stiffness, pain, swelling, redness in arm. Next morning and for 36 hours following: fever, severe pain/stiffness/redness--which was spreading significantly--and swelling in arm. Difficulty in moving or lifting arm. Went to ER morning of Nov. 12 and diagnosed and treated for cellulitis. Kept in hospital for 36 hours for treatment and observation. At end of treatment, attending decided not cellulitis, but cellulitis-like reaction. Redness and swelling in arm remained for another full day.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Unknown time of onset. Patient called our clinic reporting she had develop redness, tenderness, and pain at injection site after the pneumonia vaccine was administered. Patient reported she was seen by her PCP who declared the reaction an allergic response to the vaccine.

PATIENT RECEIVED VACCINATIONS.  SHE THEN ASKED QUESTIONS ABOUT OTHER MEDICAL SERVICES AND NEXT APPOINTMENT.  ABOUT 5 MINUTES AFTER THE IMMUNIZATIONS SHE AROSE AND WALKED TOWARD THE WAITING ROOM.  IN THE HALLWAY, SHE WALKED INTO A WALL AND FAINTED.  CLINICIAN WAS BEHIND HER AND CAUGHT HER AND KEPT HER UPRIGHT AND WITH HER AUNTS HELP CARRIED HER TO A PADDED CHAIR AND INSTRUCTED HER TO BEND FORWARD AND PUT HER HEAD BETWEEN HER KNEES.  THE AUNT TRIED TO KEEP PATIENT'S HEAD UP.  WITH TRANSLATION AND BY CLINICIAN DEMONSTRATING, PATIENT BENT FORWARD ON THE CHAIR AND PUT HER HEAD DOWN NEAR HER KNEES.  CLINICIAN DEMONSTRATED FOR HER TO TAKE SOME DEEP BREATHS.  AFTER ABOUT 10 BREATHS CLINICIAN HELPED HER TO SIT UPRIGHT AND HAD A DRINK OF WATER BROUGHT TO HER WHICH SHE DRANK.  AFTER MONITERING HER FOR ANOTHER 5 MINUTES, CLINICIAN PUT A CHAIR NEXT TO PATIENT AND HAD HER RELATIVE SIT BY HER AND HOLD HER HAND AND WATCH HER FOR FAINTING FOR ANOTHER 15 MINUTES.  CLINICIAN CHECKED ON HER AND AFTER 15 MINUTES WITH PATIENT STATING SHE FELT FINE NOW, CLINICIAN LET HER LEAVE WITH HER RELATIVES.

8 hours after shot was given, patient said he felt like he had the flu. For the next 48 hours, patient had a high temperature and took acetaminophen and then felt fine. He reports that his temp broke, then spent 20 minutes sweating. He rested for 48 hours (bedrest) and said a rash appeared on the injection site. He said it was a raised rash (4-6 inches length, 4 inches wide around injection site). Then for 3 days, he experienced paranoia and schizophrenia (these are underlying conditions), had severe hallucinations (voices) for 1 hour. The 2nd day and 3rd day he continued to experience the voices but they diminished over time. The injection site is still slightly discolored from previous rash and has a noticeable border upon observation on 1/6/15 by pharmacy.
OTHER_MEDS: Depakote; Paroxetine; Valium; Buspar; Allergy eye drops; OTC APAP
CUR_ILL: No. Patient left the pharmacy in good condition. There were no immediate reactions at the time of administration.
HISTORY: Patient states he has Paranoia/Schizophrenia disorder; No known drug allergies

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Severe muscle pain in left arm from shoulder to elbow. Could not move left arm without lifting it with right hand because of pain. Severe pain for 4 days. Two months later I still have muscle pain and take Naproxen Sodium 220 mg so I can sleep at night.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: This case was reported by a lawyer via call center representative and described the occurrence of Guillain Barre syndrome in a female patient who received FLUARIX QUADRIVALENT (batch number 57C93, expiry date unknown). On an unknown date, the patient received FLUARIX QUADRIVALENT. On an unknown date, an unknown time after receiving FLUARIX QUADRIVALENT, the patient experienced Guillain Barre syndrome (serious criteria GSK medically significant). On an unknown date, the outcome of the Guillain Barre syndrome was unknown. It was unknown if the reporter considered the Guillain Barre syndrome to be related to FLUARIX QUADRIVALENT. Additional details were received as follows: This case was previously reported to VAERS. The patient received a dose of FLUARIX QUADRIVALENT, and experienced Guillain Barre syndrome. The reporter wanted to know whether the FLUARIX vaccine contained egg.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: This is a spontaneous report from a contactable consumer. A 72-year-old female patient received PREVNAR 13 (Lot # L93594; Expiration Date Jan2017) via an unspecified route of administration on 22Oct2015 at 0.5 ml single. Medical history included lung cancer from Mar2013 to 08Nov2014 (she had had radiation and chemo for a year and a half after diagnosis), chronic obstructive pulmonary disease (COPD) from Mar2013 and ongoing, emphysema from Mar2013 and ongoing, ongoing colitis since about 20-25 years ago and under control. The patient was on oxygen at the time of this report as she was a lung cancer survivor. Concomitant medications, all ongoing, included APRISO (caplets) at 0.375 mg once daily for colitis, clonazepam (manufacturer unknown) at 0.5 mg once daily to settle her down, SYNTHROID at 0.075 mg once daily for thyroid, SPIRIVA daily for emphysema, ADVAIR daily for emphysema, PROAIR as needed for emphysema. The patient experienced cough in Oct2015, and low grade fever, rib sore and throat sore on an unspecified date in 2015. The admission to hospital in Oct2015 was involved for cough, throat sore and rib sore. The patient had a bad cough about a week after getting PREVNAR 13. The cough got so bad she couldn't talk sometimes. She had had a bronchitis like cough that made her ribs sore and her throat sore. She also had a low grade fever with the cough. She then called her pulmonary specialist and he gave her nitrates and started her on prednisone (manufacturer unknown), both for cough. The cough had started getting to the point it was not so bad. She no longer coughed for 20 minutes at a time. No treatment was received for throat sore and rib sore. The patient was still experiencing cough, throat sore and rib sore. The outcome of low grade fever was unknown. Follow-up (30Dec2015): New information reported from a contactable consumer includes: PREVNAR 13 details (vaccination date, Lot # and Exp Date), concomitant details (ongoing), events details (seriousness, treatment and outcome).
OTHER_MEDS: APRISO; clonazepam; SYNTHROID; SPIRIVA; ADVAIR; PROAIR
HISTORY: 03/2013, 11/08/2014, Lung neoplasm malignant; 03/2013, Chronic obstructive pulmonary disease; 03/2013, Emphysema; Colitis, since about 20-25 years ago, currently under control; Radiotherapy, for lung neoplasm; Chemotherapy, for lung neoplasm; Oxygen supplementation

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Case number PHEH2014US023773, is an initial spontaneous report from a medical assistant received on 21 Nov 2014 with a follow up information from a medical assistant received on 29 Dec 2014. This report refers to an 80-years-old female patient. On 09 Mar 2012, she had swelling in the dorsum of the left hand from a rooster. She was put on antibiotic and tetanus (manufacturer and batch number: not reported). No concomitant medication was reported. On 10 Apr 2012, she had second dose of tetanus diphtheria vaccine (other manufacturer, batch number: U3769BA, expiry date: 26 Jan 2013) at a dose of 0.5 ml in the left deltoid. On 20 Apr 2012, she was contacted to notify that she required a third tetanus in Aug 2012. The patient received FLUVIRIN (batch number: G34A4, expiry date: 30 May 2015) multidose vial intramuscularly at a dose of 0.5 ml in the left arm on 23 Oct 2014. On the same day after vaccination, the patient experienced soreness in the arm and she could not lift her arm. Her blood pressure on 21 Nov 2014 was 130/80 (right arm sitting position). She performed a lab draw for complete blood count (CBC), complete lipid, T2, thyroid stimulating hormone (TSH), vitamin D, sedimentation rate and blood creatine phosphokinase MB (CPK-MB) isoenzymes. Urinalysis revealed specific gravity as 1.030 and PH as 5. Glucose, ketones, nitrate, bilirubin and urobilinogen were nil with large number of leukocytes and small amount of blood and proteins. Culture and sensitivity was done and results were not reported. She was treated with ciprofloxacin. On 05 Dec 2014, laboratory results were rechecked. Her left arm was still hurting and she had limited ROM. Her blood pressure was 140/70 (right arm sitting position). On 16 Dec 2014, she had back pain and suspected urinary tract infection. Her weight reduced to 128 pounds from 132 pounds. Her body temperature was 97.7. Blood pressure was 126/70 (left arm in sitting position). Urinalysis on 16 Dec 2014 revealed specific gravity as 1.025, pH was 6, glucose, nitrate, bilirubin and urobilinogen were nil, ketone was 5, leukocytes were Lg (large) +++, blood: 250 (hemolyzed) and protein was 300. It was reported that events got better, but she had trouble in urinating. She was treated with MACROBID 1 DF twice daily for 10 days with no refills. The final outcome of the events was reported as condition unchanged. Seriousness and causality of the events were not reported. Follow up information from a medical assistant received on 29 Dec 2014: Updated patient demographics (weight of patient), medical history, historical drug, vaccination history, dose and site, expiry date of suspect vaccination, laboratory values, events (back pain, blood pressure increased, weight decreased, trouble urination, urinary tract infection, joint range of motion decreased) and treatment.
LAB_DATA: 11/21/2014, Bilirubin urine, Normal; 12/16/2014, Bilirubin urine, Normal; 11/21/2014, Blood creatine phosphokinase MB, Unknown; 11/21/2014, Blood pressure measurement, 130/80, High; 12/05/2014, Blood pressure measurement, 140/70, High, right arm sitting position; 12/16/2014, Blood pressure measurement, 126/70, High, left arm sitting position; 11/21/2014, Blood thyroid stimulating hormone, Unknown; 11/21/2014, Blood urine, Present, Small amount; 12/16/2014 Blood urine, 250, Significant, Hemolyzed; 12/16/2014, Body temperature, 97.7, Normal; 11/21/2014, Culture urine, Unknown; 11/21/2014, Full blood count, Unknown; 11/21/2014, Glucose urine, Normal; 12/16/2014, Glucose urine, Normal; 11/21/2014, Lipids, Unknown; 11/21/2014, Nitrite urine, Nor

Case number PHEH2014US022554, is an initial spontaneous report from a pharmacist received on 10 Nov 2014 and with a combined follow up received from the pharmacist via quality assurance department (QA reference number: 343542) on 16 Dec 2014 and on 17 Dec 2014 respectively, with the follow-up information received from Quality Assurance Department (reference number: 343542) on 27 Feb 2015. This report refers to a 66 years old female patient. Historical conditions were not reported. No concomitant medication was reported. The patient was vaccinated with FLUVIRIN (batch number: 145623, expiry date: 30 Apr 2015) intramuscularly in deltoid on 08 Nov 2014. It was reported that the prefilled syringe FLUVIRIN stopper jammed and the pharmacist was only able to administer 2/3rd of the dose to the patient. No adverse event reported. It was reported that there was no damage to package and was stored in the original box until the time of use. It was also reported that there was difficulty to push plunger. The complaint was raised for FLUVIRIN batch 145623 as the stopper jammed. No sample was available for analysis. No root cause was identified during the BD investigation. The most probable root cause is that the needle, not provided by Novartis, was plugged, although no sample available for analysis it is difficult to determine the exact nature of the defect. The root cause has therefore been determined as supplier/material defective due to a blocked needle. Combined follow up received from the pharmacist via quality assurance department (QA reference number: 343542) on 16 Dec 2014 and on 17 Dec 2014 respectively: Updated expired date of vaccine, site of vaccination and reporter comment in narrative. Follow-up information received from the Quality Assurance Department (reference number: 343542) on 27 Feb 2015: Updated FLUVIRIN vaccine batch review report.

This case was reported by a consumer via call center representative and described the occurrence of injection site muscle pain in a 40-year-old male patient who received FLUARIX. In October 2015, the patient received FLUARIX. In October 2015, less than a day after receiving FLUARIX, the patient experienced injection site muscle pain and injection site discomfort. On an unknown date, the outcome of the injection site muscle pain and injection site discomfort were not recovered/not resolved. The reporter considered the injection site muscle pain and injection site discomfort to be probably related to FLUARIX. Additional details were provided as follows: This case was not previously reported to anyone. Sometime in early to mid of October 2015, the patient received the FLUARIX vaccine in his left arm at work for a routine vaccination. In October 2015, less than a day after receiving the vaccine, the patient experienced a muscular type ache in the arm at the injection site, which has continued till the time of reporting. The patient's arm hurts on moving and he had not experienced anything like this from previous flu vaccinations. In October 2015, less than a month after receiving the vaccine, the patient experienced mild discomfort until about three days before the time of reporting, when he woke up and noticed the discomfort in his arm had increased. He initially thought that he had slept on it wrong and stated that it feels like a band around his arm at the area of the injection site. However, the discomfort has continued and was only a little better at the time of reporting. The reporter wanted to be contacted as soon as possible because he was concerned that the events could progress into something worse. The patient wanted to know if the events were common to experiences for almost 3 months and inquired solution for the discomfort.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Case number PHEH2014US024249, is an initial spontaneous report received from a pharmacist on 04 Dec 2014. This report refers to a 27 year old female patient. Her medical history and concomitant medication was not reported. She was vaccinated with FLUVIRIN (batch number: 1412601) intramuscular on an unknown date. On 04 Oct 2014, 1-2 days after vaccination she experienced skin discoloration at the injection site. The patient stated that the color of the skin looked like it was bleached where the injection was given and became worse over time and the area had become bigger about the size of a dime (the area looks lighter than the rest of her skin). The pharmacist stated that she saw the patient's arm last week. The patient stated that it was about quarter size now and the patient was seen a dermatologist. Nothing was prescribed by the dermatologist and the dermatologist stated they had not seen anything like this before. Outcome of the event was unknown. Seriousness and causality assessment was not reported.

Case number PHEH2014US023971, is an initial spontaneous report received from a pharmacist on 01DEC2014, with a follow-up report received from the pharmacist on 17DEC2014, with a follow up report received from the pharmacist on 19JAN2015, with the follow-up information received from Quality Assurance Department (reference number: 343532) on 27FEB2015. This report refers to a 29  year old male patient. Historical condition and concomitant medication were not reported. His previous vaccinations (unspecified) were well tolerated. He was vaccinated with FLUVIRIN 2014/2015 (seasonal influenza vaccine, batch number: 14584P, expiration date: 30APR2015) intramuscularly in left arm on 30NOV2014 at 08:45 PM. It was reported that during administration the plunger of the FLUVIRIN pre-filled syringe (PFS) got stuck and could not be fully depressed. As a result the patient received a partial dose. No adverse event was reported following these administration errors (vaccine under dose and syringe issue). The complaint was raised for a stuck plunger for FLUVIRIN batch 14584P. No same was available for analysis. No root cause was identified during either the Catalent or BD investigation. The most probable root cause is that the needle, not provided by was plugged, although with no sample available for analysis it is difficult to determine the exact nature of the defect. THe root cause has therefore been determined as supplier/material defective due to a blocked needle. Follow up report received from the pharmacist on 17DEC2014: Updated vaccine expiration date. Follow up report received from a pharmacist on 19JAN2015: Updated vaccination details (vaccination history, site and time of vaccination). Follow-up information received from the Quality Assurance Department (reference number: 343532) on 27 FEB 2015: Updated FLUVIRIN 2014/2015 vaccine batch review report.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Deep, vague pain in Right chest, Right upper torso and Right upper back, followed by numbness tingling in these areas, sensation of tight band in the torso, weakness of the R leg. Right foot drop at 3 a.m. on 12/02/15.  Numbness tingling of both feet, and Right upper thigh.  Cold sensation to Right leg.  At 6 a.m. on 12/02/15, unable to move Right leg.  Foot drop R>L foot. Decrease tone to anal sphincter.  Some anal leakage.  Treated with high dose IV steroids for 5 days, followed by tapering steroids by mouth.  MRI of brain, C spine, T spine and L spine negative, Cat scan of chest negative, spinal tap and many lab tests have not found an etiology.  Treated from 12/2/15 to 12/9/15, then transferred to another Hospital, acute inpatient rehab from 12/9/15 to 12/18/15. Followed by Neurology at the second hospital. Repeat MRI revealed lesion at T4-T5, and T6.  Repeat spinal tap negative.  MRA of spine negative for bleed.  Now undergoing outpatient rehab.  Using a walker for short distances, and wheelchair for long distances.  Weakness in R leg continues, and neuropathic pain experienced throughout the body, R > L. Global fatigue continues.  Neuropathic pain treated with Gabapentin.
LAB_DATA: MRI with and without contrast of brain and entire spinal cord negative.  MRI positive for lesion at T4-T5, T6.  Cat Scan negative.  MRA of spine negative.  Spinal tap at both hospitals negative.  Countless lab tests all negative.
OTHER_MEDS: Magnesium Oxide 250 mg one tablet by mouth daily. Vitamin D3 4000 IU by mouth daily. (Manufacturer of Tdap was Adacel)  expiration February 3, 2018.

After that, it was 10 hours of screaming each day. My child gradually improved. However, to this day, she still has bouts of the same high-pitched screaming out of the blue, though not as often. Her other sibling did not take the vaccine and does not have this problem.

Patient came to the pharmacy to receive her Prevnar 13 vaccination. The patient reported that 3 to 4 days after the injection of Prevnar 13, the site of injection began to turn purple in color.  Subsequent to that, a redness also appeared on or around the purple coloration and has grown incrementally since it appeared.  She has reported no extraordinary pain or swelling at the site of injection. She currently does not experience any pain or swelling at the site.  She did report feeling fatigued for at least 4 days post injection and is still slightly fatigued.  She has not applied any ice or used any anti-inflammatories since the injection.  Upon being notified of the event, the pharmacist interviewed the patient over the phone to record the pertinent information as well as to encourage the patient to contact her physician with regard to this event.

A 66-year-old female patient of unspecified ethnicity received PREVNAR 13 on right arm single dose and flu shot on left arm, both via an unspecified route of administration on 13Sep2015. Medical history included erythromycin base allergy, allergy, stomach problems, diarrhea of presumed infectious origin, hypothyroidism, vitamin D deficiency, pure hypercholesterolemia, disorder of magnesium metabolism, dehydration, pernicious anemia, anxiety, depressive disorder, multiple sclerosis, migraine, essential hypertension, acute sinusitis, acute respiratory infection, chronic pancreatitis, pain in joint, ankle, and foot, thoracic radiculitis, osteoporosis, abdominal pain, abnormal glucose tolerance test. Surgical history included hysterectomy-Fibroid/Ovaries still present in 1986, tonsillectomy in 1968. Family history included father: heart disease-CABG, obesity, diagnosed with unspecified heart disease; mother, congestive heart failure, hypertensive disorder, diagnosed with hypertension, unspecified heart disease. The patient's concomitant medications included ALIGN (capsule), AMPYRA (10 mg tablet extended release) 1 tablet twice a day, Aspirin low dose 81mg tablet once a day, AVONEX Pen (30 mcg/0.5mL kit 0.5) once per week, calcium 600+D3 600-400 mg-Unit 1 tablet with food BID, magnesium oxide 400 mg tablet once a day, multivitamins capsule, Niacin (250mg tablet) 1 tablet once a day, Vitamin C 250 mg 1 tablet once a day, Vitamin D 5000 1 tablet daily except Monday and Friday take 2 tablets, ZYRTEC 10 mg once a day, Cyanocobalamin 100 mcg 1 tablet once a day, PROLIA (60 mg/ml solution) next injection on 24Oct2015, simvastatin 20mg one tablet by mouth once daily, XANAX (0.25 mg tablet) 1 tablet once a day, ARMOUR THYROID 60 mg 1 tablet once a day, lisinopril 10 mg 1 tablet BID and duloxetine HCl 60mg capsule delayed release one by mouth once daily. The patient had three siblings one brother, diagnosed with obesity and two daughters healthy. The patient experienced cellulitis, vaccination site rash, essential hypertension, the area of injection was red, over area warmth to touch, injection site became infected and inflamed on an unspecified date with outcome of unknown. The patient was treated for the cellulitis with KEFLEX capsule, 500 mg, 1 capsule, orally, TID. The outcome of the events was unknown. Mother phones public health office in the AM of 1/7/2016 to report suspected reaction to influenza vaccine. Reports child to be fatigued, fussy, not her self, axillary temperature of 102-103 degrees F, and red pinpoint at injection site. Child also had PCV13, Pediarix, and Hib that same day. None of the other sites are red or significant. Mother reports has been giving child recommended dose of acetaminophen on schedule. Encouraged hydration, cool sponge bath, and notified mother of symptoms that would be significant enough to bring child to ER. Mother reports understanding. Public Health nurse phones mother again at 4:45 PM on 1/7/2016 to check on child. Mother reports child's fever has gone down and is now at 100.8 degrees F. Child is now acting more like herself and eating and drinking normally. Mother will call with any additional questions.
LAB_DATA: None; child did not see a provider; mother treated fever and discomfort with acetaminophen; public health nurse provides additional education and support.

Fatigue, fever (measured at 102 deg), pain and redness at injection site and general pain. Took Tylenol every 4hrs for 18 hrs. When condition did not improve, went to urgent care center (01/09/2016 @4:00 pm). Received prescription for antibiotics, which resolved fever and body aches but not injection site arm pain. Arm pain worsened over next 12 hours. Went to ED on 01/10/2016 for further treatment. Diagnosed with cellulitis and treated for infection (WBC was 18) with IV antibiotics and treated for pain with morphine. Received prescription for a course of a different antibiotic.  Symptoms have largely resolved since Sunday night. Pain in arm at injection site has improved. Redness decreasing but still present.
LAB_DATA: WBC - 18 (after 18 hrs of antibiotics); K - 5.7; Temp - 102 F (after repeated treatment with Tylenol); Ultrasound done in ED. Ruled out abscess at injection site.

This case was reported by a other health professional via call center representative and described the occurrence of injection site discomfort in a 53-year-old female patient who received BOOSTRIX (batch number KJ4MS, expiry date 19th November 2017). Co-suspect products included FLUARIX QUADRIVALENT (batch number 32BH5, expiry date 30th June 2016). Concurrent medical conditions included attention deficit disorder and sulfonamide allergy (causes angioedema). Concomitant products included alprazolam, Dextroamphetamine, amiloride and hydrochlorothiazide and zolpidem. On 22nd December 2015, the patient received BOOSTRIX (intramuscular) .5 ml and FLUARIX QUADRIVALENT (intramuscular) .5 ml. In December 2015, less than a month after receiving BOOSTRIX and FLUARIX QUADRIVALENT, the patient experienced injection site discomfort (serious criteria disability), weakness (serious criteria disability), injected limb mobility decreased (serious criteria disability), grip strength decreased (serious criteria disability) and joint clicking (serious criteria disability). On an unknown date, the outcome of the injection site discomfort, weakness, injected limb mobility decreased and grip strength decreased were not recovered/not resolved and the outcome of the joint clicking was unknown. The reporter considered the injection site discomfort, weakness, injected limb mobility decreased, grip strength decreased and joint clicking to be possibly related to BOOSTRIX and FLUARIX QUADRIVALENT. Additional details were provided as follows: This case was reported by a physician assistant. On 31st December 2015, the patient visited physician assistant's office and reported that she experienced injection site discomfort at both the sites. The patient also experienced difficulty with movement, specifically described as difficulty in hooking bra along with trouble in raising her arms, range of motion issues, shoulder popping, shoulder weakness and lack of grip strength. The specific date of onset for all the events were unknown, it could be between 22nd December 2015 and 31st December 2015. The events were worsening at the time of reporting and the healthcare professional felt as though they were disabling. The reported batch number (328HS) for FLUARIX QUADRIVALENT did not exist and was updated to 32BH5 as per sales database.
OTHER_MEDS: Alprazolam; Amiloride and Hydrochlorothiazide; Dextroamphetamine; Zolpidem

This patient received a ZOSTAVAX immunization in Nov. 2009 and experienced an adverse reaction consisting primarily of significant pain in the area of injection that persistent in the area of injection for ten moths according to the patient. The patient characterized it as carrying a leaden weight. The pain slowly improved and was a non-factor until 12/20/15 when she noticed a dull aching sensation in exactly the same place with progression of a rash that resulted in a clinical diagnosis of shingles on 12/21/15. There was no blistering or itching. The distribution was the C5 dermatome of the left arm. She was treated with acyclovir and otc analgesics. The pain in now only a dull ache and doing well. I have previously reported the first part of this case to Medwatch (no, I don't have a file number).
HISTORY: The patient is healthy and active. She has a remote history of viral cardiomyopathy and a current diagnosis of osteoporosis. I am not involved in the care of this patient. I am a friend who happens to be a pharmacist.

In the middle of the night a little more than 24 hours after receiving my pneumonia vaccine, I began to feel even stronger pains than usual. When I woke up on Saturday morning (I had received my vaccine on Thursday evening), I noticed that I had a large, red, swollen mark where my vaccine had been received. In the preceding 48 hours I had increasingly higher fevers and chills (vacillating between 94 and 101), headaches, muscle aches in my neck, shoulders, and back, and I could not move my arm above my head, or put on a shirt without excruciating pain (like a 6 or 7 on a 10-point pain scale). My resting heart rate was between 80 and 110 bpm (it's typically 60-70). The swelling grew in size at about half an inch a day (both deep and wide). I could barely lift anything or bend down either. I began immediately taking Advil and Benadryl, and applying hydrocortisone cream to the site. I also rested, drank a lot of water, and applied hot and cold packs to the site. However, each day it worsened. Finally, on Monday morning I went back to the pharmacist who immunized me - and a physicians assistant at a local clinic - and both seemed alarmed, but told me to wait and keep applying the same treatments I had been doing. The physicians assistant told me to come back on Wednesday to receive antibiotics if conditions did not improve. However, as the conditions kept worsening, on Monday evening, approximately 96 hours after receiving the vaccine, I consulted with my mother (a retired RN nurse) and she recommended I try taking azitromicina (Z-pack) as this seemed particularly severe to her. I did so, and 12 hours after my first dose - as I write this - my fever has been reduced (to about 99) and more importantly the vaccination spot has not grown in size today. I will be completing the Z-pack and updating you with results.

From ED H and P: HPI Comments: 15 mos old previously healthy male who presents to the ED after a phone discussion with their PCP.  Mother, who is a PA informs us that the patient has been having episodes today, the longest of which was 45 minutes wherein he would have markedly diminished head control ability.  The patient would often sluggishly let his chin rest on his torso, and occasionally would let his head flip backwards and flop around.  During this time he would be slightly irritable.  Mom feels the R sided cervical posterior muscles have been slightly firm. Patient throughout the day has noted to be slightly more clingy. For about 10-15 minutes today the patient stopped speaking which is highly unusual for the patient.  He has had marked difficulty ambulating - normally he can run in a straight line but now walks very unsteady.  Healthy full term child otherwise. Sx started about 11 am-- improved over 12 hours. Resolved completely after about 24 hours. Past Medical History Past Surgical History Family History Review of Systems Constitutional: Negative for fever, chills, activity change, crying, irritability and fatigue. HENT: Negative for hearing loss, neck pain and neck stiffness.  Eyes: Negative for pain, discharge, redness and itching. Respiratory: Negative for cough, shortness of breath, wheezing and stridor.  Cardiovascular: Negative for chest pain, leg swelling and cyanosis. Gastrointestinal: Negative for nausea, vomiting and abdominal pain. Genitourinary: Negative for dysuria, urgency, decreased urine volume and difficulty urinating. Musculoskeletal: Positive for gait problem. Negative for joint swelling. Skin: Negative for color change, pallor and rash. Neurological: Positive for speech difficulty. Negative for seizures, weakness and headaches. Psychiatric/Behavioral: Negative for behavioral problems and agitation. Physical Exam Nursing note and vitals reviewed. Constitutional: He appears well-developed and well-nourished. He is active. No distress. HENT:  Head: Atraumatic. No signs of injury.  Right Ear: Tympanic membrane normal. Left Ear: Tympanic membrane normal.  Nose: Nose normal. No nasal discharge. Mouth/Throat: Mucous membranes are moist. Dentition is normal. No dental caries. No tonsillar exudate. Oropharynx is clear. Pharynx is normal. Eyes: Conjunctivae and EOM are normal. Pupils are equal, round, and reactive to light. Right eye exhibits no discharge. Left eye exhibits no discharge. Neck: No rigidity or adenopathy. When patient has his head slumped to the chest his R sided cervical paraspinal muscles feel more tight and protuberant. Cardiovascular: Regular rhythm, S1 normal and S2 normal.  Pulmonary/Chest: Effort normal. No nasal flaring or stridor. No respiratory distress. He has no wheezes. He has no rhonchi. He has no rales. He exhibits no retraction. Abdominal: Soft. Bowel sounds are normal. He exhibits no distension. There is no tenderness. There is no rebound and no guarding. Musculoskeletal: Normal range of motion. He exhibits no edema, no tenderness, no deformity and no signs of injury. Neurological: He is alert. He displays no atrophy. No cranial nerve deficit. He exhibits normal muscle tone. Coordination and gait abnormal.  Reflex Scores:  Patellar reflexes are 2+ on the right side and 2+ on the left side. Does not make coherent speech or verbal efforts during exam.  Will occasionally stop holding head up and keep it resting on his torso.  Gait markedly ataxic and abnormal.  Skin: Skin is warm and dry. Capillary refill takes less than 3 seconds. No petechiae, no purpura and no rash noted. He is not diaphoretic. No cyanosis. No jaundice or pallor. MEDICAL DECISION MAKING/PLANS: 15 mos old male with abrupt onset of ataxia, poor head control, loss of speech.  Findings concerning for pathology including but not limited to posterior fossa tumor, demyelinating syndrome, less likely hydrocephalus, viral process. Patient is afebrile and aside from neurological findings, otherwise well appearing,
LAB_DATA: All lab work and imaging (MRI) normal

This case, manufacturer control number 2015-0180667, received via Gilead, is a non-serious case of a patient who experienced: drop in oxygen level from 95 to 88%. The initial receipt date was 02 November 2015 and follow up information was received on 25 November 2015 (case remained non-serious). On 07 January 2016, upon medical review, the event of drop in oxygen level from 95 to 88%, was upgraded to medically significant per the safety physician. A full narrative has been generated below. This case, manufacturer control number 2015-0180667 is a report from a solicited Patient Support Program, referring to a 67 year old female patient. The other HCP reported the following event drop in oxygen level from 95 to 88% for this case. Medical history included: Current conditions: Pulmonary arterial hypertension, Asthma. Historical condition: None Reported. Historical drug: None Reported. On 19 October 2015, the patient received Ambrisentan 10 mg, QD (daily) for treatment of Primary pulmonary hypertension. Additional suspect products included: REMODULIN, ADCIRCA, TRACLEER and an Influenza vaccine. Concomitant medications included CYMBALTA, BONIVA, LIPITOR, SYMBICORT, Potassium, Furosemide, ACIPHEX, PLAVIX, SPIRIVA, Calcium + Vit D, XOPENEX, LASIX. On 26 October 2015, the patient's oxygen level dropped from 95% to 88% after switching from Bosentan to ambrisentan. The patient's physician was aware of the event and was monitoring the patient. Relevant laboratory/diagnostic tests included: 26 October 2015: Oxygen saturation: Dropped from 95 to 88%. Ambrisentan was continued. Drop in oxygen level from 95 to 88% was Serious with an outcome of unknown.
LAB_DATA: Patient's fever was detected on 20 Oct 2015: Value not reported. On 26-OCT-2015: Oxygen saturation dropped from 95 to 88%
