Case number PHEH2015US019971, is an initial spontaneous report from a consumer (patient) received on 30 Sep 2015. This report refers to 68 years old female patient. Medical history was not reported. Concomitant medications included B12 injection and other unspecified medications. The patient was bitten by a bat on the left foot. The patient was started with post exposure prophylaxis of RABAVERT (batch number: 556011A, expiry date: Feb 2018) into left arm on 25 Sep 2015. The vaccination did not hurt and it was not thick. On the same day the patient also received HRIG (batch number: unknown, other manufacturer) into left deltoid. As per the patient the HRIG was very thick and syrupy and it "liked to kill" her because it was very painful. The patient reported that it took about 15 seconds for the nurse to administer the full dose and she felt it all the way down her arm to her thumb nails and through her whole body. The patient stated that the nurse even at one point mentioned that she "thinks she did it backwards". The patient stated that the pain continued for some time and throughout the day. The arm pain was so bad that she thought that she was having a heart attack. On 26 Sep 2015 the patient began having flu-like symptoms described as aches and headache which progressively got better but still occurs. The patient stated that currently she does not feel great but is "functional". No hospitalization or ER/doctor visits were necessary. The patient went back for her next dose of RABAVERT on 28 Sep 2015 and that was when she really realized that her original dosing was incorrect. Outcome of vaccination site pain was recovered on 25 Sep 2015. Outcome of aches and headache was improving. Causality of the events of vaccination site pain, aches and headache was reported as almost certain. The outcome and causality of flu like symptoms was not reported. Seriousness criteria were not reported. Seriousness assessment of vaccination site pain was upgraded based on information in the source document.

Information has been received from a published literature article and refers to a subject of unknown gender (aged 18-28). This report refers to a 20 year old subject enrolled in a not blinded other studies. The study population comprised patients of the private, multispeciality group practice with regional centers, the clinic maintained an electronic vaccination registry for immunizations administered by clinic providers, local public health agencies, and immunization providers. No measles cases were reported in the area during the study period. Two cohorts comprising 685 subjects were enrolled during 2009-2010. Cohort 1 (113 subjects) participated in a 10-year longitudinal study at the clinic examining immunogenicity and adverse events following the second MMR II vaccine dose (hereafter, "the longitudinal study"). To achieve adequate sample size, the clinic's vaccination registry was used to recruit subjects from cohort 2 for whom receipt of 2 MMR II doses was documented but who did not participate in the longitudinal study (572 subjects). Invitation letters were mailed to both cohorts, and follow-up telephone calls were made. Additionally, cohort 1 subjects who participated in the measles cell mediated immunity (CMI) substudy during the longitudinal study were asked to participate in the current CMI substudy. Although only 16 cohort 1 subjects (14.2%) had low or undetectable MeV antibody concentrations during the longitudinal study, 93 of 113 cohort 1 subjects had low or undetectable concentrations of antibody (defined previously) to at least one of the viruses targeted by MMR II during the longitudinal study, and all cohort 2 subjects were offered a third dose of MMR II. Serum was collected from all subjects immediately before (baseline) and 1 month and 1 year after MMR3 receipt. At each visit, subjects were questioned about measles occurrence, exposures, vaccinations, and other health events. MMR vaccine was administered during the initial visit. Informed consent was obtained from all subjects. Institutional review boards of the Clinic Research Foundation and the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention approved the study. Sample size determination and exclusion criteria were previously described. The 60 participants in the longitudinal measles CMI substudy or subjects with a low or undetectable MeV antibody concentration in greater then or equal to 1 serum specimen collected during the longitudinal study were asked to participate in the current CMI substudy. However, only 34 subjects (56.7%) meeting these criteria were re-enrolled. A convenience sample from cohort 2 was used to reach the recruitment goal of 60 subjects. Laboratory testing was performed at the end of the study. Other than each subject's unique identifier code and serum collection dates, laboratories were blinded to study information. Plaque Reduction Neutralization (PRN) Testing was performed using low-passage Edmonston MeV on Vero cell monolayers, as previously described. End points were determined for all serum samples tested, and 50% neutralizing doses were calculated using the Karber method. Serial 4-fold dilutions of serum were tested in duplicate starting at 1:8 and ending at 1:8192 against virus diluted to give 35-35 plaques/well and run in parallel with the Second WHO International Standard Reference Serum (66/202). After incubating the virus-serum mixtures at 337 degrees centigrade with 5% CO2, the mixtures were transferred onto corresponding 24-well tissue culture plates containing confluent Vero monolayers; after incubating for 1 hour at 37 degrees C, the inoculum was removed, and cells were overlaid with medium containing carboxy methylcellulose and returned to the incubator for 5 days prior to staining with neutral red and plaque counting. Serum samples from individual subjects were tested in the same assay run. Titers were standardized against the WHO reference serum, with a titer of 1:8 corresponding to 8 miU/mL in this assay. Cyropreserve
LAB_DATA: Neutralising antibodies, low baseline antibody concentration; Neutralising antibodies, Negative

No information regarding the patients' medical history or concurrent conditions was provided. The objective of the study was to further elucidate the relationship between Hepatitis B virus (HBV) and diabetes. The authors examined the data derived from the Survey from years 2005-2010. Survey was a program of studies designed to assess the health and nutritional status of adults and children. The authors excluded 13902 subjects who were younger than 20 years of age at the time of screening interview and 851 subjects without body mass index (BMI) information. Then, they excluded 933 patient whom hepatitis B serology was not available and 32 subjects, whose diabetes status could not be determined. From 15316 patients included in the analysis, 4063 patients were vaccinated with doses of hepatitis B vaccine (recombinant) (manufacturer unknown) injection (dose and route of administration were not reported) on unspecified dates. The vaccination was assessed by self-report. There were no concomitant therapies reported. 91.07% of the vaccinated patients received all 3 doses of hepatitis B vaccine (recombinant) (manufacturer unknown) and the remaining patients received less than 3 doses. As the analysis was mainly based on the serological results, the authors did not separate the subjects who received all 3 doses or less than 3 doses. It was reported that the immunization status of the patients was assessed by hepatitis B surface antibody (HBsAb), hepatitis B core antibody (HBcAb) and hepatitis B surface antigen (HBsAg) testing. Positive hepatitis B immunization status was based on positive result of HBsAb test and negative results of both HBcAb and HBsAg tests. Any other combination of results was considered as negative hepatitis B immunization status. Out of 4063 patients vaccinated with hepatitis B vaccine (recombinant) (manufacturer unknown), there was no serological evidence of immunization for hepatitis B in 2476 cases. Therefore, HBV vaccination was deemed to be unsuccessful in those 2476 patients, who were reported to be vaccinated. The outcome of the events was not reported. The reporters considered the event to be related to the therapy with hepatitis B vaccine (recombinant) (manufacturer unknown). They stated that as the titer of HBV declines with time, the high vaccination failure rate in this sample set could be a time-related issue, however they could not exclude other causes from the limited information available. Additional information has been requested.
LAB_DATA: Hepatitis B surface antibody (date unspecified): negative

This case was reported by a consumer via call center representative and described the occurrence of dizziness in a 38-year-old female patient who received RABAVERT. Co-suspect products included HYPERRAB. The patient's past medical history included thyroidectomy, hepatitis (reaction to PTU (Propylthiouracil) which was given for hyperthyroidism) and septicemia. Concurrent medical conditions included premature ventricular contractions, premature atrial contraction, Graves' disease, sinusitis, renal scarring, spinal disorder (due to car accident), Meniere's disease, labyrinthitis, allergy and rabies. Concomitant products included atenolol, Levothyroxine and Potassium Supplement. On 1st December 2015, the patient received RABAVERT. On an unknown date, the patient received HYPERRAB. On 1st December 2015, immediately after receiving RABAVERT, the patient experienced dizziness, numbness of upper extremities, tinnitus, balance disorder, driving ability disturbed, hot flashes, weakness, sensation of pressure in ear, head pressure, heartbeats skipped, swelling of fingers, throat swelling and confusion. The patient was treated with ALEVE. RABAVERT was discontinued. HYPERRAB was discontinued. On 1st December 2015, the outcome of the numbness of upper extremities, throat swelling and confusion were recovered/resolved. On an unknown date, the outcome of the dizziness, tinnitus, weakness and head pressure were not recovered/not resolved and the outcome of the balance disorder was unknown and the outcome of the driving ability disturbed, sensation of pressure in ear, heartbeats skipped and swelling of fingers were recovered/resolved and the outcome of the hot flashes was recovering/resolving. It was unknown if the reporter considered the dizziness, numbness in upper extremities, tinnitus, balance disorder, driving ability disturbed, hot flashes, weakness, sensation of pressure in ear, head pressure, heartbeats skipped, swelling of fingers, throat swelling and confusion to be related to RABAVERT. Additional details were received as follows: This case was previously reported to a doctor. The patient was positive for Antinuclear antibody. The patient experienced an event to either RABAVERT vaccine or HYPERRAB when receiving them for post-exposure prophylaxis. HYPERRAB was administered in her finger, arm and buttocks. The patient was treated at the hospital because of the rabies exposure but not admitted. She could barely drive home due to her dizziness. The patient's fingers were swelled to twice their size and then resolved after 30 minutes. The patient's throat also swelled and resolved after a few days. Her arms and hands went numb and this numbness resolved after about an hour. She got dizzy and fell back onto the table. She is still experiencing tinnitus, dizziness and a feeling of being off balance. The patient believed most of the events began immediately after receiving RABAVERT and HYPERRAB. The patient underwent Nuclear magnetic resonance test and treated with ALEVE for some events for which, doses were based on her weight of 148 pounds. The patient believed that one of RABAVERT and HYPERRAB caused the reported events and was not receiving any subsequent doses.
LAB_DATA: Lab tests were done on an unknown dates. The patient may have autoimmune disease, her grandmother had lupus; Antinuclear antibody, Positive; Nuclear magnetic resonance imaging, Unknown
CUR_ILL: Ventricular extrasystoles; Basedow's disease; Sinusitis; Kidney fibrosis; Spinal disorder, due to car accident; Meniere's disease; Labyrinthitis; Hypersensitivity; Supraventricular extrasystoles; Rabies
HISTORY: 2013, Thyroidectomy; Hepatitis, reaction to PTU (Propylthiouracil) which was given for hypothyroidism; Sepsis

Initial unsolicited pregnancy report received from literature on 19 November 2015. This case is linked to 2015SA192129 (same literature). Abstract: Given the illness and deaths caused by respiratory syncytial virus (RSV) infection during the first year of life, preventing infant RSV infections through maternal vaccination is intriguing. However, little is known about the extent and maternal effects of RSV infection during pregnancy. We describe 3 cases of maternal RSV infection diagnosed at a center during winter 2014. Case-patient 1 (26 years old, week 33 of gestation) received a diagnosis of RSV infection and required mechanical ventilation. Case-patient 2 (27 years old, week 34 of gestation) received a diagnosis of infection with influenza A (H1N1) virus and RSV and required mechanical ventilation. Case-patient 3 (21 years old, week 32 of gestation) received a diagnosis of group A streptococcus pharyngitis and RSV infection and was monitored as an outpatient. Clarifying the effects of maternal RSV infection could yield valuable insights into potential maternal and fetal benefits of an effective RSV vaccination program. This case involves a 27-year-old female patient who was vaccinated with influenza vaccine (batch number, site of administration were not reported) on unspecified date during pregnancy. It was reported that at the time of vaccination the patient was 34 weeks and day 4 pregnant (gravida), LMP not reported. Hence, it was a case of drug exposure during pregnancy. The patient's prior obstetric history was notable for a spontaneous abortion at 8 weeks, and her medical history was notable for childhood asthma and smoking one half to 1 pack of cigarettes per day before pregnancy and concomitant medications were not reported. On an unspecified date after vaccination, patient presented worsening cough, congestion, fevers, chills, dyspnea, fetal hydrocephalus consistent with aqueductal stenosis (which was diagnosed during the second trimester), on hospitalization day 2 experienced membranes ruptured, breech presentation, congestion, pulmonary edema, cough was productive for green sputum, evoked concern for pneumonia, exacerbation of asthma, hypotension, tachycardia. Later the patient was diagnosed with group influenza A (H1N1) virus and RSV (Respiratory syncytial virus infection). On an unknown date patient was hospitalized. Laboratory investigations included rapid influenza test which was negative, leukocyte count was 21*109 cells/L, chest radiograph showed a nonspecific opacity in the right middle lobe, oxygen saturation was stable (94 percent to 94 percent on room air) and nasopharyngeal aspirate was sent to be tested by viral respiratory PCR panel (eSensor; GenMarkDx) which panel was positive for influenza A (H1N1) virus and RSV respectively. The patient was treated with a 5-day course of prednisone and albuterol for exacerbation of asthma, azithromycin for cough and fever and ceftriaxone, vancomycin, azithromycin, and oseltamivir for secondary bacterial infection. At the time of this report patient was not recovered from the events and on an unknown date, patient recovered from pulmonary edema. On hospitalization day 3 at 39 weeks of gestation, the patient underwent a classical cesarean delivery of a (birth weight 3,640 grams) female infant with Apgar scores of 3 and 7 at 1 and 5 minutes. Patient remained intubated and was transported to the surgical ICU after delivery. She was extubated without difficulty within an hour of ICU admission and transferred to the postpartum unit 12 hours after delivery. On hospitalization day 10, patient was discharged (discharge date not reported) home with percentage of oxygen saturation in the mid-90s on room air. Upon internal review, the case was assessed as serious due to important medical events fetal hydrocephalus consistent with aqueductal stenosis and membranes ruptured. Documents held by sender: none.
LAB_DATA: Chest radiograph showed a nonspecific opacity in the right middle lobe, which evoked concern for pneumonia; PCR, Unknown, Positive; Leucocyte count, Unknown, 21*10E9
CUR_ILL: Asthma; Cigarette smoker, smoking one half to 1 pack of cigarettes per day before pregnancy
HISTORY: Spontaneous abortion, spontaneous abortion at 8 weeks

The arm continued to itch and be sore. On Tuesday, December 29th I went to urgent care. The doctor said she hadn't seen my type of reaction before. She told me I could do the following: take prednisone, put  Benadryl cream or hydrocortisone ointment on the area, and I could also take Benadryl. She also gave me a prescription for an antibiotic, which I could fill, if my arm became infected. I went back to pharmacy to show the pharmacist. She said she hadn't seen my type of reaction. She told me to take Benadryl. I took Benadryl for a few days.  My arm slowly started to get better. That took a couple of weeks. Also, I had shingles ten years ago.

On 28-DEC-2015, the patient had tympanic tubes placed in her ears bilaterally. On 30-DEC-2015, patient was doing good with the tubes placed in her ears bilaterally (recovering) and she seems fine after the extra dose of varicella vaccine. The nurse stated that, as 30-DEC-2015, the patient no longer takes of VARIVAX (Merck) and it was unknown if she continues to take PROQUAD (Merck). Causality assessment was not provided. Additional information has been requested.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: This case was reported by a consumer via call center representative and described the occurrence of device use error in a 76-year-old female patient who received ADVAIR Diskus unknown (batch number 5ZP1526, expiry date February 2017) for drug use for unknown indication. On 19th November 2015, the patient started ADVAIR Diskus (unknown) 100/50 ug at an unknown dose at unknown dosing. On 20th November 2015, 1 day after starting ADVAIR Diskus, the patient experienced device use error. The action taken with ADVAIR Diskus was unknown. On an unknown date, the outcome of the device use error was unknown. Additional details included that the patient reported that she used ADVAIR for the first time "yesterday". It went well and she reported that she felt it really helped her. On the morning of reporting, when she tried to use the device, she could not get it open. She was trying to flip the light purple section up to expose the mouthpiece. She had forgotten that the inhaler needed to be twisted to expose the mouthpiece. She was attempting to use the product incorrectly. Follow up received by a consumer on 4th December 2015 and 17th December 2015: The reporter stated that, the patient started the course with ADVAIR Diskus on 18th November 2015, and she might have received a dose of Flu vaccine on the same day. On 1st December 2015, 13 days after receiving the Flu vaccine and ADVAIR Diskus, the patient experienced cold symptoms, sniffles and cough. The patient thought that, she had flu. The patient visited back the doctor, who confirmed that she did not have the flu, but sinusitis instead. She was prescribed an antibiotic. In November 2015, less than a month after vaccination and after receiving ADVAIR Diskus, the patient never felt good (malaise), at some point felt nauseated, wheezing and trouble breathing while walking. On 17th December 2015, the patient was still wheezing. It was unknown if the events were related to Flu vaccination. The patient would talk to her doctor about taking ADVAIR twice per day instead of once per day, which has let to an underdose. The patient denied permission to contact her physician.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: This case was reported by a other health professional via call center representative and described the occurrence of fever in a 61-year-old female patient who received FLUARIX QUADRIVALENT. On 21st October 2015, the patient received FLUARIX QUADRIVALENT .5 ml. In October 2015, less than a month after receiving FLUARIX QUADRIVALENT, the patient experienced platelet count low, spleen enlarged, liver enlargement, hemoglobin decreased, elevated liver enzymes and hepatitis C test positive. On 23 October 2015, the patient experienced fever. The patient was treated with TYLENOL. On an unknown date, the outcome of the fever, platelet count low, spleen enlarged, liver enlargement, hemoglobin decreased, elevated liver enzymes and hepatitis C test positive were recovering/resolving. The reporter considered the fever, platelet count low, spleen enlarged, hemoglobin decreased, elevated liver enzymes and hepatitis C test positive to be probably related to FLUARIX QUADRIVALENT. It as unknown if the reporter considered the liver enlargement to be related to FLUARIX QUADRIVALENT. Additional details provided were as follows: This case was reported by a certified medical assistant, who herself was the patient. This case was previously reported to a doctor. On 21st October 2015, at 05:00, the patient received a dose of FLUARIX QUADRIVALENT vaccine in left deltoid. On 23rd October 2015, at 05:00, 2 days after vaccination, the patient developed fever (101.5 degrees F). The patient took TYLENOL. The fever continued for the next 3 days. On 27th October 2015, at 12:00 noon, the fever was (102.5 degrees F). There were no other external symptoms present. On the same day, the patient had blood drawn and underwent laboratory tests, which showed high liver functions and an abnormal blood count. All inflammatory marker tests showed elevations. The patient tested positive for Hepatitis C. On 28th October 2015, the patient underwent an abdominal ultrasound, which revealed an enlarged liver and spleen. The spleen was dangerously enlarged. Over the next week, the patient underwent blood work, which showed liver functions kept rising. The Serum glutamic oxaloacetic transaminase (SGOT), serum glutamic pyruvic transaminase (SGPT) and Alkaline Phosphatase tests showed elevations. Two days later test result came back, that the patient did not have Hepatitis C. Her hemoglobin levels decreased from 12.5 to 9.7. The patient stressed that, she was normally a very healthy individual. The patient again underwent a 2nd set of Hepatitis C titers 2 weeks after the initial lab work and results came back negative. The patient added that a month before the vaccination, she had routine blood work done and all levels were good. The patient was scheduled for laboratory work in coming week and said she would have results that she can share when she receives the follow up form.
LAB_DATA: 11/2015, Alanine aminotransferase, Elevated; 11/2015, Aspartate aminotransferase, Elevated; 11/2015, Blood alkaline phosphatase, Elevated; 10/27/2015, Blood count, Abnormal; 09/2015, Blood test, All levels good; 10/23/2015, Body temperature, 101.5 degree F; 10/27/2015, Body temperature, 102.5 degree F; 10/2015, Haemoglobin, 9.7; 10/2015, Haemoglobin, 12.5; 10/27/2015, Hepatitis C virus test, Positive; 11/2015, Hepatitis C virus test, Negative; 11/2015, Hepatitis C virus test, Negative; 10/27/2015, Inflammatory marker test, Elevated; 10/27/2015, Liver function test, High; 10/28/2015, Ultrasound abdomen, Enlarged liver and spleen

Once I picked up the prescription for the eye issue, I had him one dose which was around 4pm. After that he played like normal. But then he strated showing red rashes on his face. I called children's nurse hotline at 8:50PM. The told me to take him to the urgent care. The doctor on site that night said she believed that he was allergic to the prescribed medication for his eye and/or the flu nasal spray. She told me to stop giving him the medication for his eye issue and to monitor his rash. The rash she believed to be hives that was due to the allergic reaction. Once we got back home his hives had spread to his eyes, the back of his neck, legs, arms, and he complained that his feet hurt and they were red and swollen. I gave him a cool bath and put some Aveeno lotion on him. But then he woke up the next morning (1/16/2016) with his left eyelid swollen shut, although the hives went away. He complained about his eyes hurting, his tummy, and his back hurting. I have him a dose of ibuprofen around 5pm. It is now 10:50pm on 1/16/2016 that my son is covered again in hives.
LAB_DATA: The doctors have done nothing but tell me to wait and give him cold baths.
CUR_ILL: I took my son to the doctors because he had woke up in the morning and his right eyelid was swollen shut. Once we were there they attempted to treat my son by prescribing him a pink antibiotic. The doctor also asked if we wanted to get the flu shot. I didn't want to make my son cry so I turned down the shot, but then he recommended the nasal spray. I wasn't really interested in the spray, but the doctor insisted.
HISTORY: My son has seasonal allergies that usually show up in the summer.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Hello, I am a provider. I have a case to present.  I am having a hard time calling the 800 # as I only have personal cell phone access out in the field. Here is the case: 25 yo male received anthrax vaccine in left deltoid x 48 hours ago. This was his third shot in the series and he was on schedule. No previous reactions. At 24 hours, he had erythema, warmth and edema at 13cm x 9cm at the local injection side. He also c/o pruritus. No lymphadenopathy, no numbness and tingling, no systemic symptoms. He was diagnosed with a local severe reaction and treated with ibuprofen and Benadryl.  Today, at 48 hours, the swelling and erythema has gotten worse; at 19cm x 17cm; still no other symptoms. Pruritus resolved with Benadryl. The rash does not extend beyond the elbow. Vitals are normal minus a slightly elevated pulse (but his normal sits in the 90s/100s). Pulse is 107; afebrile.  He is following up every 24 hours.
LAB_DATA: He will continue to follow up. Diagnosed as a local severe reaction. I also contacted the vaccine agency for further advice.
OTHER_MEDS: Adderall 20mg extended release; pseudophed 60mg q 6 hours; guafenison DM 600/30mg q 12 hours

This case was reported in a literature article and described the occurrence of anaphylaxis in a 56-year-old male subject who received Flu seasonal TIV Dresden. This case refers to patient 9 in the literature article. Concurrent medical conditions included penicillin allergy. On an unknown date, 1 hr after receiving Flu seasonal TIV Dresden and dTpa vaccine, the subject developed anaphylaxis. Serious criteria included GSK medically significant and life threatening. Additional event(s) included angioedema with serious criteria of GSK medically significant, shortness of breath, vomiting and fatigue. The subject was treated with antihistamine. The outcome of anaphylaxis was recovered/resolved. The outcome(s) of the additional event(s) included angioedema (recovered/resolved), shortness of breath (recovered/resolved), vomiting (recovered/resolved) and fatigue (recovered/resolved). The investigator considered that there was a reasonable possibility that the anaphylaxis, angioedema, shortness of breath, vomiting and fatigue may have been caused by Flu seasonal TIV Dresden and dTpa vaccine. Additional information was provided: This case was reported in a literature article and it described the occurrence of vaccine-triggered anaphylaxis in a 56-year-old male patient who had received an unspecified Tdap (manufacturer unknown) and an unspecified trivalent influenza vaccine (manufacturer unknown). The patient was a male. The subject's medical history included atopic disease with amoxicillin allergy. No further information on the patient's concurrent medical conditions, medical or family history, or concomitant medication was provided. On an unspecified date, between the 1st of January 2009 and the 31st of December 2011, the patient received an unspecified dose of an unspecified Tdap and an unspecified trivalent influenza vaccine (dosages unknown; administration routes and sites unspecified; batch numbers not provided). On an unspecified date, within 60 minutes and less than 90 minutes after the vaccination, the patient developed angioedema, shortness of breath, vomiting and fatigue. This was classified as anaphylaxis by the family practice doctor. According to the authors the case was considered as Brighton level 2 and setting of initial evaluation was clinic. The patient was treated by oral antihistamine. At the time of reporting the outcome of the events was recovered. This event was classified as vaccine related according to the authors. The authors concluded that "Anaphylaxis after vaccination is rare in all age groups. Despite its rarity, anaphylaxis is a potentially life-threatening medical emergency that vaccine providers need to be prepared to treat. This case is 1 of the 28 valid cases reported in the same literature article.

This case was reported in a literature article and described the occurrence of anaphylaxis in a 12-year-old female subject who received Flu seasonal TIV Dresden. This case refers to patient 5 in the literature article. Concurrent medical conditions included penicillin allergy. On an unknown date, 1 day after receiving Flu seasonal TIV Dresden, the subject developed anaphylaxis. Serious criteria included hospitalization, GSK medically significant and life threatening. Additional event(s) included generalized urticaria, pruritus, rash, syncope and lump feeling in throat. The subject was treated with epinephrine, antihistamine, H2 blocker, steroid (unspecified), antiemetic and lidocaine cream. The outcome of anaphylaxis was recovered/resolved. The outcome(s) of the additional event(s) included generalized urticaria (recovered/resolved), pruritus (recovered/resolved), rash (recovered/resolved), syncope (recovered/resolved) and lump feeling in throat (unknown). The investigator considered that there was a reasonable possibility that the anaphylaxis, generalized urticaria, pruritus, rash, syncope and lump feeling in throat may have been caused by Flu seasonal TIV Dresden. This retrospective pregnancy case was reported in a literature article and described the occurrence of congenital hydrocele in a neonate. The mother received Tdap vaccine. The pregnancy resulted in a live neonate with a congenital anomaly. The neonate was diagnosed with congenital hydrocele. Serious criteria included GSK medically significant and congenital anomaly. Additional event(s) included maternal vaccine exposure. The outcome of congenital hydrocele was unknown. The outcome(s) of the additional event(s) included maternal vaccine exposure (unknown). The investigator considered that there was a reasonable possibility that the congenital hydrocele may have been caused by Tdap vaccine. Additional information was provided: This retrospective pregnancy case was reported in a literature article and it described the occurrence of a congenital hydrocele in a newborn infant of unspecified gender whose mother had received an unspecified Tdap vaccine (manufacturer unknown) during pregnancy. The patient's mother was between 12 and 45 years of age at the time of the vaccination. No information regarding her obstetric history, last menstrual period, expected date of delivery or gestation at the time of vaccination was provided apart from the authors commenting that women who had the vaccine within 3 days of the delivery had been excluded from the analysis. No further information on the patient's concurrent medical conditions, medical and family history or concomitant medication was provided. On an unspecified date between 1 May 2005 and 31 August 2009, the patient's mother received a dose of an unspecified Tdap vaccine (dosage unknown; administration route and site unspecified; batch number not provided). Please note that this vaccine was not recommended for pregnant women at the time and that the authors commented that the reason why most of the women had received it during this period was either for prophylaxis for open wounds/trauma or during routine health supervision. On an unspecified date between 1 May 2005 and 31 August 2009, at least 3 days after the vaccination, the patient was delivered (unspecified method) and subsequently diagnosed with a congenital hydrocele that was classified using code 7786 from the International Classification of Diseases (Ninth Revision). This was a serious case as the patient was diagnosed with a congenital anomaly. Treatment was unknown. Outcome was unknown at the time of reporting; although the authors mentioned that no infant had an International Classification of Diseases diagnosis code for pertussis in the year following birth. The authors did not comment on any causal relationship between the vaccine and this event. The authors concluded that "the results of this retrospective study are encouraging. However, prospective trials will be required to confirm the safety and efficacy of Tdap during pregnancy. Both trials have recruited small cohorts of healthy women in the third trimester (30-32 weeks) of pregnancy to further evaluate safety and immunogenicity of Tdap vaccine immunization in the mother and Tdap in the infant. The new universal recommendations for immunization of pregnant women during second and third trimester will afford further opportunity to collect prospective safety data on large cohorts of women". This case is 1 of the 5 valid cases reported in the same literature article.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: This retrospective pregnancy case was reported in a literature article and described the occurrence of ventricular septal defect in a neonate. The mother received Tdap vaccine. The pregnancy resulted in a live neonate with a congenital anomaly. The neonate was diagnosed with ventricular septal defect. Serious criteria included GSK medically significant and congenital anomaly. Additional event(s) included maternal vaccine exposure. The outcome of ventricular septal defect was unknown. The outcome(s) of the additional event(s) included maternal vaccine exposure (unknown). The investigator considered that there was a reasonable possibility that the ventricular septal defect may have been caused by Tdap vaccine. Additional information was provided: This retrospective pregnancy case was reported in a literature article and it described the occurrence of a ventricular septal defect in a newborn infant of unspecified gender whose mother had received an unspecified Tdap vaccine (manufacturer unknown) during pregnancy. The patient's mother was between 12 and 45 years of age at the time of the vaccination. No information regarding her obstetric history, last menstrual period, expected date of delivery or gestation at the time of vaccination was provided apart from the authors commenting that women who had the vaccine within 3 days of the delivery had been excluded from the analysis. No further information on the patient's concurrent medical conditions, medical and family history or concomitant medication was provided. On an unspecified date between 1 May 2005 and 31 August 2009, the patient's mother received a dose of an unspecified Tdap vaccine (dosage unknown; administration route and site unspecified; batch number not provided). Please note that this vaccine was not recommended for pregnant women at the time and that the authors commented that the reason why most of the women had received it during this period was either for prophylaxis for open wounds/trauma or during routine health supervision. On an unspecified date between 1 May 2005 and 31 August 2009, at least 3 days after the vaccination, the patient was delivered (unspecified method) and subsequently diagnosed with a ventricular septal defect that was classified using code 7454 from the International Classification of Diseases (Ninth Revision). This was a serious case as the patient was diagnosed with a congenital anomaly. Treatment was unknown. Outcome was unknown at the time of reporting; although the authors mentioned that no infant had an International Classification of Diseases diagnosis code for pertussis in the year following birth. The authors did not comment on any causal relationship between the vaccine and this event. The authors concluded that "the results of this retrospective study are encouraging. However, prospective trials will be required to confirm the safety and efficacy of Tdap vaccine during pregnancy. Two trials are underway to assess the safety of Tdap vaccine during pregnancy. Both trials have recruited small cohorts of healthy women in the third trimester (30-32 weeks) of pregnancy to further evaluate safety and immunogenicity of Tdap vaccine immunization in the mother and Tdap in the infant. The new universal recommendations for immunization of pregnant women during second and third trimester will afford further opportunity to collect prospective safety data on large cohorts of women". This case is 1 of the 5 valid cases reported in the same literature article.

Information received on 08JAN2016 from a pharmaceutical company and consumer. A 38 year old male experienced Multiple Sclerosis following the administration of BioThrax (anthrax vaccine adsorbed) and other vaccines. On 05JAN2016, the consumer contacted a pharmaceutical company to report that he was John Cunningham virus (JCV) positive. At that time, he was on therapy with Aubagio (teriflunomide) and Tysabri (natalizumab) for multiple sclerosis. The natalizumab was stopped for the JCV. During contact with the consumer, he revealed to the pharmaceutical company that he felt that there was a link between the multiple sclerosis and anthrax immunization that he received. The pharmaceutical company forwarded the report to the vaccine manufacturer. On 08JAN2016, contact was made with the consumer by the vaccine manufacturer. The consumer reported that he had received the vaccine in two intervals for a total of 5 doses. He recalled that in 1999 his dosage of anthrax vaccine was halted due to the agency "putting the vaccine on hold for side effects". Immunization was resumed in approximately 2000-2001. The consumer also recalled that he was immunized for smallpox, Japanese encephalitis, and other vaccines on or around that time.  In 2010, he was diagnosed with multiple sclerosis. The consumer stated that he felt the multiple sclerosis was related to anthrax vaccine because he had no prior hereditary issues or autoimmune disorders, and he was told that his multiple sclerosis could be due to "environmental triggers" which he attributed to the anthrax vaccine. The consumer denied concurrent medication and medical history at the time of event. Reporter's Comments: Report forwarded from Sanofi, which contains information regarding an Anthrax vaccine. Sender's Comments: This is a consumer report from an individual who received multiple vaccines including BioThrax, smallpox and Japanese encephalitis vaccine and reports his subsequent diagnosis of multiple sclerosis. While the consumer believes the diagnosis of multiple sclerosis is related to BioThrax vaccination, multiple vaccines were administered on or about the same time.  In the absence of adequate medical assessment of the reported events a causality association is deemed not assessable.
HISTORY: Patient denies medical history or hereditary issues

Diagnosed with Guillain-Barre on 1/12/15 then treated with 5 days of IVIG.  Symptoms improved then began regressing 2/16/15.  Retreated with 5 days of IVIG with minimal improvement.  Relapsed further and diagnosis was changed to Chronic Inflammatory Demyelinating Polyneuropathy on 3/12/15.  Started on high dose steroids.  Symptoms continued to relapse until I could no longer move my arms or walk.  Last walked on 3/20/15.  Admitted for hypertension urgency on 3/24/16 for 2 days.  Had a syncopal episode on 3/29/15 requiring a visit to the ED.  By 4/3/15, I had lost 20 pounds due to swallowing difficulty and was no longer moving anything but my head.  Admitted for 5 days of plasmapheresis.  Discharged on 4/10/15 able to move my arms and walk.  Treatment to prevent relapses continue with IVIG every 3 weeks and methotrexate weekly.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: This spontaneous report was received from a consumer (patient's mother) referring to an 11 year old female patient. The patient was healthy. No information regarding concomitant medications was provided. On 02-SEP-2010, the patient was vaccinated with the first dose of GARDASIL (exact dose, frequency, route, lot # and expiration date were not provided). In approximately September 2010 (reported as soon, after receiving the vaccine), the patient started experiencing the earliest symptoms including fatigue not relieved by sleep, sleeping a lot over 12 hours a day and even more in the weekends, constant (24/7) headaches and migraines not responding to the pain relievers, stabbing 24/7 bilateral ear pain, abdominal pain, nausea, all over joint pain. The patient did not know what was wrong, but she did not feel good. The patient also did not look good had constant dark circles under her eyes, her skin color was ashen and she appeared listless. She missed days at school and other activities (dance and cheerleading). The patient visited pediatrician repeatedly and other specialists including neurologist; ear, nose and throat specialists (ENT's), gastrointestinal specialists (GI), Obstetrician Gynecologist (OBGYN) and made several visits to the emergency room. The patient also received many blood tests, computerized axial tomography (CAT) scans and magnetic resonance imaging (MRI). The patient was prescribed unspecified medications to alleviate her symptoms but it only made her to feel worse. The pediatrician suggested that patient's illness might be psychosomatic and recommended to visit a psychologist. On an unspecified date in October 2010, the patient was tested for the Lime disease. The first, as well as second and third round of testing, was negative. In April 2011, the patient's fatigue and pain was all consuming so she could no longer go to school or participate in dance or cheerleading. The patient's symptoms included hyperacusis, constant sore throat, visual disturbances, light sensitivity, cognitive issues such as memory and severe comprehension problems, random numbness and tingling, weird "bug crawling" skin sensations, generalized weakness throughout her body (it was difficult for her to sit in the shower to bathe), dizziness, feeling close to passing out just standing, fainting and heart palpitations (onset dates for the events were not reported). She stayed in her bedroom shielding herself from the everyday living. It was hard to take her out of the house even for a doctor's appointment. In May (year unspecified), the patient was tested for a tick-borne diseases. She was highly positive for Bartonella henselae and Mycoplasma pneumonia (blazing infection with Mycoplasma pneumonia). The testing also showed that the patient's immune system was struggling and was impaired. Western Blot for Lyme disease was negative. The results were interpreted by the doctors as just an exposure to Bartonella and a classic Bartonella rash the patient developed as stretch marks. In approximately April 2011 (reported as after a month of receiving that injection) the patient's health deteriorated rapidly. The patient's back had caused them severe pain that had them lying in bed for a year. The patient was diagnosed with degenerative disc disease and had been given epidurals to stop the pain. On an unknown date, reported as soon after the patient's back, the patient got extremely fatigued to the point the patient was falling asleep everywhere and had to get at least 2 naps a day in order to function. On an unknown date, the patient got severely depressed and had suffered from panic attacks. Then on an unknown date, the patient got diagnosed with hypothyroidism and had been seeing a doctor for that for months so they could get the patient's dose right. Even though the dose was right and the patient's thyroid had gained a balanced hormone level, the patient was still having the symptoms. Then on an unknown date, both the patient's wrists disabled themselves and the patient couldn't use the patient's wrists. They found ganglion cysts growing in the joints of the patient wrists but they were not big enough to be causing that amount of pain. Then on an unknown date, the patient went to get cysts aspirated and had steroids injected into the patient's wrists. Still then the patient's wrist were in agony. Then after a few weeks of getting patient's wrists done, the patient's body started to get terrible chronic pain everywhere. The patient had always suffered from chronic pain and the patient thought it was nothing just the patient's muscles aching because maybe the patient did something to them playing football. On an unknown date (reported as just before Christmas of unknown year), the patient was diagnosed with fibromyalgia and had to be put into a rehabilitation hospital for nearly a month to try learn to deal with the chronic pain. At the time of the report, the patient was getting tested for Lyme's disease and Bartonella, as the patient was showing the rash all over the patient's body (onset date unspecified) and had been told all the time that it was just stretch marks. The patient started to take low dose naltrexone. It was meant to have done wondered for Lyme's disease and fibromyalgia. The patient stated that the GARDASIL destroyed the patient's health. The outcome of the events of fibromyalgia, ganglion cysts, degenerative disc disease, health deterioration, falling asleep everywhere, depression, panic attacks, stretch marks, hypothyroidism, pain in wrists and extremely fatigue was unknown. This was the very first 2 year child this season I was going to vaccinate for Flu shot. The whole family of 4 came in for the vaccines. I knew the other 3 would have the same vaccine and were given the FLUARIX. The father got the shot first, then the little girl but she was very scared, screaming in the room. While approaching her with the shot, she waved her hand in front of the needle and got a scratch kind of injury. This distracted me. I meant to check the dose of the shot before I gave the younger child but by this time he was confused and getting scared. So the parents and I decided we would give the shot to him quickly and then proceed with the documentation to prevent further agitation. I reached for FLUVIRIN, checked the expiry date, but forgot to check the age range, and gave the child the vaccine. I did not realize my mistake until the next day when I usually go over my day and think of how I could improve myself. I called my manager and let her know and following her advice called the CDC first to know of what to do. I did not have access to the child's information until 3 days and my manager was aware of that. By the next day I received feedback from CDC that no exaggerated adverse events were anticipated and no further vaccination was recommended. The next day I informed the mother who was very upset and angry as to why she wasn't informed as soon as I came to know. I explained to her that it was because my manager told me that the policy was to first check with CDC what their advice was and inform VAERS which was also done by myself. I think this happened partly because the label only had the age information in small letter unlike FLUARIX which had that in big fonts to draw my attention to it. Also last year we did have FLUZONE MDV which looks like FLUVIRIN, so that was in my mind.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: At 3:30 I noticed a small rash on my daughter's chin and a small rash with hives on her forehead.  I spoke with the nurse at our PCP's office to report the symptoms and requested the doctor be notified and a non-urgent call back to discuss.  I gave my daughter 25 mg Benadryl around 4:00.  Between 3:30 and 4:30, the rash and hives were more spotty on other areas of the face so I administered another dose of 25 mg Benadryl (the highest recommended dosage for her age).  I then phoned my PCP again because the rash had spread to the eye area and looked swollen. I spoke with my PCP who recommended we go to the ER for further assessment.  However, as I prepared the family to leave for the ER, around 4:45, the rash appeared to be diminishing.  I did not feel an ER visit was indicated. My daughter had no difficulty breathing nor any other symptoms during the event.  By 5:30, the rash had decreased at least 90% and was 100% cleared by 6:30.
HISTORY: Mild grass, tree pollen and mold allergies

This literature study report was received from a literature article. The author stated that newly diagnosed HIV-positive individuals are 35 to 100-fold more susceptible to Streptococcus pneumoniae infection compared to non-infected individuals. Therefore, the PPV23 has previously been recommended, though efficacy and effectiveness of vaccination remains controversial. Early severe B cell dysfunction is a central feature of HIV infection. The specific nature of the immune cells involved in the production of protective antigen-specific antibodies in HIV-positive individuals remains to be elucidated. There were three goals in this study. First, to elucidate the immunogenic response to PPV23 in newly diagnosed HIV-positive individuals. Second, to evaluate whether is it potentially beneficial to provide 6-12 months of HAART (highly active anti-retroviral therapy) to suppress viral load and potentially improve immune function before PPV23 vaccination in newly diagnosed HIV-positive individuals with CD4<200. Third, to elucidate the phenotypic distribution of PPS-selected B cells in newly diagnosed HIV-positive individuals, dependent on CD4 count, compared to HIV-negative individuals. This case concerns a patient of unknown age and gender. Forty-three pneumococcal polysaccharide vaccine naïve newly diagnosed HIV-positive volunteers participated in the open observational study. HIV-positive individuals were stratified according to CD4 counts. Twenty two HIV-negative volunteers participated in this study. All volunteers were vaccinated with PNEUMOVAX 23 (dose and route of administration not provided) on day 0. All adverse events to vaccination were recorded. On an unknown date one patient experienced Arthus-type reaction. The outcome of the events was unknown. The authors considered the event to be related to PNEUMOVAX 23. The authors concluded that despite CD4-dependent pneumococcal polysaccharide-specific deficiencies in newly diagnosed HIV-positive patients, vaccination was beneficial based on opsonophagocytic titers for all newly diagnosed HIV-positive groups. In HIV-positive patients with CD4<200 cells/microL, 6-12 months of HAART did not improve opsonophagocytic titers or antibody concentrations. Based on these findings, immunization with the PNEUMOVAX 23 should not be delayed in newly diagnosed HIV-positive patients with CD4<200 cells/microL. Additional information has been requested.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Pt fainted after injection, low blood pressure, low heart rate. After 15-20 min. pt was fine. When the patient received his HVP vaccination, he had an episode of syncope with brief LOC, fell and hit face with no lac/mild contusion only and vital signs following syncope showed bradycardia to the 50s and hypotension to 80s over 40s which persisted for approximately 8 minutes. Hypotension/bradycardia initially concerning for vaccination triggered anaphylaxis but given its full resolution within 10 minutes and blood pressures and heart rate increasing back to the 130s over 80s with heart rate in the 80s to 90s with none of the other accompanying features of anaphylaxis including no wheezing, no lip swelling, no vomiting, no rashes, we think that this is much more likely to be vasovagal reaction to a painful stimulus like vaccination. Patient had a similar episode of syncope when he had a splinter removal several years prior, lending further evidence to this being a vasovagal reaction. However given family concern we are happy to refer to Allergy and Immunology to see whether a skin test for HPV vaccine produces any local reaction that would indicate patient has an allergy to this important vaccine. We recommended that the patient have any painful procedures like splinter removal, vaccination, suturing etc done sitting or lying down in a safe position where syncope will not produce a fall. Patient sustain only mild left facial contusion which was improved by applying ice pack for 15 minutes. Neurologic exam following the incident indicated that the patient was articulate speaking in full sentences with normal facial neurologic exam, normal strength, normal gait and otherwise reassuring overall appearance following the episode.

This medically confirmed literature report (initial receipt 13-Oct-2015) concerns a 26 year old male patient. The patient has no relevant past medical history. On an unknown date, the patient received an influenza virus vaccine (brand and batch number unspecified) to the left arm. The patient did not experience any paresthesias or other symptoms at the time of injection. Sixteen hours post influenza vaccination, the patient developed progressively worsening weakness over his distal left upper extremity.  After 20 hours, the patient experienced total weakness in the affected muscles.  The patient had no past medical history and the review of the systems were unremarkable. Physical examination revealed a small puncture wound in the posterolateral portion of his mid-arm approximately 2.5cm distal to the clinically identifiable deltoid tuberosity.  A motor exam demonstrated 4/5 strength in his triceps, 2/5 strength in his brachioradialis and 0/5 strength in wrist extension, finger extension and thumb extension.  No sensory abnormalities were noted. The remainder of the neurovascular exam was within normal limits. The day after influenza vaccination, the patient presented to an outpatient hand surgery clinic complaining of left wrist drop.  An magnetic resonance (MR) imaging of the left upper arm on the day after the injection revealed edema along the course of the radial nerve without focal collection. The nerve itself was not grossly enlarged or damaged. Ultrasound (US) examination of the patient's arm on the day after the injection demonstrated swelling of the radial nerve in the distal third of the arm starting approximately 3 cm distal to the injection site. At the center of the swollen segment, an adhesive band was identified as compressing the nerve, likely an incidental finding since the band was not near the site of injection and the nerve was found to be swollen proximally and distally to the band. Given the results of the MR and the US, the impression was that the nerve palsy was secondary to a demyelinating process related to inflammation around the nerve and not to axonal damage. A splint and a steroid taper were prescribed. Surgery in the form of neurolysis was offered but the patient elected non-operative management. One month following the injury, nerve conduction studies and electromyography (EMG) demonstrated severe left radial neuropathy with total motor axonal loss with sparing of the radial sensory nerve.  A follow-up ultrasound obtained at the same time revealed progression of the swelling of the radial nerve in both size and craniocaudal extent, with involvement of the posterior interosseous nerve and signs of supinator atrophy.  This swelling and atrophy were absent on the ultrasound taken the day after injury. Approximately six months post initial injury, the patient reported progressive improvement in motor symptoms beginning with the brachioradialis and progressive inferiorly to his thumb extensor over time. At one year post injury, physical examination revealed 5/5 strength in his triceps, 5/5 strength in his brachioradialis and 4/5 strength in wrist extension, finger extension and thumb extension.  The patient reported minimal functional limitations and was able to resume work in full. The outcome was recovered. Reporter's Comments: Reporter's comments: Imaging suggests that the nerve injury was caused by injection of the vaccination into the nerve sheath and not the nerve itself.  It is hypothesised that the injectate dissected down the tissue planes along the radial nerve causing a chemical neuritis, leading to axonal ischemia and axon loss.  The progressive development of symptoms over time supports the notion that the palsy developed secondary to an inflammatory process.  Alternatively, it is also possible that the total axonal loss was due to ischemia from a chemical neuritis induced by the injectate.  The authors believe the reason for the palsy was inappropriate location of the injection. Sender'

This medically confirmed literature report (initial receipt 13-Oct-2015) concerns a 34 year old female patient. On an unknown date, the patient received an intramuscular injection of an influenza virus vaccine (brand and batch number unspecified) to the deltoid region of the arm. The patient reported 3 weeks of right shoulder pain beginning during vaccination. She noted more pain than usual during the vaccination and stabbing.  The patient experienced 9/10 shoulder pain with internal/external rotation and adduction afterwards. She denied any instability, clicking/popping, neurologic symptoms in the arm/hand, or any new repetitive activity. On examination, active internal/external rotation, resisted external rotation both with the shoulder adducted and abducted to 90 degrees and shoulder impingement maneuvers were painful. Reflexes, strength, sensation and AC joint provacative maneuvers were normal. Traumatic infraspinatus and/or teres minor tendon injury was suspected as the cause of her pain. She received little benefit from oral anti-inflammatory medication, a diagnostic subacromial lidocaine injection and 6 physical therapy sessions. T2-weighted shoulder MRI demonstrated infraspinatus tendinosis without frank tear. She was scheduled to undergo ultrasound-guided diagnostic lidocaine injection of the infraspinatus tendon sheath. The outcome was not reported. Reporter's Comments: Reporter's comments: In this case, improper injection proximally into the deltoid muscle resulted in infraspinatus tendon injury. Iatrogenic infraspinatus tendon injury during deltoid IM injection is a rare complication. Sender's Comments: Company comments: Seriousness: Serious. Medically significant. Listedness: Unlisted. Brand of vaccine not specified. Assessment according to the CCSI for CSL Inactivated Influenza Virus Vaccine and the Afluria Product Information, all events are unlisted, except for injection site pain. Causality: Possible. Increased pain was noted upon vaccine injection, with eventual development of impairment of shoulder joint motion and pain in the following 3 weeks. This patient developed signs and symptoms consistent with previously described cases of shoulder injury related to vaccine administration (SIRVA) in literature. SIRVA is due to an inflammatory effect from vaccine administration into the subdeltoid bursa. This inflammatory response may be due either to the antigenic or nonantigenic components of the vaccine. Given the temporal relationship and the plausible mechanism, this case is assessed as possibly related.

3 immunizations on 11-12-15. Resulted in high fever and an emergency room visit on 11-14-15. Blood test results showed white cells in blood. PA and hospital report indicates it could be from the injections. Three (3) different vaccines administered, Thursday, November 12, 2015 about Noon-12:15 pm, by pharmacist. I reported this reaction by phone to my doctor (Monday, Nov. 16?), and also a pharmacist (19th) where the injections were given. All 3 injections were given in my left arm/shoulder because I have a torn rotator cuff on my right shoulder. The shingles vaccine was injected under the skin under my upper left arm and the other 2 injections were given in the top of my shoulder. As I expected, my left shoulder was tender to the touch, and very uncomfortable when leaning on it, similar to past immunizations. I report this because I had to go to the emergency room where white cells/bacteria were found in my blood. I was told there by the PA that it was probably introduced with the vaccine injections. On 11-12-15 I had a 10:00 a.m. appointment with Dr. at the local clinic, not for an illness, but for a routine, 6-month appointment, including a routine blood test. Everything was fine. I talked with Dr. about having the 3 immunizations that another clinic had recommended when I was there Sept. 22. Both Dr. and a pharmacist said it shouldn't be a problem to have all three vaccines at one time. She contacted the local pharmacy. I had no problems until about 10:50 p.m. that night. I felt intermittent chills, and after I was in bed, my body started sharking uncontrollably for what seemed like a long time, until I went to sleep. The next morning, Friday the 13th, my temperature was about 100 degrees, and it kept rising all day. I had a terrible headache, couldn't think clearly and was unable to get out of bed except to go to the bathroom. I did not eat all day, and when I drank a glass of skim milk, it curdled and came up. After I woke up Saturday, all morning my temperature varied from 102 degrees to over 103 degrees (103.7 degrees at one point). In mid-morning when my daughter phoned, she told me that I wasn't making any sense. When I didn't recognize my husband, he took me over to our local hospital to the emergency room. They did a variety of tests (blood test, urine, chest x-ray), and the PA said there were white cells in my blood, saying it was bacteria most likely.
LAB_DATA: Emergency room - 11-14-2015. Blood test, Chest X-ray, urine test. Found white cells in blood.
OTHER_MEDS: Omeprazole; Losartan; Spironolactone; Pravastatin; TRAVATAN Z; Acetaminophen; Aspirin
CUR_ILL: None - I had a 6 mo appt. that A.M.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: I had time to walk to designated area, sit down and then I was being dragged out by someone on each arm and taken to emergency room. I do not remember anything at all (3 days) until I woke up with one of my coworkers praying at the side of my bed. I have spoke to many Reps, private doctors and ENT's concerning this matter. I feel as if no one can answer my questions or they do not want to get involved. I have been looking for answers for several years. I am submitting this information to you: As I do not know that it ever has been. I was told they almost killed me by attending nurses. I feel it should be know to you. I have refused any other vaccinations since age 17. At my current age and health I feel I should receive common vaccinations but fear them. To ask at my current age 54 should I fear necessary vaccinations. To ask if this situation could be responsible for or contribute to my consistent sinus, ear, teeth and heart problems I have developed since then. Any information or guidance you may provide in this situation would be greatly appreciated.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: On 01/20/16, medical assisitant (MA) administered TDAP (Adacel) Lot#: U5214AA Exp: 12/04/17, Manuf: SP; and HPV9 (Gardasil) Lot#: L016429 Exp: 08/09/17 Manuf: Merck & Co vaccines. Per MA pt tolerated well immediately after administration. Pt's mother was present and stated the same. As stated by MA, she left the room door slightly open to be able to observe the pt, and mother was present with pt. Less than 4 minutes later we heard a loud scream, which was the pt's mother asking for help. MA was the first to respond, since she was near the room, and per MA she noted the pt was on the floor faced up, and called code blue.  All medical and nursing staff responded to code blue. Front desk called 911. Pt was conscious, A&O x 4, vitals WNL, and pt denied any pain. A bump on her forehead was noted and slight blood on her gums. Pt's mother stated she was looking at her phone, and from her peripheral vision she saw the pt falling down from exam table/bed. Pt's mother stated the pt fell face forward, and she turned her over. Pt's mother stated the pt gets nervous around blood and needles. She stated the pt has" fainted at school when learning about blood cells, and gets pale after receiving vaccines." Notified pt's mom to always alert anyone giving her vaccines or drawing her blood of this. About 8 min later the paramedics arrived and assessed pt. Per pt's mother, she was given the option to have the ambulance take pt to hospital, or stay and take pt to the ER within the pt's insurance network. Pt's mother stated she would stay and take the pt to ER herself. Paramedics left and pt was continuously assessed by Dr., and myself for about 45 min. Vitals were WNL, pt was A&O x 4, and still denied any pain 0/10. Pt was provided with water and cold compresses. At 4:06 pm Dr. okayed pt to go. Discharge instructions provided to pt's mother, by Dr.   Pt's mother verbalized understanding.
HISTORY: After event, mother notified us that the patient gets pale when she receives vaccines, and has fainted at school when she was learning about blood.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: This case was reported in a literature article and described the occurrence of neurological symptom in a adult male patient who received Hepatitis B vaccine. On an unknown date, the patient received the 1st dose of Hepatitis B vaccine. On an unknown date, less than a week after receiving Hepatitis B vaccine, the patient experienced neurological symptom (serious criteria disability). On an unknown date, the outcome of the neurological symptom was unknown. The reporter considered the neurological symptom to be related to Hepatitis B vaccine. Additional information was provided: This case was reported in a literature article and it described the occurrence of unspecified neurological symptoms in a male patient of unspecified age who had received an unspecified Hepatitis B vaccine (manufacturer unknown). The patient had a Doctorate of Philosophy and worked in a medical school laboratory at the time of the event. He and his sister received the vaccine on the same day, but the author commented that she was fine. No further information on the patient's concurrent medical conditions, medical and family history or concomitant medication was provided. On an unspecified date, the patient received the first dose of an unspecified Hepatitis B vaccine. Dosage was unknown; administration route and site were not unspecified; batch number was not provided. On an unspecified date, within a week of the administration of the vaccine, the patient was experiencing unspecified neurological symptoms and required a wheelchair. No further clinical details or diagnosis were provided by the author. The event was considered as disabling as it required the use of a wheelchair. Treatment was unknown. Outcome was unspecified at the time of reporting. The author believed that the vaccine could have caused the event. The author concluded that "the controversy regarding vaccines will continue, with no resolution in the foreseeable future due to the divergence of views. Are vaccines a success story? Yes, they are as can be attested to with polio, smallpox, rubella diphtheria, measles and tetanus. How do we address the concerns mentioned earlier? One answer is to give one vaccine at a time, which would help identify which vaccine gives an adverse reaction. Added to this, waiting 90 days between live virus vaccines is prudent. Last, never give a vaccine to a child who has been ill in the last 2 weeks, or if there are signs of inflammation, such as active allergies, wheezing, or eczema". The article corresponding to this case is not available for submission due to copyright restrictions.

This spontaneous consumer report (initial receipt 13-Jan-2016) concerns a 60 year old female patient. The patient has a medical history of GERD, globus hystericus (reported as 'globus'), diphenhydramine allergy, amoxicillin allergy, hypertension and anxiety.  Prior vaccination with Afluria in Nov or Dec 2014 resulted in hives.  This reaction was treated with diphenhydramine to which she experienced an allergic reaction and was placed on prednisone which helped.  Concomitant medications include nebivolol, ranitidine, alprazolam, pravastatin and vitamin D. On 01-Dec-2015 at 09:30, the patient received Afluria (influenza virus vaccine polyvalent, batch number: unknown) via the intramuscular route for protection against the influenza virus.  On 01-Dec-2015 following influenza vaccination, the patient experienced headache and tiredness.  At 02:00 on 02-Dec-2015, the patient experienced pain in the back of her right leg and tingling on the right side of her face (also reported as occurring on 01-Dec-2015).  That same day, she went into work, was sent to ER/OT and was admitted to hospital for a mild/moderate allergic reaction.  Treatment comprised of prednisone (20 mg for 4 days) due to her diphenhydramine (Benadryl) allergy.  On 05-Dec-2015, the patient woke up with heart palpitations and called the ER doctor who told her to stop prednisone and take her alprazolam (Xanax).  On 11-Dec-2015, the patient returned to the ER for a rash that developed and palpitations.  The patient described it as hives.  The ER discharge noted acute anxiety and told her to continue alprazolam (Xanax).  She was also provided with an epinephrine which she has not used.  The patient stated white marks on her face and stomach but rash comes and goes.  The patient stated headache, tingling in face and leg pain comes and goes as well. The outcome was reported as not recovered. Linked case: 2016057877 (same patient). Reporter's Comments: n/a. Sender's Comments: Company comments: Seriousness criterion/criteria: Hospitalisation. Listedness: Unlisted. Assessment according to the CCSI for CSL Inactivated Influenza Virus Vaccine and the Afluria Product Information, acute anxiety and all other events are unlisted. Paraesthesia, headache rash and hives are listed. Causality: Possible. Time to onset is same day for headache and tiredness and next day for other events and 11 day for rash. Although the patient was treated with antihistamine and steroids events are not typical of type 1 allergic reaction. The case did not meet Brighton collaboration group definition for anaphylaxis due to delayed onset for rash and urticaria. History of anxiety was a probable factor in causation of palpitation rash and or events. Causality with vaccination cannot be completely excluded due to temporal association.
OTHER_MEDS: Bystolic; Ranitidine; Xanax;  PRAVASTATIN; VITAMIN D
HISTORY: Hypertension; GERD; Globus; Benadryl allergy; Amoxicillin allergy; Anxiety

This literature marketed report as received from the authors of the published article, refers to a 17 year old patient of unknown gender with reactive airway disease. At the age of 12 months (in approximately 1999) and at the age of 4 years (in approximately 2002), the patient was vaccinated with doses of MMR vaccine (manufacturer unknown) (lot number, expiry date, dose, site and route of administration not reported). On 14-FEB-2015, the patient was seen in an emergency department for evaluation of reactive airway disease. In the waiting room at the same time there were two children who were later confirmed to have measles. The patient began a 5-day course of prednisone (manufacturer unknown) (oral tablet, 50 mg daily); however, symptoms continued, and the patient returned to the emergency department the next day (on 15-FEB-2015) and received methylprednisolone (125 mg, intravenously). The patient had documented receipt of two doses of MMR vaccine (manufacturer unknown), therefore was not administered with intramuscular immune globulin after they had been identified as a person exposed to the two children with measles. On 02-MAR-2015, 16 days after the first emergency department visit, the patient was hospitalized for vomiting and dehydration. The patient was also found to be febrile and to have a confluent popular rash that began on the face and spread to trunk and extremities and had small vesicular oral lesions. Measles was confirmed by laboratory testing (on an unknown day in approximately March 2015), and the patient received supportive treatment with anti-emetics and intravenous fluids. The author concluded that it was not known whether the patient developed immunity to measles in response to the administered doses of MMR vaccine (manufacturer unknown) or whether the patient had an unrecognized immunocompromising condition, but the recent steroid use might have weakened the patient's immune response and rendered the patient susceptible to wild measles strain. The outcome of the measles and vaccination failure was not reported. The author considered vaccination failure and measles to be related to MMR vaccine (manufacturer unknown), since the patient had received 2 doses of MMR vaccine (manufacturer unknown) and did not meet criteria for being severely immunocompromised, but did develop measles after being exposed in the setting of a hospital emergency department to patients with laboratory-confirmed measles. Additional information has been requested.

This case was reported by a physician via other manufacturer and described the occurrence of seizure in a 16-year-old female patient who received MENVEO (batch number M14072, expiry date 30th November 2015). Co-suspect products included Meningococcal B vaccine (batch number L13514, expiry date 31st July 2016). Previously administered products included MENVEO (1st dose received on 3rd June 2011). On 4th September 2015, the patient received the 2nd dose of MENVEO (intramuscular) .5 ml and the 1st dose of Meningococcal B vaccine (intramuscular) .5 ml. On 4th September 2015, less than a day after receiving MENVEO, the patient experienced seizure (serious criteria hospitalization and GSK medically significant), photosensitivity, walking difficulty and extra dose administered. Meningococcal B vaccine was discontinued. On an unknown date, the outcome of the seizure, photosensitivity and walking difficulty were recovering/resolving and the outcome of the extra dose administered was unknown. It was unknown if the reporter considered the seizure, photosensitivity and walking difficulty to be related to MENVEO. Additional details were provided as follows: The reporter preferred not to answer the medical history details of the patient. On 3rd June 2011, the patient received the 1st dose of MENVEO vaccine. On 4th September 2015, at 12.26 pm, the patient again received a dose of MENVEO vaccine in the left deltoid, which led to an extra dose administered. On the same day, the patient also received TRUMENBA in the right deltoid intramuscularly. The patient experienced psycho seizures, photosensitivity and she was not able to walk very well at the time of reporting. On 5th September 2015 to 15th September 2015, the patient was hospitalized for duration of 10 days. The patient did not experience any illness at the time of vaccination. The patient was not deceased. The reporter considered the psycho seizure, photosensitivity and walking difficulty to be related to TRUMENBA.
HISTORY: 06/03/2011, MENVEO, Prophylaxis, 1st dose received on 3rd June 2011

SYMPTOM_TEXT: My father had interstitial lung disease for about 10 years at this point. He never received a flu shot before, & in the fall of 2009, there was widespread worry about swine flu.  Because of his condition, he decided it was prudent to get a flu shot.  Within 2 weeks of receiving the flu shot, his lung capacity went from 88% to 44% and he ended up in the hospital on oxygen.  His condition continued to downgrade until 1-1-10 when he received a lung transplant (he was in such need at that time, he was placed on the list and called for a transplant in less than a week).   I believe he would have died within a week or two of that time.  He did eventually die on May 16, 2010 due to complications of the lung transplant.

This spontaneous report derives from an internet website where a currently approximately 20-year-old patient of unknown gender reported on themself. Soon after the vaccination, the patient faced with the extreme fatigue and was slacking in school. The patient was in the swim team but was unable to participate or go to practices. They would come home from school, fall asleep at 15 o'clock and would sleep through the next day. The patient would feel sick and unable to get up. The patient was taken to the diagnostic center where a diagnosis of dysautonomia was made, and then was sent to the neurologist for help with their frequent migraines. There was no preventative medication for the migraines and the only thing they could do was take TYLENOL with codeine and go asleep. Sleep helped take away the migraine. The patient did not recover from the adverse events ("still tired a lot and get migraines"), but they learned to deal with them. The reporter did not assess the relationship between the suspect drug and the events (the patient's doctors rejected the idea that the vaccine was associated with the events, they blamed it on dysautonomia and said that tiredness could be due to the fact that the patient was playing all of the sports and then suddenly stopped). Her symptoms began with dizziness in the morning. The following week she developed an ongoing headache with extreme fatigue.  I took her back and forth to the doctor told she needed more sleep and water. Her next symptom was shortness of breath and fast heart rate with increased headache. We were sent to a cardiologist who then sent us to a neurologist. After ER visits, rheumatology, endocrinology, and two more neurologist we still had no help for my daughter who cannot think anymore her muscle and joint pain is crippling and her head hurts so bad she cannot open her eyes.  The symptoms just keep coming we are not faced with gastric issues adding to her pain. We received a POTS diagnosis from two neurologists. My daughter cannot play, read, think, stand up, take a shower.  She just lays and cries all day every day.  My straight A student is now a shell of who she used to be.  In pain and not able to care for her basic needs.
LAB_DATA: MRI of the Brain and Spine, Echo and EKG on her heart. CAT scan of head. EEG and sweat test with Blood work and a Tilt Table Test to confirm POTS syndrome.
CUR_ILL: No know illness at the time of vaccine.
HISTORY: No medical conditions existed.  Healthy and athletic.
