SYMPTOM_TEXT: This spontaneous report was received from Licensed Practical Nurse (L.P.N) concerning a 37 year old female patient with asthma, migraines and hypothyroidism. The patient's medical history included vomiting, as a reaction to PERCOCET, and back pain. On 25-JAN-2016, the patient was vaccinated with a 0.5 mL dose of PNEUMOVAX 23, (Lot # reported as L036437) intramuscularly. Concomitant therapies included SYNTHROID, FIORICET, EVOCLIN, DILAUDID, DEPO-PROVERA and PROVENTIL HFA. On 25-JAN-2016, the nurse reported that the patient experienced pain at the left deltoid injection site, initially, and the pain at the injection site had increased to a pain level 6; and when the injection site was touched the pain increased to a pain level of 8 (on a pain scale of 1-10). On 25-JAN-2016, the annual blood tests of CBC, CMP, THS and lipid panel were performed (results not provided). On the same date, the result for the aspartate aminotransferase (AST) was slightly elevated. My daughter woke up and said she did not feel good. Her forehead was hot. We took her temperature and she had a fever. While leaving the bathroom, she fainted. She had a fever and stayed home the next day.
Began to hyperventilate.

Within 5 minutes of receiving her 2nd round of Gardasil, my daughter passed out on the exam table. Since that time she has been having periodic fainting spells, including but not limited to severe stomach pains. Her recent spells have developed muscle twitches in her arms. And we took her to the emergency room. Now going to doctors looking for answers. An ultrasound showed nothing in the abdomen but the EEG is showing signs of seizures.  My daughter was the picture of health before receiving this vaccine and her doctor is convinced it is not from the HPV vaccine.  I am convinced it is. I'm praying I have not caused my daughter to be sterile! Please let me know if any remedies have yet been found!
OTHER_MEDS: Iron. Would need to contact doctor for manufacturer of HPV vaccine.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Arm started hurting and I could not raise it. It kept hurting for days. My arm has continued to hurt and I have trouble raising it.

Based upon the follow-up information received on 27-Jan-2016, influenza vaccine was added as a company suspect drug. Initial information regarding this clinically sponsored solicited case was received on 13-Jan-2016 from the patient via the Patient Support Program. This case concerns an approximately 64 year old adult male patient who had mild flu symptoms few days after and was feeling tired and felt funny, unspecified time after receiving Praluent and influenza vaccine. No past drugs or concurrent conditions were reported. On 30-Dec-2015, the patient commenced therapy with subcutaneous alirocumab injection at the dose of 75 mg every other week (lot/batch number and expiry date unspecified) for Hyperlipidemia, unspecified delivered via alirocumab prefilled pen. On an unknown date, the patient started treatment with influenza vaccine (dose, form, route, frequency, lot/batch number and expiry date: unknown). On an unknown date, the patient reported having mild flu symptoms that started a few days after last injection. An unspecified time later, since an unknown date, the patient has been feeling tired lately. Reportedly, today was the first day he was starting to feel a little bit better. He has had sinus trouble for over 20 years and it was not unusual for him to have flu symptoms. Upon follow-up it was reported the patient felt funny after the 1st injection. I was seen by Dr's assistant. She did an x-ray of my shoulder and said the findings were normal, and gave me a cortisone injection in my shoulder, prescribed Piroxicam 20 mg, and sent me to clinic for therapy. I was diagnosed with a frozen shoulder from acute trauma. I have more movement now in my arm, but I still cannot take off or put on clothes over my head without pain...and I have limited arm movement, going from left to right and it can only be done with pain. I am trying to exercise my arm more...but, the nights I go to exercise class, the next morning I have more pain in my shoulder than normal. I am an avid golfer....and I am wondering now, if I will event be able to play again.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: My wife is the subject of this report. I am writing this as an eyewitness to the events following her "over 65" flu vaccine administered at approximately noon on Wednesday, November 4, 2015. My wife does have several health issues (mechanical heart valve, arthritis, pre-diabetic, lactose intolerant and high blood pressure which is under control and is on a number of medications which are attached for section 17). Prior to the administration of this vaccine, she was able to walk and was not feeling ill. I am not a doctor, so I will be using laymen's terms to describe this decline in her health during the afternoon and evening of November 4, 2015. Patient had a noon appointment for an "over 65" flu shot on November 4, 2015. She was able to walk into the office and upon the completion of her visit was able to walk back to the car. Shortly thereafter, we returned to our home and she was able to walk into our house with no problem. During the afternoon, she progressively felt worse. Her first symptom was heartburn about an hour after her shot. Approximately 2-3 hours later she had intense chills to the point of having to have three blankets over her but still had chills, more heartburn, wheezing, difficulty breathing and irregular/rapid heartbeat. Toward the evening, she attempted to get up to go to the bathroom. She was so weak, especially in her lower back and legs, that she could not get up even with the assistance of a walker. Finally, with my help, we got her up to hold on to the walker. This was extremely difficult for her to do. I held on to her as she made her way to the bathroom which took a very long time. She got in the bathroom and on the toilet but again it was a very slow process. After being on the toilet, I attempted many times to help her stand up so she could hold on to the walker. As I was helping her get up, I was holding her under her arms but I just could not hold to her. With my hands under her arms, patient slowly dropped to the bathroom floor. At that point, I decided that we needed to call 911. At approximately 8:45 p.m., the ambulance arrived. They were able to get patient up and onto a chair and then onto a stretcher. Her blood pressure was elevated and she was having an irregular heartbeat, a rapid heartbeat and extreme weakness. When she arrived at the hospital, she did have a fever of 100.4 degrees as well as rapid heartbeat, irregular heartbeat and elevated blood pressure. Patient remained at hospital for seven days. Following patient's release from the hospital, she was admitted for rehabilitation. She spent three weeks there and received physical and occupational therapy. Following her stay, she received home care services for several weeks. She received, primarily, physical therapy to assist her with her balance and to strengthen her legs so she could walk without a walker. Currently, patient improved enough so that she no longer needs to use her walker unless her arthritis becomes a problem. Please note, that in the hospital/doctor's report, staff indicates that they did not feel that this was caused by the "over 65" flu shot; however, we were both told by the admitting physician that he would not rule out that this could have been a reaction to the flu shot. Patient was told by at least one other hospitalist that what happened was a reaction to the flu shot which she received. She also has been told by two additional physicians that she is to no longer get the "over 65" vaccine. As an eye-witness to this event, I am positive that the vaccine did create this severe reaction. Patient is now very concerned regarding receiving any flu shot in the future. This needs to be addressed by someone at VAERS or the CDC. We would also like to know if the flu strains were different from any other year. We would appreciate a call from someone at your office to explain this.
OTHER_MEDS: Digoxin; Gabapentin; Lansoprazole; Metoprolol succinate; Warfarin sodium; Lactase; Ramipril; Spironolactone; Prednisone; LASIX
HISTORY: Atrial fibrillation; GERD; Congestive heart failure with unknown ejection fraction; Mitral valve replacement; Chronic back pain related to spinal nerve pain, with bilateral neuropathy and arthritis; Hypertension; Adenoidectomy; Tonsillectomy

She is a cancer survivor. The patient previously took sulfur and experienced drug hypersensitivity. Concomitant medications included THYROLAR 0.115 (units unspecified) every day for thyroid disorder, ongoing, and oral Aspirin ongoing. On an unspecified date, in Aug2015, the patient experienced pain in extremity. On an unspecified date, in Sep2015, the patient experienced sleep difficult, petechiae, memory disturbance and pain aggravated. On an unspecified date, in Oct2015, the patient experienced atrial fibrillation, potassium decreased, light headedness, and nausea. She never had diagnosis of heart problems before. She was not admitted to the hospital. Activities of daily living impaired (it was difficult for her to get up and down off toilet) on an unspecified date in Nov2015. On an unspecified date, she experienced also joint pain, malaise and movement disorder and she was very tired from lack of sleep. Emergency room or doctor visit was required. Treatment was received for the event atrial fibrillation (metoprolol), and pain (ibuprofen). She saw a cardiologist. She will get monitored every 6 months. The patient recovered from the events, atrial fibrillation, and potassium decreased. She did not recover from the events, pain in extremity, sleep difficult, petechiae, memory disturbance, pain aggravated, and activities of daily living impaired; while clinical outcome of the other events was unknown. Follow-up (11Jan2016): New information reported from the same contactable consumer includes: patient details, medical history, suspect drug (changed from "PREVNAR" to "PREVNAR 13") and concomitant medications details, reaction data, case seriousness changed from "non-serious" to "serious".

SYMPTOM_TEXT: On 12/21/2015 patient was given a Tdap vaccine as part of a new hire assessment. She denied contraindications to Tdap. Two days after receiving the vaccine she developed fatigue, irritability, sore throat, denies redness and swelling of arm. She denied having fever or airway reaction. Her dad remembered that she had a rxn as a child to a DTP and was advised to never be vaccinated with DTP/TD vaccine again. She states she was unaware that she had a contraindication until she had the current reaction. Her symptoms progressed to vomiting. She saw her PCP. On 01/13/2016 she came to EH and reported incident. She had vomiting yesterday and now has gland swelling on the L cervical node. She reports she had no airway rxn. Still feeling poorly. Denies fever. She was advised to complete a PSA. She is advised to seek medical care for increase in gland swelling and given information that it could cause airway impingement if swelling increases. If there are in airway symptoms she should seek immediate emergency care including use of ambulance. She demonstrates an understanding of directions. (Created on 1/11/2016 and 8:59).
HISTORY: Undisclosed prior reaction to DTP as child. Prior reaction was unknown to patient.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: This spontaneous case was initially received on 26-Oct-2015. The case report was received from a(n) Non Health Professional and concerns a(n) 60 years old female patient. Weight: not provided, Height: 63.5 inches. For concomitant medication and therapy dates refer to the appropriate report sections. Suspect drug(s), timing and conditions surrounding the onset of reaction(s)/event(s): The patient received Afluria for indication Protection against the influenza virus on 20-Oct-2015 - 20-Oct-2015, Batch no: not provided, Route of administration: Intramuscular, Dose: no information provided. Additional suspect drug(s): No additional drugs suspected. Reaction(s)/event(s) and outcome: On 22-Oct-2015, after starting / treatment with Afluria the patient experienced Drowsiness (non serious, outcome: Not Recovered / Not Resolved), Malaise/Increased malaise (non serious, outcome: Not Recovered / Not Resolved), Chills (non serious, outcome: Not Recovered / Not Resolved), Felt warm/[Had a fever because] she was warm to touch/Feeling hot/Forehead was hot to touch (non serious, outcome: Not Recovered / Not Resolved). On 25-Oct-2015, after starting / treatment with Afluria the patient experienced Fever (non serious, outcome: Not Recovered / Not Resolved), Nasal congestion/Congestion in context of nasal congestion (non serious, outcome: Not Recovered / Not Resolved). On an unknown date, after starting / treatment with Afluria the patient experienced Rhinorrhoea (non serious, outcome: Not Recovered / Not Resolved). Action taken: discontinued. Event treatment: No antipyretic treatment. Patient treated with oxymetazoline. For relevant test results see appropriate report section. Reporter's assessment: ***Follow-up information received from a HCP on 06-Nov-2015: The reporter reported the term 'lack of effect' and assessed the causality as 'unlikely' in relation to Afluria. ***Case correction 08-Feb-2016: AE 8 'lack of effect' updated to core listed, AEs 1 to 8 upgraded to serious based on reported lack of effect. Sender's Comments: Company's evaluation and comment: Seriousness criterion/criteria: Non serious. Listedness: According to the Reference Safety Information, the events Malaise/Increased malaise, Chills and Fever are listed events of Afluria, the events Drowsiness, Felt warm/[Had a fever because] she was warm to touch/Feeling hot/Forehead was hot to touch, Nasal congestion/Congestion in context of nasal congestion and Rhinorrhoea are unlisted events of Afluria. Case Causality: Possible. Company's evaluation and comment 26-Nov-2015: no change in assessment. Company evaluation and comment: updated 11-Feb-2016. Seriousness criterion/criteria: Medically significant due Lack of effect. Listedness: Assessment according to the CCDS for CSL Inactivated Influenza Virus Vaccine, and the Afluria PI, drowsiness is unlisted. All other events (malaise, increased malaise and chills, warm to touch, feeling hot, forehead hot to touch, nasal congestion, congestion  and rhinorrhoea) are listed in context of Influenza like illness (ILI). Lack of effect is also listed as vaccine efficacy is not 100%. Causality: Possible. Time to onset is 3 days for initial events(drowsiness, malaise, chills, fever) and 6 days for respiratory tract symptoms. The time to onset is not consistent for lack of efficacy as seroconversion following immunisation takes at least 2 weeks. Additionally there is no lab data to suggest Influenza infection. The events most likely represent Influenza like illness which is defined as fever, in association with  upper respiratory tract symptoms (nasal congestion and rhinorrhoea) and 2 systemic symptoms (chills malaise). ILI can occur in the week following vaccination. Causality is considered possibly related for all events but not in context of vaccination failure. Causality is unrelated for event of Lack of effect.

This spontaneous report as received from a patient's mother refers to an approximately 26 year old non-pregnant female patient. There were no concomitant medications, concurrent conditions and medical history reported. In February 2008, September 2008 and January 2009, the patient was vaccinated with first, second and third dose respectively of GARDASIL (route and site of administration, lot number, expiration date and indication were not reported). It was reported that the patient was hospitalized at the beginning of 2009 (reported as 20 days after receiving the third and final dose of GARDASIL). At the time of hospitalization, the doctors stated that the patient's "immune system was attacking her". It was also reported that the right side of the patient's body "had essentially been crippled". She no longer had the ability to move her right hand backwards and muscle growth along the right side of her body had ceased. There was no flexibility in the patient's right foot. In order to walk the patient had to "drag her leg" and driving was very difficult for her. The reporter also stated that the patient's symptoms have gotten worse since the original symptoms have developed. The patient's mother also reported that the patient's right ankle bone was much bigger than her left ankle, during the call she compared the right ankle to "that of 60 year old woman", she also mentioned that the patient experienced unspecified symptoms related to her condition occurring in her ribcage area. Lab diagnostic studies included bone tests on wrists and ankles, x-rays, and computerised tomography (CT) (results not provided). The patient sought medical attention via several doctors visits. The outcome of the events was reported as not recovered/not resolved at the time of the report. The reporter did not provide the relatedness, however the doctors at the hospital did not associate the patient's symptoms with the GARDASIL. The reporter considered the events as significant disability. Upon internal review the event of hemiplegia was considered as medically significant. Additional information has been requested.

This case was reported by a consumer via call center representative and described the occurrence of iron decreased in a 16-year-old male patient who received FLUARIX. Previously experienced adverse reactions included tremor, nausea, anxiety, numbness and tingling (after receiving FLUARIX vaccine in Oct 2014, refers case US2016018245). Previously administered products included Flu vaccine (non-GSK vaccine received prior to 2014 without experiencing any adverse events). Concurrent medical conditions included esophageal acid reflux and pineal gland cyst (since birth). Concomitant products included MENINGITIS VACCINE, omeprazole and vitamin D nos. In October 2015, the patient received FLUARIX (intramuscular). In November 2015, 30 days after receiving FLUARIX, the patient experienced nausea, anxiety, numbness of extremities, tingling feet/hands and panic attack. On an unknown date, the patient experienced iron decreased. The patient was treated with iron. In December 2015, the outcome of the nausea, anxiety, numbness of extremities, tingling feet/hands and panic attack were recovered/resolved. On an unknown date, the outcome of the iron decreased was not recovered/not resolved. It was unknown if the reporter considered the iron decreased, nausea, anxiety, numbness of extremities, tingling feet/hands and panic attack were recovered/resolved. On an unknown date, the outcome of the iron decreased was not recovered/not resolved. It was unknown if the reporter considered the iron decreased, nausea, anxiety, numbness of extremities, tingling feet/hands and panic attack to be related to FLUARIX. Additional details were provided as follows: This case was previously reported to a doctor. This case was reported by the patient's grandmother. In 2015, the patient also had  meningitis vaccine along with flu vaccine, but the reporter thought the patient only had flu vaccine in 2014. The reporter did not know which GLAXOSMITHKLINE flu vaccine the patient received. In November 2015, approximately 1 month after receiving the vaccine, the patient experienced nausea, anxiety, numbness and tingling in hands and feet, and panic attack (same symptoms occurred after vaccinated in October 2014 except the tremors). The patient had a total of 2 panic attacks that required a visit to the emergency room (ER) between November 2015 and December 2015. The patient sometimes had more minor symptoms that subsided without medical attention. This year the symptoms were more concentrated on the patient's right side. In 2015, the patient underwent laboratory test such as Magnetic Resonance Imaging (MRI), Electroencephalogram (EEG) and Computerized tomogram (CT), but all that was found was a cyst on the patient's pineal gland that was thought to be benign and something he was born with. Since December 2015, the patient did not experience any event. At the time of reporting, the patient had started having low iron levels.
LAB_DATA: In 2015, the patient underwent laboratory test such as MRI, EEG and CT, which revealed a cyst on the patient's pineal gland that was thought to be benign and something he was born with.
CUR_ILL: Gastrooesophageal reflux disease; Pineal gland cyst, since birth
HISTORY: 11/2014, Tremor; 11/2014, Nausea; 11/2014, Anxiety; 11/2014, Hypoaesthesia; 11/2014, Paraesthesia, after receiving FLUARIX 14-15 season vaccine in Oct 2014, refer case US2016018245; Influenza vaccines, non-GSK vaccines received prior to 2014 without experiencing any adverse events

SYMPTOM_TEXT: This case was reported by a consumer via call center representative and described the occurrence of tremor in a 15-year-old male patient who received FLUARIX. Concurrent medical conditions included esophageal acid reflux. Concomitant products included omeprazole and Vitamin D. In October 2014, the patient received FLUARIX (intramuscular). In November 2014, 30 days after receiving FLUARIX, the patient experienced tremor (serious criteria hospitalization), nausea (serious criteria hospitalization), anxiety (serious criteria hospitalization), numbness of extremities (serious criteria hospitalization), tingling feet/hands (serious criteria hospitalization) and panic attack (serious criteria hospitalization). In January 2015, the outcome of the tremor, nausea, anxiety, numbness of extremities, tingling feet/hands and panic attack were recovered/resolved. It was unknown if the reporter considered the tremor, nausea, anxiety, numbness of extremities, tingling feet/hands and panic attack to be related to FLUARIX. Additional details were provided as follows: This case was previously reported to a doctor. This case was reported by the patient's grandmother. The reporter did not know which GSK flu vaccine the patient received. Three times between November 2014 and December 2014, the patient had a sudden onset of tremors, numbness and tingling in hands and feet, and severe nausea. He visited emergency room (ER) each time and at least once was kept under observation for 2 days. It was believed that the patient experienced panic attacks, but the reporter thought he was only anxious because he did not understand what had happened to him. The symptoms subsided between panic attacks before suddenly coming back out of the blue. The patient was fine between January 2015 to October 2015. For tolerance to vaccination received in October 2015, refer case US2016GSK020967.

10-2005 severe pain in left shoulder blade. Hand paralyzed. 12-18-2005 called 911 - hospital - vertigo. 10-2007 2nd episode of pain. Again hand paralyzed. No one knew what was wrong with me. 6-23-2008 went to clinic - Dr, looked at MRI's, CAT Scans - MRI Head - EEG and blood work - X-rays - angiogram of head - nerve conductions. Parsonage Turner syndrome. After two weeks after influenza vaccine, I woke up with excruciating pain in left shoulder blade. 11-21-05 Dr's office - could not stand or sit (pain) (Hydromorphone and carisoprodol) back office - lay down sometime later left hand fingers paralyzed. 12-16-05 Dr. ordered MRI. 12-18-05 Fell back on bed twice, very dizzy daughter called 911. Hosp CT brain, EKG tracing, Rx meclizine, never had vertigo. 12-22-05 Dr office 1:30. 12-27-05 Neurology, 3:00. 12-29-05 Dr's office feeling dizzy, meclizine. 1-4-06 Dr office 11:00 results of test. 1-5-06 MD 9:00. Starting to feel better. Starting  to move fingers. 2-2-06 Dr 10:30 chest x-rays (no acute disease). 2-6-06 Neurologist consultation. 2-17-06 Dr. 2-20-06 Dr ENG test 3:00. 2-24-06 Dr results of test vertigo. 3-21-06 10:45 MRI head. 3-28-06 12:45 Neck. 4-3-06 Dr. 12:15. 5-2-06 Dr office 1:00 EEG, within normal limits. 5-30-06 Dr. results of EEG and blood work. 6-15-06 12:45 Ultrasound. 6-16-06 Dr 1:00 new prescription. 6-26-06 11:00 Neurologist bring copies of tests. 6-30-06 Dr check-up. 7-6-06 New Dr. 7-12-06 6:00 AM Angiogram 5 hour test. 2 artery x-rays head - 1 artery x-rays neck. 2 place catheter in art - OPTIRAY 320/150 ML. 7-18-06 Dr results of blood work. 8-9-06 11:00 MRI, get films. 8-14-06 Dr 10:30 bring films of MRI in. No one really knows what is wrong with me. Nothing is showing up in all those tests starting with pain in shoulder blade again. Can't move fingers on left hand. 10-29-07 Dr (CNS) 2:00 NPI x-rays. 11-10-07 Dr (CNS) 7:00 test. 11-14-07 3:30 MRI Brain. 11-19-07 Dr has 4:00. 11-27-07 Dr (CNS) 2:40 results of test prescription for splint-hand-thumb sticks up. 11-27-07, 12-4-07, 12-06-07, 12-10-07, 12-13-07, 12-17-07 for therapy left hand. 12-12-07 CAT Scan. 1-2-08 Dr. Bring in MRI brain, neck and back, CAT scan of chest. 1-9-08 Radiologist 10:30. 1-14-08 Dr (CNS) wants to see MRI 11-14-07 - MRI 12-12-07. 1-16-08 Dr wants to see all films. 1-22-08 Radiologist 10:30. 2-13-08 Dr 2 x-rays. 2-18-08 Dr 11:15 MRI arm. Office x-rays neck and chest. 3-4-08 9:45, 3-12-08 11:00, 3-18-08 11:00 therapy hand - left hand can't button, can't tie laces, can't pick up anything. 3-21-08 Dr (CNS) bring in MRI results. 3-14-08 (Chiropractor) 3 visits per week. Bring in x-rays and tests. 3 visits per week 4-17, 4-18, 4-21, 4-23, 4-25, 4-28, 4-30, 5-2 this helped somewhat. Hand looking bad. 4-23-08 Dr (CNS) called me. Referral came in for another clinic. 5-29-08 Dept of Neurology called about referral. 6-22-08 Sunday traveled. 6-23-08 Monday appointment at new clinic with Dr 3:30. He spoke with us, examined my hand, looked at the MRIs and x-rays. Dr told us that I have Parsonage Turner syndrome, The nerves can grow back. Do not get any flu vaccines shots. Dr was very nice, answered our questions. Not one doctor locally knew what I had (then and now). 6-24-08 Tues. returned home. Someone looked up Parsonage Turner syndrome on her computer. Couldn't  find anything, except Intrinsic weakness and claw hand. Also an unusual cases of claw hand (case report). Nothing stating vaccine injury compensation program. 7-22-08 Therapy 11:00 staff made me a splint to help keep my thumb down. 7-30-08 Therapy 10:00. 8-6-08 Therapy 10:30. 8-15-08 Dr (CNS) 10:45 check-up. 8-26-08 Therapy 10:30 nerve machine (TENS). I have notes up until 2015.
LAB_DATA: Monomelic amyotrophy - left hand - symptoms are severe 1-25-2011

This case was reported by a consumer and described the occurrence of vaccination failure in a male patient who received BEXSERO. Co-suspect products included BEXSERO. Concurrent medical conditions included exposure to communicable disease (total 3 students including the patient had become sick with meningococcal disease). On an unknown date, the patient received the 1st dose of BEXSERO. In October 2015, the patient received the 2nd dose of BEXSERO. In February 2016, an unknown time after receiving BEXSERO and 91 days after receiving BEXSERO, the patient experienced vaccination failure (serious criteria GSK medically significant), bacterial meningitis (serious criteria hospitalization and GSK medically significant), headache, stiff neck and fever. On an unknown date, the outcome of the vaccination failure was unknown and the outcome of the bacterial meningitis, headache, stiff neck and fever were recovered/resolved. It was unknown if the reporter considered the vaccination failure, bacterial meningitis, headache, stiff neck and fever to be related to BEXSERO and BEXSERO. Additional details were provided as follows: The patient was previously healthy and had no chronic conditions or medications. There were total 3 students (including the patient) who had become sick with meningococcal disease outbreak at the university. Approximately 3 and half months after vaccination with 2nd dose of BEXSERO, the patient experienced the events. The patient was hospitalized for 3 days and was released. There were no complications. The reporter did not know about any results of diagnostic testing on cerebrospinal fluid. This case was considered as suspected vaccination failure since the details regarding confirmatory laboratory tests were not provided.
CUR_ILL: Exposure to communicable disease, total 3 students including the patient had become sick with meningococcal disease

SERIOUSNESS CRITERIA: OTHER - MEDICALLY SIGNIFICANT. Initial report received from a consumer on 29 September 2014 via a social media page. That report is from social media and contact information in based upon the location of our trading partner. A female consumer reported that in 1975, at two months of age, she received DTP (DIPHTHERIA, TETANUS AND PERTUSSIS VACCINE (ADSORBED)) (manufacturer and lot number not reported) and an unspecified amount of time later experienced spinal meningitis and encephalitis ("I had just gotten my DPT shot"). According to the reporter, family history included a third cousin who experienced a similar "allergic reaction", and the reporter attributed the events to a "recessive gene". Symptoms included a fever of 106 degrees, and per the reporter "they took the fluid off my brain with a needle, and I still have the white freckle from the scar on my scalp". Outcome was not reported. Documents held by sender: None. Addendum on 2 February 2016: Upon second medical examination of the case during internal review, a significant correction was performed to correct the product code of DPT from 'DIPHTHERIA/TETANUS/WHOLE CELL PERTUSSIS ADSORBED VACCINE' to 'DIPHTHERIA, TETANUS AND ACELLULAR PERTUSSIS VACCINE'. Addendum on 5 February 2016: Upon second medical examination of the case during internal review, a significant correction was performed on 5 February 2016 to correct the product code of DPT from 'DIPHTHERIA, TETANUS AND ACELLULAR PERTUSSIS VACCINE' to 'DIPHTHERIA, TETANUS AND PERTUSSIS VACCINE (ADSORBED)'. Sender's Comments: This is a poorly documented, consumer-reported case of meningitis in a 2-month-old following DTP vaccination. Infants are at higher risk for meningitis, as are patients with certain underlying diseases. In addition, the event occurred in 1975 prior to the availability of a vaccine for Hib, a common cause of meningitis in infants. Additional information regarding the patient's past medical history, laboratory and pathology findings, and vaccination details would be helpful in fully assessing the case.

I received a pneumococcal polysaccharide booster in my left arm on Monday afternoon.  On Tuesday afternoon while changing a shirt I observed that a large area around the injection site was red and swollen.  My upper arm felt tight, as if being squeezed.  By the time I saw a Doctor Wed. morning the swelling and redness had spread further toward the underside of my arm.  It did not itch, but was tender to the touch.  It did not respond to Benadryl (I had taken two doses 6 hours apart on Tuesday night.). There was no treatment prescribed other than ibuprofen, which I declined to take.  Over the next few days the reddened areas turned yellow, then faded completely by week's end.  Five years previously (in Dec., 2014 I had had a metal plate removed from that arm because it was infected with strep.  The plate was surgically inserted to repair a broken humerus in 2006.

That night on 10/19/15, the day I received the flu shot in my left arm, my left arm was painful and appeared red and swollen for next 2 weeks. It was difficult to sleep on the left side  awakened during the night by pain until this very day. I also couldnt even put arm under pillow. Perhaps most disturbing is that the next day I had very limited range of motion with my left arm.  Specifically, on 10/20/15, I was unable to lift my left arm at to the side more than a few inches, and I was also unable to lift my left arm to the front of my body more than a few inches. The pain in my shoulder became worse over the next few months (Very painful about 6 out of 10).  The pain was initially like a toothache  deep inside arm. Jan 8, 2016- Still same problem with limited range of motion; New symptom of numbness/tingling in area between elbow and wrist, which made doing my job as a college professor difficult (e.g., hard to type  need to take breaks). Weakness in arm  feels heavy  tired arm. On Jan 19, 2016 I went for a for muscular-skeletal ultrasound, and on Jan 21, 2016 I had an appointment with an orthopedic surgeon who diagnosed me with rotator cuff tendonitis with calcium deposits, and I received a cortisone shot that day.  Although the cortisone shot lessened the pain for a few weeks, I currently have worse pain prior to receiving the shot, and I am left with the same restriction of motion (i.e., inability to move my left arm out to the side more than few inches, and inability to move my left arm to the front more than a few inches; otherwise I am in pain).  It is difficult and painful to put my left arm in a jacket, I can't put my left arm behind my back, and pushing on a soap dispenser or opening a door with my left arm is painful.  These are current symptoms that I still have since receiving the flu shot on 10/19/15.
LAB_DATA: Muscular-skeletal ultrasound on left arm on 1/19/16; x-ray of left arm on 1/21/16 and cortisone shot on 1/21/16
HISTORY: Hypothyroidism under control for 9 yrs, and never had a problem with the flu shot previously. Thyroid levels have been normal for years.

Patient's mother reported by phone that her daughter's right upper arm was hot and red. I received this report shortly before 5 p.m. on 02/17/2016. With another staffer, we called the patient's mother to assess her daughter. The daughter's behavior was normal and the child had no fever. I advised the mother to offer the child acetaminophen or ibuprofen before bedtime and that she take the child to the doctor if the redness and heat got worse overnight. At 9:15 a.m. on 02/18/16, through yet a third staffer, we called the client's mother for a report on the child. The child had no fever; slept well overnight; the extent of the redness was the same as the evening before; behavior was as usual; and "Motrin" had been given the previous evening. The injection site still "hurts a lot" and is "warm." I advised the mother, through the interpreter, to continue pain medication and to outline the extent of the redness to be able to monitor its progression. Another follow-up call at 4:20 PM 02/18/16 yielded the same information: child is behaving as normal; had "Motrin" during the day; slept well overnight; no fever; arm "hurts a lot"; no change in extent of redness.
Muscle aches, pain all over.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: This spontaneous report was received from a nurse via field representative refers to a 18 year old male patient. The concurrent condition included no allergy. The patient had never passed out during sports. No family history of sudden cardiac death. There was no weight changes and no current vision abnormalities. The patient's medical history included headaches. On 12-FEB-2016, the patient was vaccinated with GARDASIL 9 (lot # L014415, dose 1, intramuscular in the left arm, dose not provided). No concomitant therapy was reported. After dose 1 was administered, the patient was discharged to waiting area. Approximately after 60 seconds in waiting area, patient suffered sudden loss of consciousness. Ammonia salts were applied but the patient remained unresponsive. There was onset of hand clenching and tightening but no clonic movements were noted. Oxygen mask was applied at 2L but the patient remained unresponsive. Oxygen was increased to 3L and the patient became responsive but very sluggish, pale, nauseated, lightheaded. Oxygen saturation was 99-100%, heart rate was 55, blood pressure was 108/62. Later emergency medical service arrived and blood pressure improved to 112/69 and pulse improved to 85. The patient was taken to the emergency department. The patient denied any chest pain or palpitation before losing consciousness. There was no loss of urine or tongue bite. All diagnostic tests for systems were normal. The patient was finally discharged with instructions to come back if he passes again especially if he don't get dizzy beforehand or if he has chest pain or palpitations. The outcome of the event was unknown. The causality assessment was not reported. No product quality issue was involved. The case was considered serious due to life threatening event. Additional information has been requested.
LAB_DATA: 02/12/2016, Blood pressure measurement, 108/62; 02/12/2016, Blood pressure measurement, 112/69; 02/12/2016, Heart rate, 55; 02/12/2016, Heart rate, 85; 02/12/2016, Oxygen saturation, 99-100%; 02/12/2016, Oxygen saturation, 100%
HISTORY: Headache; 10/23/2014, Hepatitis A virus vaccine, (unspecified), immunisation

Patient had the Gardasil series on the following dates: 3/27/14, 7/2/14, and 4/7/15.  On 7/25/15, Mother was awoken on a Saturday to dog barking.  She noted child lying on bed stiff with arms drawn up toward chest, eyes rolling upward and foaming at the mouth with the dog lying on top of the child.  Mother unsure of the length of activity- no loss of bladder or bowel.  Patient was seen over the course of several months for an EEG, sleep study, and had a Head CT done on 7/25/15.  The CT and EEG were essentially normal, and her sleep study showed some sleep apnea, possibly due to enlarged tonsils.  The mother states she has had a total of 4 of these type "seizures", but they have not been witnessed by anyone other than her. This is a spontaneous report obtained from two contactable pharmacists. A 76-year-old female patient received PREVNAR 13 (Lot M69971, Expiration date: Jul2017, NDC number: 00005197105) on 17Dec2015 at 11:46 A.M., in right arm, at 0.5 ml, single dose; and second dose of FLUVIRIN (Lot 1515101, Expiration date: May2016, NDC number: 66521011810) intramuscular, in right arm, on 17Dec2015, at 0.5 ml, single dose. The vaccines were administered at pharmacy and were purchased with private funds. No illness was noted at time of vaccination. No antipyretics were administered prior to vaccination. Relevant medical history included ongoing high blood pressure (diagnosed years before this report, prior to age 65), ongoing gout (diagnosed at least 4 years before this report), blood clots (diagnosed 4 or 5 years before this report, developed after knee and hip surgery, 3 blood clots in her lung, one blood clot in her leg), ongoing fluid retention (diagnosed prior to age 65), ongoing degenerative back pain (diagnosed prior to age 65), knee operation (done 4 or 5 years before this report), hip surgery (done 4 or 5 years before this report), pain (ongoing), neuropathy (ongoing), and osteoporosis (ongoing). She was evaluated by physician on site. BP 123/79, P78, R18. Client was given juice and crackers, as she had not eaten since breakfast. At the onset of the event, 911 was called. The EMT squad arrived and also evaluated vital signs and level of consciousness. No visible injuries were sustained. The mother declined transport to the hospital. The patient is a 42 yo healthy female who experienced immediate pain, local erythema, pruritis, edema and nodule formation at the injection site after receipt of IIV to her (R) deltoid, with brief systemic symptoms of mild light headedness and loss of focus to events and a 'lump in her throat.' The clinical history and clinical exam are not consistent with IgE mediated event as the symptoms were localized and not urticarial. I suspect her systemic symptoms were in response to pain and stress. Per report of clinic RN vital signs were stable. Her presentation is most consistent with formation of a hematoma secondary to injection. Aspiration is no longer a recommended technique due to the absence of any large vessels in the deltoid. The patient is not on any blood thinners or has any known coagulopathy. The injection site was consistent with appropriate technique. The patient was educated on self care of continued ice, followed by heat in 1-2 days, rest, (with caution to maintain ROM in the shoulder to prevent freezing), and ibuprofen tid (take with food).

SYMPTOM_TEXT: It started on 9-10-15 at 1:00A.M. A burning pain in one spot on my back between my right shoulder blade and my spine. For the next 2 days I had increased pain that traveled up my back to my neck and over to my right shoulder. On 9-12-15 I went to E.R. with a level 10 pain. They gave me a morphine shot, muscle relaxer pills and pain pills. On 9-13-15 I was groggie and couldn't use my right arm. On 9-14-15 I was back in E.R. because I completely loss the use of my right arm. They checked my heart, checked my right arm for a blood clot, everything was o.k, then they saw a rash on my arm and realized I had shingles. The E.R. doctor took me off the other pain pills and gave me pills to help with the virus. The rash went from my wrist under arm to my elbow then up to my shoulder, across the top of my shoulder and spread out over my shoulder blade down to where the pain started. For the next 3-4 weeks I could only sleep for 30 min. at a time because of the burning pain in my arm and shoulder. In Nov. I called Dr. office and they gave me gabapentin 100 mg. For nerve pain. Mid November I could touch my arm so I started Phy. therapy, 3 x a week. In mid Dec. Dr office made an appointment (at P.T. request) for me to see a Neurologist. That appointment was for 1-28-16 with Dr. She examined me and was surprised to see how bad my shoulder muscles had atrophied. She increased the Gabapentin to 300 mg. for pain and healing, have an MRI on Feb 5th, (that's done) see an Occ. Therapist on Feb 9th (did that) have an EMG on Feb. 23 (next week) and continue with P.T. My right arm is still not working correctly.
Ongoing pain in shoulder and arm.
OTHER_MEDS: Lisinopril - 40MG; Amlodipine Besylate - 5MG; Atenolol - 25MG; Glipizide - 5MG; Metformin - 1000MG; Aspirin - 325MG

SYMPTOM_TEXT: I received the shingles vaccine a week ago.  The next day, my upper arm was totally swollen.  A huge red blotch was in the center where the shot was given, and there was redness all around that.  There was significant pain, and it was awfully itchy.  It got worse over the next few days.  I couldn't sleep for three nights because of the swelling and pain.   Yesterday, the swelling had totally subsided and the red center blotch turned somewhat black and blue, so I know it is going away.  But when I initially asked about any side effects of the vaccine, I was told there might be a few hours of swelling and redness, and that wasn't the majority of people.  After my symptoms worried me, I asked another person about her experience with the vaccine, and she had the same outcome as I did.  So I am reporting this to make sure that you know this is not an uncommon reaction to the shingles vaccine, and the truth should be told to those asking about potential reactions to the vaccine.  I have never had an adverse reaction to any other medications/vaccines...only this one.

The patient had also received capsule of Lyrica (150 mg, once a day, orally) for fibromyalgia from an unspecified date to 08 February 2016. The patient's medical history includes allergy, compromised immune system, respiratory illness, genetic/ chromosomal abnormalities, endocrine abnormalities, obesity and concomitant medications were not reported. On an unspecified date in October 2014, few days following the vaccination, the patient had experienced Guillain Barre Syndrome (diagnosed on March 2015). On an unspecified date in December 2015, few months following the vaccination, the patient had experienced urinary tract infection, Fell and hit her head. The patient's concurrent conditions includes well controlled diabetes from 2010. The patient was hospitalized on an unspecified date in December 2015. Laboratory data includes test (needles placed in feet and back) was performed and platelet was 14 times than normal. MRI and X-ray was performed in December 2015, no abnormalities found. On December 2015, blood test was performed, diagnosed with ear infection. The patient had received antibiotic (unspecified) for urinary tract infection as corrective treatment. The outcome of event Guillain Barre Syndrome was reported as recovering. The patient was not recovered from event urinary tract infection and outcome of event Fell and hit my head was not reported. The patient was discharged from hospital on an unspecified date in first week of January 2016. List of documents held by sender: none. Sender's Comments: The patient experience Guillain Barre Syndrome and Urinary tract infection with INFLUENZA VACCINE (unknown manufacture). Time to onset is not compatible with the role of the vaccine. Further information for e.g investigative details ruling out any congenital condition metabolic disorders, maternal pre and postnatal history would help assess the events better. The patient received other vaccines so making it difficult to assess the role of each vaccine in particular based on the information available, the role of the vaccine cannot be assessed.

Patient received his 2nd dose of flu vaccine for this season and his dad noticed he was wheezing a few minutes afterwards when he arrived home. Dad brought him back to the office and administered a nebulizer  treatment of albuterol sulfate inhalation. 2-23-16 This is a 9 month old here for check-up. Is doing quite well with his molding helmet per Dr. PE is otherwise normal. Immunizations up to date. Recheck in 3 months. 2-23-16 This is a 9 month old here for check-up. We just saw him earlier this morning here for his 9 month check-up. Had a molding helmet on but his exam was normal. We gave him the second flu shot and upon arriving home about half an hour later he started having a little bit of wheezing. Neither of his parents are allergic to eggs. He did not have any problems at all with his first flu shot in November 2015. Upon examination he has more of a croupy sounding voice with very, very minimal wheezing in the lower lung fields. I gave him a neb mask treatment and the wheezing cleared up. I went ahead and did an RSV test but this was negative. Thus may just be the onset of some croup. However it was certainly related from a time point of view within an hour of giving him his flu shot so it could also be a flu shot reaction but he responded well to the breathing treatment. I am going to go ahead and put him on PRELONE syrup 4 ml. Once a day for the next 3 days. They will elevate the head of the bed, use a vaporizer. They will call if symptoms worsen. 6-11-15 This is an extended visit for this 2 week old that was born at 37 weeks. Had an induced vaginal delivery because of maternal preeclampsia. Was admitted directly to the NICU where certainly after birth started having some seizure activity. We don't have the complete dictated records yet. Was sent home with the diagnosis of hypoxic ischemic encephalitis and is on KEPPRA and also Phenobarbital which are being monitored by the neonatology service. We are going to try to get an appointment in the near future with neurology. The child otherwise is taking pumped breast milk 60-90 cc's every 3 hours and is gaining weight. The child's exam does have a right turn of his head but will work with this over the next couple of weeks. May need physical therapy if it does not resolve. Neurological evaluation is normal. HEENT is negative. Neck is supple. Chest is supple to auscultation. Cardiac exam is normal. Abdominal exam is unremarkable. IMP: Seizure disorder secondary to hypoxic encephalopathy. Will get an appointment as soon as we can. Will also recheck in 1-2 weeks to make sure that his weight gain is going well. Answered numerous questions for this very nice family.
HISTORY: No known allergies; Has plagiocephaly and torticollis; History of hypoxic ischemic encephalitis

He prescribed Methylprednisolone 4 MG Dosepack and also Benadryl, and Zyrtec.   Also use Desoximetasone that I already had.  I then saw someone at a dermatolgy center on February 8 and 18th.   She believed it was related to our dogs, but I receive allergy injections that covers the dogs.   We treated our dogs and house for fleas, but no evidence of fleas was found. I am still taking the Benadryl and Zyrtec and using the prescription hydrocortisone cream and an over-the-counter one for my face and neck.

The patient had been receiving intramuscular SYNAGIS, 15.0 milligrams per kilogram, unknown frequency started on 15-Apr-2015 for prematurity and unknown influenza vaccine. The patient presented 2 episodes of pneumonia and, in both of them, the symptoms were dry cough, irritability, flu, and pulmonary secretion (described as catarrh in the chest). Due to the first episode of pneumonia, the patient was hospitalized for 8 days in order to receive unspecified treatment and to be monitored. After being discharged, she underwent inhalation with saline solution for 3 days and the events were resolved. The patient was treated with Acetylcysteine, Cloperastine Fendizoate (seki), Saline solution, Amoxicillin and Salbutamol Sulphate. SYNAGIS was continued. The patient recovered from the events of pneumonia, dry cough, irritability, flu and pulmonary secretion on an unspecified date. Assessment of the serious criteria for the report was as follows by the reporter: hospitalized. Laboratory values are available. The reporter stated that there was no reasonable possibility that the events of pneumonia, dry cough, irritability, flu, pulmonary secretion were related to SYNAGIS and influenza vaccine. SYMPTOM_TEXT: Information received from an Investigator in a vaccine pregnancy registry. A 35 year old female (gravida 1 para 0) received dose 4 of BioThrax vaccine in JAN2015 (at 4 weeks 0 days estimated gestational age (EGA)). The female was determined to be pregnant in JAN2015, 10 days after vaccination. She sent a study referral (generated from active case finding efforts) in FEB2016 which indicated that she had a miscarriage in MAR2015 (5 weeks + 3 days EGA). Treatments included: oxycodone hcl / acetaminophen, promethazine and acetaminophen. No further information is expected. The subject was not eligible for entry in the registry; the Investigator forwarded the information to the vaccine manufacturer.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: 15mo presents for follow up after inpatient stay for complex febrile seizure. Presented to facility febrile after short episode at home witnessed by babysitter (cold hands, perioral cyanosis, staring, drooling x20sec) and was subsequently admitted for ALTE vs febrile seizure. During admission she had a 5-10 minute tonic-clonic febrile seizure on pediatric ward (witnessed by resident) at facility, and then was transferred to PICU. She had no further fevers or seizures after she was transferred. She was discharged from the PICU later that afternoon (<12hrs later). Tmax since discharge was 100.1 measured 2 nights ago. PO intake has been normal. She has not had any cough/runny nose/diarrhea/vomiting/signs of illness. She does have a rash on her body that started the day of her first seizure and really began to get darker pink/red colored the day she was in the PICU, and is now fading. Mom insists that it is different appearing than her normal eczema breakouts. She was discharged from the PICU with Diastat, and a consult was placed for outpatient peds neurology consult. The febrile seizure occurred 10 days after her first MMR vaccine was given.
LAB_DATA: Rapid RSV/Flu were negative, as was outpatient respiratory viral panel, UA, chemistry, CBC, blood & urine cultures.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Needle injury. My husband and I went together to get our annual Flu shots. We noticed the pharmacist seemed clumsy while getting out supplies, but didn't know there could be a serious problem since we had never had problems with a vaccine before. The pharmacist gave me a shot first. It felt like he had done it too hard. Then he gave my husband a shot and blood was dripping down my husband's arm and the pharmacist was slow to do anything about it. When someone has been well trained or has lot of experience their movements are smooth and quick. They have the cotton ball ready to go and the bandaid, but he was klutzy. My arm hurt then but I thought it would go away in a couple of days. Instead it kept hurting so I took some OTC pain pills. Then I noticed that certain movements of my left arm (where the shot was given) hurt so much I stopped making those movements. Straight movements were ok but nothing to the side or back or up, as when putting my hair in a ponytail. I couldn't pick up my toddler grandkids anymore. I now wear shirts that button down the front because it hurts too much to put my arm thru a sleeve with an upwards and sideways motion. When I would roll onto my left side in bed it hurt, and I am a left-side sleeper. This keeps waking me up throughout the night. After 2 months of thinking it would get better on its own, thinking if he had hit a nerve there wouldn't be much that could be done anyway, I did some Internet research and found that it has been given a name: SIRVA. I read accounts of women who experienced what I was going through. I still gave it a few more weeks since some of the women said nothing had helped. Then with the pain still bad and certain movements very painful I went to see my primary care doctor. We ruled out a blood clot with an ultrasound, then after a second visit also did an xray of the left humerus, then an MRI of the humerus. This MRI showed degenerative changes of the shoulder so I then had an MRI of the shoulder. The MRI of the shoulder showed a partial thickness tear of the supraspinatus tendon. At time at my desk job I have pain up and down my arm, and I avoid the movements that are very painful. I take 5 ALEVE a day. If I don't take ALEVE even just holding my arm straight I can feel pain, sometimes a deep ache. I have to try to put my arm on an extra pillow in a certain way to try to get sleep. I use heat daily to help with the discomfort and have iced the upper arm/shoulder a few times also. A friend who is a physical therapist showed me 2 exercises/stretches to do telling me I couldn't stop using my shoulder completely or it would be even worse. I have now scheduled an appointment with an orthopedist. I don't know if I will eventually need surgery or not. This all started with the Flu shot. Initial unsolicited report received from a non-healthcare professional on 20-Jan-2016. This case involves a 40-year-old male patient, who was vaccinated with Fluzone (batch number: unknown, dose, dose in series, route and site of administration were not reported) on an unspecified date. Medical history and concomitant medications were not reported. On 16-Jan-2016 at 5:00 P.M, unspecified time after vaccination, patient found positive for influenza A virus test. It was reported that the patient required emergency room/doctor visit. Laboratory investigations and corrective treatments were not reported. At the time of this report patient was not recovered from the event. Documents held by sender: none. Follow up information received from the non-healthcare professional on 19 February 2016. The patient received a dose of FLUZONE (batch number U5321FA, expiration date 30 Jun 2016) on 22 October 2016. It was reported that the patient did not receive any previous vaccine. The patient did not have any known drug allergy and patient had tonsillectomy in 2001. Upon internal review this case considered as serious due to important medical events: Influenza A virus infection and vaccination failure. On 16 January 2016, two month after vaccination, the patient found positive for influenza A virus and it was a vaccination failure case. Sender's Comments: As with any vaccine, vaccination with INFLUENZA QUADRIVAL A-B VACCINE may not protect 100% of susceptible individuals. In the current case, the patient was tested positive for influenza group A 86 days post vaccination. Additional information regarding infectious work-up results, patient's immune status at the time of vaccination (medical history, concomitant medication), exact chronology with symptoms as well as confirmatory investigation results (details of test method used to confirm specific influenza A strain, e.g. PCR) are needed for complete assessment. Based on the available information, a possible vaccination failure cannot be ruled out.

After her stomach was relieved, she would return to my breast for food, however the behavior at the breast would resumes in a vicious cycle. This has been continuous for the past 4 weeks, and has not ended. Prior to this she was eating every 4 hours during the day and sleeping 6-8 hour at night. SYMPTOM_TEXT: This case was reported in a literature article and described the occurrence of vaccination failure in a 21-year-old female patient who received Hepatitis B vaccine. Concurrent medical conditions included intravenous drug user (ivdu), staphylococcus aureus endocarditis (secondary to methicillin-susceptible Staphylococcus aureus), non-ischemic cardiomyopathy (ejection fraction 15%) and hepatitis c (positive for hepatitis C viral antibodies with an undetectable hepatitis C viral RNA initially followed by a low level viremia). On an unknown date, the patient received Hepatitis B vaccine at an unknown dose. In November 2013, several years after receiving Hepatitis B vaccine, the patient experienced vaccination failure (serious criteria GSK medically significant) and hepatitis b (serious criteria GSK medically significant). On an unknown date, the outcome of the vaccination failure and hepatitis b were unknown. The reporter considered the vaccination failure to be related to Hepatitis B vaccine. It was unknown if the reporter considered the hepatitis b to be related to Hepatitis  B vaccine. Additional information was provided: This case was reported in a literature article and it described the occurrence of an occult hepatitis B infection in a 21-year-old female who had received unspecified hepatitis B vaccines (manufacturer unknown). The patient was an intravenous drug user. Concomitant medical conditions included tricuspid valve endocarditis secondary to methicillin-susceptible Staphylococcus aureus which was complicated by non-ischemic cardiomyopathy (ejection fraction 15%) for which the patient was hospitalized at the time of the event. No further information on the patient's concurrent medical conditions, medical and family history or concomitant medication was provided. On unspecified dates, the patient had received an unspecified number of hepatitis B vaccines for prophylaxis as part of a nursing training programme. Dosages unknown; administration routes and sites unspecified; batch numbers was not provided. In November 2013, date unspecified, several years after the vaccination, the patient tested positive for hepatitis C viral antibodies with an undetectable hepatitis C viral RNA initially followed by a low level viremia whole admitted due to an tricuspid valve endocarditis. She was persistently negative for hepatitis B surface antigen, but she tested positive for hepatitis B e antigen and hepatitis B viral DNA in 2 separate occasions. In addition to this, the patient became positive for hepatitis B core antibodies during her admission. However, she was negative for hepatitis B e antigens and hepatitis B core antibodies and had no detectable hepatitis B viral DNA six months later. According to the authors, this meant that the infection had subsided. This case was considered as medically relevant by GSK due to suspected vaccination failure. The patient was found to be positive for hepatitis C antibodies (undetectable DNA) and hepatitis B surface antibodies and negative for hepatitis B core total antibodies and human immunodeficiency virus antibodies on 19 November 2013. She tested negative for hepatitis B surface antigens on 17 January 2014 with an aspartate aminotransferase of 1873 IU/mL, an aspartate aminotransferase of 4518 IU/mL and a hepatitis C viral load of 902 IU/mL. Her hepatitis C viral load had dropped to 642 IU/mL on a test performed the following day, but she was found to have a hepatitis B viral load of 8364 IU/mL. Repeat liver enzymes level performed on 24 January 2014 showed a drop on her aspartate aminotransferase and aspartate aminotransferase levels (561 IU/mL and 203 IU/mL respectively). A serology performed on 25 January 2014 was negative for hepatitis B surface antigens, positive for hepatitis B surface and core (total) antibodies as well as for hepatitis B e antigens, but negative for hepatitis B e antibodies. She had a viral load of 174 and 4608 IU/mL for hepatitis C and hepatitis B virus respectively

My infant received the DTaP at 9 months, 2 weeks, 1 day. She was 16 lbs. She also received her polio vaccine the same day. That evening, 11/18/2016, she spiked a 102 fever overnight from Wednesday to Thursday that I assumed was related but a normal immune response. Then she had a couple dirty diapers that were green and kind of liquid that really burned her bottom. We hadnt eaten anything new except she had applesauce (natural, unsweetened) for the first time Wednesday night and Thursday with lunch, but I dont think that can cause stomach upset.... anyway, she was in bed that Wednesday night asleep by 8:30pm. She was still asleep the next morning (11/19/2015) at 10:32am! I went in and checked to make sure she was breathing frequently. She would kind of rouse a little then lay down and go back to sleep. I messaged our doctors messaging system to see if I should be concerned or do anything. My other two never did this. Even if ill, they never slept nor sleep that much. She already had a low grade temp (100.4) when we saw Dr. on Wednesday but no other symptoms until after the vaccine. She slept and slept and slept from bed time (8:30pm) the evening of the day she got the vaccine and just wouldnt  rouse. When I finally did get her up to offer her to nurse, she was very fussy, which isnt like her at all. I went in to change clothes about 11:15am (day following vaccine 11/19/15) and she didnt wake but I dropped a shoe and she woke and saw me and fussed to get up so I got her up and nursed her and she fell right back asleep. My husband came home a few minutes later for lunch and he changed her diaper while I ran a quick errand and he said it was wet, but not that wet - and she had been asleep 15 hours... and she then fell back asleep in his arms and he held her until I got home. I got home and all she wanted was to nurse and sleep. I laid her down again around 1:20pm after nursing for a while and she continued sleeping. I then messaged our doctors office again. They stayed in touch checking in on her. She finally woke around 4pm that afternoon and nursed but was fussy and stayed very fussy and tired that day. It was then a rough few days. After the 20 hour sleeping marathon, she continued to have temperature spikes between ibuprofen doses. Being in touch with our doctor, we continued to treat symptoms at home. On Friday 11/20/15, she was awake more but still spiking a fever, fussy, and I noticed she was posturing with her left fist/arm where her left thumb was tucked in her fist and her arm pulled back. I would try to open up her hand and she would pull it back into that position. THIS IS WHAT SCARED ME THE MOST! The posturing! This lasted for several days along with the high fever. So Saturday 11/21/2015 we took her in to a clinic and saw a pediatrician - she said her right ear was infected so she got a shot of rocephin antibiotic. However, this was based on just some ear redness and no tests were done to confirm infection and whether it was bacterial or viral. Sunday morning she seemed to be perking up, her temp was around 100.3 and she hadnt had any ibuprofen since the clinic about 5:30pm Saturday. So we went ahead and came to traveled for the Thanksgiving holiday, on Sunday 11/22/2015. About an hour into the trip, she cried so I stopped to check her diaper and nurse her. Her temperature was back up over 102 (this was about 11:30am Sunday), so I gave her infant ibuprofen. She traveled pretty well and slept a lot, nursed pretty well and had a good number of wet diapers. Her cough was worse - and really wet. At bed time her temp was 98.8 so I thought behind us. Monday morning, 11/23/2015, her temp ran 100.2 to 99.8 so still elevated but not too bad - and her last ibuprofen was 11:30am yesterday. Also on Monday 11/23/2015 her body was covered (trunk and face and neck) with a rash - it didnt seem to bother her and wasnt raised at all. Shes also continued to cough quite a bit. She also was really clingy, fussy and just looke
CUR_ILL: She had a 100.4 temp at the doctor when we got there but no other symptoms.

Initial unsolicited report received from the literature on 14 September 2015. This case is linked to 2015SA146032, 2015SA146043, 2015SA146044, 2015SA146045, 2015SA146046, 2015SA146047, 2015SA146048, 2015SA146049, 2015SA146050, 2015SA146051, 2015SA146052, 2015SA146053, 2015SA146054, 2015SA146056, 2015SA146057, 2015SA146058, 2015SA146059, 2015SA146060, 2015SA146061, 2015SA146062, 2015SA146063, 2015SA146064, 2015SA146065 and 2015SA146066, 2015SA146067 (Same literature). The following is verbatim from the article: Background: Reporting of adverse events (AEs) following vaccination can help identify rare or unexpected complications of immunizations and aid in characterizing potential vaccine safety signals. We developed an open-source, generalizable clinical decision support system called Electronic Support for Public Health-Vaccine Adverse Event Reporting System (ESP-VAERS) to assist clinicians with AE detection and reporting. Methods: ESP-VAERS monitors patients' electronic health records for new diagnoses, changes in laboratory values and new allergies following vaccinations. When suggestive events are found, ESP-VAERS sends the patient's clinician a secure electronic message with an invitation to affirm or refute the message, add comments, and submit an automated, prepopulated electronic report to VAERS. High-probability AEs are reported automatically if the clinician does not respond. We implemented ESP-VAERS in December 2012 throughout an integrated healthcare system. We queried the VAERS database to determine the system's baseline reporting rates from January 2009 to March 2012 and then assessed changes in reporting rates with ESP-VAERS. Results: In the 8 months following implementation, 91 622 vaccinations were given. ESP-VAERS sent 1385 messages to responsible clinicians describing potential AEs. Clinicians opened 1304 (94.2 percent) messages, responded to 209 (15.1 percent), and confirmed 16 for transmission to VAERS. An additional 16 high-probability AEs were sent automatically. Reported events included seizure, pleural effusion, and lymphocytopenia. The odds of a VAERS report submission during the implementation period were 30.2 (95 percent confidence interval, 9.52-95.5) times greater than the odds during the comparable preimplementation period. Conclusions: An open-source, electronic health record-based clinical decision support system can increase AE detection and reporting rates in VAERS. Keywords: Vaccine; immunization; adverse reaction; reporting; adverse event. It began on 14Dec2015 and provided significant relief but she believed much less relief than would have occurred without PREVNAR 13 injection. She continued in physical therapy through the end of February. Pain was minimal, but muscle weakness and limited range of motion continued. For tendonitis, the patient has been treated by a nurse practitioner of centers for joint surgery and sports medicine. Concomitant medications included ongoing DIURIL orally at 25 mg, daily (for years) for blood pressure, probiotics (manufacturer unknown) orally from Aug2015 and ongoing not daily 3-4/wk, TYLENOL orally until 01Jan2016 at 650 mg 2x/day for pain, aspirin at 325 mg as needed (one at a time, once in a while occasionally) for pain, tramadol (manufacturer unknown) at 25 mg from 02Dec2015 to 10Dec2015 and TYLENOL P.M. from 12Dec2015 to 01Jan2016. On an unspecified date in Dec2015, the patient experienced muscle pain, joint pain, decreased appetite, fatigue, headache, chills, swelling in her wrist where her thumb attaches, she could not sleep or get comfortable, whole arm has become tender below the elbow. Additionally, the patient experienced muscle weakness and limited range of motion on an unspecified date with outcome of unknown. The patient was hospitalized for muscle pain, for joint pain, for could not sleep or get comfortable from 07Dec2015 to an unknown date; while she was hospitalized for decreased appetite, for fatigue, for headache, for chills, for swelling in her wrist where her thumb attaches, for whole arm has become tender below the elbow from 08Dec2015 to an unknown date. The patient did not receive any treatments for the events muscle pain and joint pain, decreased appetite, fatigue, headache, chills, swelling in her wrist where her thumb attaches, she could not sleep or get comfortable, whole arm has become tender below the elbow. This case was reported in a literature article and described the occurrence of multiple sclerosis in a adolescent subject who received Hepatitis A. Co-suspect products included sodium chloride for an unknown indication. On an unknown date, 183 days after receiving Hepatitis A vaccine, the subject developed multiple sclerosis. Serious criteria included GSK medically significant. The outcome of multiple sclerosis was unknown. The investigator considered that there was a reasonable possibility that the multiple sclerosis may have been caused by Hepatitis A vaccine. Additional information was provided: This case was reported in a literature article and it described the occurrence of sclerosis multiple in patient of unspecified gender at least 10 years old and less than 26 year old who had received HAVRIX. The patient received the vaccines as part of a clinical trial with the following inclusion criteria: availability for the entire study period and using a highly effective contraceptive method during the study if sexually active. In addition to this, it had the following exclusion criteria: previous meningococcal B or hepatitis A vaccine, any contraindication for hepatitis A vaccination, scheduled to receive at least one dose of human papillomavirus vaccine between visit 1 and 28 days after vaccination 2, previous anaphylactic reaction to any vaccine or vaccine-related component, history of microbiologically proven disease caused by N. meningitidis or N. gonorrhea, current pregnancy or breastfeeding. No further information on the patient's concurrent medical conditions, medical and family history or concomitant medication was provided. On an unspecified date, the patient received 2 doses of HAVRIX following a 0 and 6 months schedule. Dosage: either 720 ELISA units or 1440 ELISA units of viral antigen per 0.5mL or 1.0mL dose (age specific doses according to country specific guidelines). Administration route: intramuscular using a 25gauge, 1inch needle; site was upper deltoid muscle with a 25gauge, 1inch needle. Batch numbers were not provided. In addition to this, the patient was administered 0.5mL normal sterile saline solution for injection (0.9% sodium chloride) as placebo at month 2. On an unspecified date, within 6 months of the second vaccine, the patient was diagnosed with multiple sclerosis. Treatment was unknown. Outcome was unspecified at the time of reporting. The authors commented that this had been considered by the investigator as related to study vaccination. The authors concluded that the "the results presented provide additional data demonstrating that bivalent rLP2086 has an acceptable safety and tolerability profile in healthy individuals greater or equal to 10 to 26 years of age. No new safety concerns were identified in this trial of a vaccine that is important for the prevention of a severe disease".

SYMPTOM_TEXT: 01/27/2015 9:30am 0.5 mL MMR Lot # k003806 vaccination administered in Upper Left Leg using 25G x 5/8" Jelco Hypodermic Needle. Grandmother 30 year veteran nurse present as patient's guardian on that day has administered many shots in her career. Stated shock at witnessing how the shot was administered 'very roughly'. Patient experienced immediate extreme leg pain at the point where the shot was administered. Doctor was phoned within a few days to request advice regards pain. Doctor stated pain was normal and would subside in few days to weeks. Leg pain continued at the area of the shot without resolution. Patient taken to see Doctor one month to six weeks later, extreme pain still present causing patient immobility. Dr. prescribed therapy. Therapy course completed, minimal to no improvement. Through the duration of aprox one year pain continues to arise particularly after moderate activity, patient is unable to walk or even stand due to extreme pain starting at the point of the shot and radiating through her leg. Doctor Visit Jan 19th, 2015 discussed continuing pain from vaccination. Was advised to file VAERS report. In contradiction to the clear onset of symptoms tracing their direct roots to the moment of administration of vaccination the Doctor advised to follow a course of testing to determine if some underlying systemic pre-existing condition existed that never manifested itself previously even though patient had multiple previous vaccinations and other normal childhood injuries that never resulted in any long term symptoms such as she has experienced directly upon adminstration of the MMR vaccination. To explore another route beside the highly unlikely idea of a possible pre-existing condition diagnosis Doctor consulted a Rheumatologist who advised an X-ray be taken to examine the possibility of injury due to trauma from the injection. X-ray results for Myositis ossificans were negative. As of the day of this report patient continues to experience debilitating leg pain on a regular basis causing her to have to refrain from anything more than minimum physical activities. She is unable to make it through a day of normal childhood activities, nor participate in sports, nor even bike a few blocks to school without experiencing pain at the spot of the vaccination that makes her have to stop all activity for at least a day before she can walk again.
Patient described shoulder pain almost immediately after receiving the vaccine she continued to have pain and could not lift her arm. She had PF and then an MRI.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Received a call from patient's mom a few minutes after leaving the clinic. She stated that patient had difficulty of breathing while in the car and had started to c/o being itchy. She immediately turned around and went back to the clinic. While in the clinic, initial oxygen Sat was 95%, was very itchy with hives on the trunk, with facial erythema but no puffiness nor swelling of the lids nor lips. DUONEB given with resolution of DOB, O2 Sat post-neb was 100%. BENADRYL 7.5  ml and Prednisolone 10 ml PO were given. Facial erythema and hives initially got worse then completely resolved after approximately an hour post-ingestion. Area of MMRV injection was markedly indurated. Consulted Dr. regarding patient's reaction. Advised to repeat a CBC but unfortunately machine does not measure eosinophils (repeat showed decreased platelet from 138 to 88 but no epistaxis/active bleeding).Serum tryptase sent to outside lab. Home meds to include: ZYRTEC, BENADRYL RTC Q 6 hours, Prednisolone 2 mg/kg, Alb nebs prn and EPIPEN Jr. pack. Will schedule f/u with Dr tom. Has previously received Flu without incident, KINRIX and MMRV combination new for patient. KINRIX site of injection without any induration. Patient was discharged home stable with instructions on what to do if hives recur and go to ER for any red flags.

When given the injection, I immediately had pain go down my arm for a few seconds and subsided quickly. By that afternoon my entire upper arm ached. I had pain in my arm that was severe when I raised my arm or adducted my arm. I took ADVIL. I could not sleep due to the pain and my shoulder was stiff in the evenings. I increased to taking 2 ADVIL at bedtime and changed my position for sleeping which helped slightly. I did not feel it was getting any better so on 11/30/2015 I went to the doctor. I was told it was not from the shot (why did it start with the shot?). I was told I had arthritis and a frozen shoulder and given exercises to do. I had an X-ray on 12/1/2015 to check for arthritis. I tried the exercises on 12/1/2015 - doing the exercises did not hurt but the pain in my upper arm became very intense after an hour and later that day, pain shot down my arm again. I stopped doing the exercises. I continued taking ADVIL and avoided adducting my arm or raising it. I waited for the doctor's call about the X-ray which I never got. My arm gradually improved. By January I stopped taking the ADVIL. I still had pain with adduction - so I had pain occasionally when driving as I turn using a hand over hand method. Today in Feb. that pain is gone. I still have pain when dancing when my arm is raised and adducts while I turn. I also have a weakness in that arm when I get a gallon jug out of the refrigerator. I always get a yearly flu shot and never had problems before.
OTHER_MEDS: Lisinopril/HCTZ; KLOR-CON; Simvastatin; Fish oil; Vit. D; METAMUCIL
