Case number PHHY2016US023690, is an initial literature case report received on 22 Feb 2016. The author discussed about the fatal allergic reaction due to influenza vaccine. This report refers to a 42-month-old female patient. Past drug history included acetylsalicylic acid and the patient experienced hives for one day during the first year of life which were thought to follow medication. There was no history of asthma and no family history indicative of allergy could be elicited. Prior to the injection of the vaccine the physician had attempted to obtain a history of allergy to eggs or chicken with negative results. Concomitant medication was not reported. The patient was vaccinated with seasonal influenza vaccine (manufacturer and batch number: not reported) subcutaneously at a dose of 0.5 ml on an unknown date. The patient complained of pains in the abdomen and chills followed by vomiting and convulsions four hours after the vaccination. On examination the patient had a rectal temperature of 109 F. The patient was hospitalized within two hours after the onset of symptoms. On admission to the hospital the patient showed pronounced cyanosis, pupils were widely dilated and unresponsive to light. The lungs showed moist rales over both pulmonary fields and the heart rate was 180 per minute. The abdomen was not distended. The extremities showed convulsive contractions during examination. During the seven hour stay in the hospital the patient became increasingly cyanotic despite oxygen and epinephrine hydrochloride therapy. It was noted that bleeding was pronounced at the sites of hypodermic puncture for the administration of medicaments and that large areas of ecchymosis developed around the injected sites. Slight bleeding was also noted from the vaginal and oral orifices. Convulsions occurred at one to two minute intervals. The convulsions ceased after about five hours and the temperature fell to 103 F. The heart rate increased in rapidity up to 240 per minute but remained regular. The respirations were noted to be Cheyne-Stokes in type. Two hours after entry to the hospital breathing ceased and artificial respiration was instituted. After the resumption of respiration constant bilateral twitching and spasms were noted. This was most decided in the lower extremities. Five hours after admission and seven hours after the onset of symptoms the patient showed great shock with pronounced collapse of the veins which rendered venipuncture difficult. Thirty minutes before death a surgical exposure of the right ankle vein was considered necessary for intravenous therapy. At that time an attempt was made to administer dextrose and saline solution with 10 per cent calcium gluconate. The patient was becoming more cyanotic and it was difficult to obtain the pulse beat. Artificial respiration was again instituted and after an intracardiac injection of epinephrine hydrochloride the patient was pronounced dead. Blood examination showed 80 per cent hemoglobin, 4.02 million red cells and 44,000 white cells with 36 per cent neutrophils, 61 per cent lymphocytes and 3 per cent eosinophils. The clinical picture of the patient was that of an allergic reaction which developed four hours after the injection and was characterized by convulsions, abdominal pain and vomiting with associated hemorrhagic phenomena., respiratory arrest, hyperthermia and death. The outcome of the event convulsions was recovered and outcome of other events was not reported. The cause of death was ascribed to anaphylactic shock secondary to the injection of influenza vaccine with air embolism as an immediate terminal contributory cause. A necropsy was performed about eleven hours after death which revealed the following: Heart: Air embolism was present in the right side of the heart and in the inferior vena cava; there were multiple epicardial hemorrhages. Thymus: Petechial subcapsular hemorrhages were present. Lungs: There were bilateral hypostatic congestion, emphysema of the r

This case was reported by a lawyer via other and described the occurrence of complex febrile convulsion in a 5-month-old male patient who received DTaP vaccine. Co-suspect products included pneumococcal vaccine and varicella vaccine. Concurrent medical conditions included Sotos syndrome, developmental delay, pervasive developmental disorder and macrocephaly. On 26th December 2000, the patient received the 2nd dose of DTaP vaccine. On 27th August 2001, the patient received pneumococcal vaccine and varicella vaccine. In December 2000, less than a day after receiving DTaP vaccine, the patient experienced complex febrile convulsion (serious criteria death, hospitalization and GSK medically significant), status epilepticus (serious criteria death and GSK medically significant), epilepsy (serious criteria death and GSK medically significant), injection site swelling, injection site erythema, apnea (serious criteria GSK medically significant), fever, cyanosis, twitching of limbs, Gaze Palsy (serious criteria GSK medically significant), shallow breathing, grunting and otitis media. On 6th February 2001, the patient experienced jerkiness and generalized tonic-clonic seizure (serious criteria GSK medically significant). On 16th November 2007, the patient experienced cardiac arrest (serious criteria death and GSK medically significant) and cough. On 17th November 2007, the patient experienced multi-organ failure (serious criteria death and GSK medically significant). The patient was treated with ATIVAN, ceftriaxone and phenobarbital. On 16th November 2007, the outcome of the complex febrile convulsion was fatal. On 17th November 2007, the outcome of the status epilepticus, epilepsy, cardiac arrest and multi-organ failure were fatal. On an unknown date, the outcome of the injection site swelling, injection site erythema, apnea, fever, cyanosis, twitching of limbs, Gaze Palsy, shallow breathing, grunting, otitis media, jerkiness, generalized tonic-clonic seizure and cough were unknown. The patient died on 17th November 2007. The reported cause of death was febrile seizure, status epilepticus, epilepsy, cardiac arrest and multi-organ failure. It was unknown if the reporter considered the complex febrile convulsion, status epilepticus, epilepsy, cardiac arrest, multi-organ failure, injection site swelling, injection site erythema, apnea, fever, cyanosis, twitching of limbs, Gaze Palsy, shallow breathing, grunting, otitis media, jerkiness, generalized tonic-clonic seizure and cough to be related to DTaP vaccine. Additional details were provided as follows: The patient was a healthy. On December 26, 2000, the patient received his second dose of the DTaP vaccine. The patient's parents recalled that there was some swelling around the injection site (right upper extremity) and site was red. Early in the morning on 27 December 2000 (within 24 hours of vaccination), the patient's parents found him seizing in his crib and took him to the emergency room. The seizure lasted about 15 minutes and was controlled with medication by the doctors. Five minutes later, the patient began seizing again with apnea and according to the timeline in the medical records, the second seizure was stopped when the patient was given an ATIVAN IV and oxygen. The medical records were unclear, but the second seizure lasted at least a few minutes, and it could have lasted as long as 15 minutes. It was noted that the first seizure was stopped at 4:30 A.M., the second seizure started five minutes later, and the second seizure was stopped at 4:50 A.M. The medical records document the patient's condition on admission and his progression. On admission, the patient was cyanotic and actively seizing. The neurology consult on 27 December 2000, noted that the patient had returned to baseline. The patient had a very high white blood cell count, which suggested that the seizure was related to fever from infection rather than fever from immunization. The patient was administered ceftriax

SYMPTOM_TEXT: This case was reported by a consumer via call center representative and described the occurrence of vaccination failure in a 63-year-old female patient who received FLUARIX QUADRIVALENT. This case was associated with a product complaint. On 18th November 2015, the patient received FLUARIX QUADRIVALENT. In December 2015, 30 days after receiving FLUARIX QUADRIVALENT, the patient experienced vaccination failure (serious criteria GSK medically significant), influenza, runny nose, cough and respiratory tract congestion. On an unknown date, the patient experienced pharmaceutical product complaint. On an unknown date, the outcome of the vaccination failure, influenza, runny nose, cough, respiratory tract congestion and pharmaceutical product complaint were unknown. The reporter considered the vaccination failure and influenza to be related to FLUARIX QUADRIVALENT. It was unknown if the reporter considered the runny nose, cough, respiratory tract congestion and pharmaceutical product complaint to be related to FLUARIX QUADRIVALENT. Additional details were received as follows: This case was not previously reported to anyone. The patient stated that, since receiving the FLUARIX QUADRIVALENT she had been sick twice, once in December (approximately one month after vaccination) and again at the time of reporting that is in February. SYMPTOM_TEXT: Pt. did fine after immunization.  Blood drawn in clinic by MA, approximately 30 minutes after vaccine.  Patient became dizzy and nauseated after blood draw.  Stated room was spinning.  He appeared pale.  He was placed in a supine position lying in the venipuncture chair and monitored.  He continued to feel nauseated on/off for up to 3 hours after the blood draw.  We monitored blood pressure and pulse and offered fluids including grape juice, water, and apple juice.  He had some crackers and grape juice prior to vaccine.  He was awake, alert, and oriented.  After approximately 2 1/2 hours he was offered to go to the ER for IV fluids and nausea medication.  He declined stating he was feeling better but that the nausea kept returning.  While we were speaking he sat forward and vomited approximately 30 cc.  He stated after vomiting he immediately began to feel better.  He was monitored for another 30 minutes, got up to use the restroom without incident, and denied wanting to go to the ER or needing nause medications prescribed from our clinic.  He requested to go home with his daughter, who was able to drive him home with her driver's permit.  He declined needing a wheelchair transport to his car.  He was instructed to call with any worsening of symptoms or should he have any neurologic symptoms such as weakness fatigue or loss of strength in any extremeties, or difficulty breathing or shortness of breath.  He voiced understanding.  Vital signs throughout the day were:  11:59 96/70 pulse 60, 2:35 110/80 pulse 54, 2:45 118/80 pulse 66, 3:04 110/80 pulse 54, 3:27 124/78 pulse 66.  Left at 1600.

Initial unsolicited report received from the literature on 14 September 2015. This case is linked to 2015SA146032, 2015SA146043, 2015SA146044, 2015SA146045, 2015SA146046, 2015SA146047, 2015SA146048, 2015SA146049, 2015SA146050, 2015SA146051, 2015SA146052, 2015SA146053, 2015SA146054, 2015SA146055, 2015SA146056, 2015SA146057, 2015SA146058, 2015SA146059, 2015SA146060, 2015SA146061, 2015SA146062, 2015SA146063, 2015SA146064, 2015SA146065, 2015SA146066 and 2015SA146067 (Same literature). The following is verbatim from the article: Background. Reporting of adverse events (AEs) following vaccination can help identify rare or unexpected complications of immunizations and aid in characterizing potential vaccine safety signals. We developed an open-source, generalizable clinical decision support system called Electronic Support for Public Health-Vaccine Adverse Event Reporting System (ESP-VAERS) to assist clinicians with AE detection and reporting. Methods. ESP-VAERS monitors patients' electronic health records for new diagnoses, changes in laboratory values and new allergies following vaccinations. When suggestive events are found, ESP-VAERS sends the patient's clinician a secure electronic message with an invitation to affirm or refute the message, add comments, and submit an automated, prepopulated electronic report to VAERS. High-probability AEs are reported automatically if the clinician does not respond. We implemented ESP-VAERS in December 2012 throughout an integrated healthcare system. We queried the VAERS database to determine the healthcare system's baseline reporting rates from January 2009 to March 2012 and then assessed changes in reporting rates with ESP-VAERS. Results. In the 8 months following implementation, 91 622 vaccinations were given. ESP-VAERS sent 1385 messages to responsible clinicians describing potential AEs. Clinicians opened 1304 (94.2 percent) messages, responded to 209 (15.1 percent), and confirmed 16 for transmission to VAERS. An additional 16 high-probability AEs were sent automatically. Reported events included seizure, pleural effusion, and lymphocytopenia. The odds of a VAERS report submission during the implementation period were 30.2 (95 percent confidence interval, 9.52-95.5) times greater than the odds during the comparable preimplementation period. Conclusions. An open-source, electronic health record-based clinical decision support system can increase AE detection and reporting rates in VAERS. Keywords. Vaccine; immunization; adverse reaction; reporting; adverse event. This case involves patient (age and gender not reported), who was vaccinated with a dose of Hepatitis A; a dose of HIB; a dose of Varicella (Manufacturer: unknown, batch number, route, dose in series and site of administration of all were not reported) all on unspecified date. The patient had also received a dose of MMR and a dose of PCV13 (Manufacturer: other, batch number, route, dose in series and site of administration of all were not reported) both on an unspecified date. Medical history and concomitant medications were not reported. On unspecified date following the vaccination, the patient had developed rash. Laboratory tests and corrective treatments were not reported. The outcome of the event was not reported. Documents held by sender: none. Follow-up information received from physician on 19-Oct-2015. No additional information was received.

Information has been received from a consumer referring to her 16 years old daughter. The patient was not pregnant. The patient had no medical history and drug reactions or allergies. On an unknown date in 2011, the patient was vaccinated with her first dose of GARDASIL (0.5 ml, lot # and expiry date unknown, intramuscular). There was no concomitant therapy reported. In 2011, almost immediately following her first intramuscular injection, the patient experienced grand mal seizures. The patient's mother also noticed at that time that her daughter's mental acumen began declining (The patient was previously an honor student in school). On unknown dates, the patient was vaccinated with her second and third dose of GARDASIL (0.5 ml, lot # and expiry date unknown, intramuscular). On an unknown date, the patient's mother took the patient to a neurologist who ran a battery of tests including electroencephalogram (EEG), nuclear magnetic resonance imaging (MRI) and computerised tomogram (CAT scan). Subsequently, the test results determined the patient was "mentally challenged". In September 2014, the patient was hospitalized at a hospital for 2 days due to severe seizures (started in September 2014). The patient was also prescribed TEGRETOL (generic) by the neurologist to lessen seizures. The patient's mother also stated that the patient was still suffering from severe seizures. The outcome of grand mal seizures, mental acumen decline and "mentally challenged" was unknown. Causality was not provided. The events were considered to be disabling by the reporter. Upon internal review, the severe seizures and grand mal seizures were determined to be medically significant. Additional information has been requested.
LAB_DATA: Computerised tomogram, mentally challenged; Electroencephalogram, mentally challenged; Nuclear magnetic resonance imaging, mentally challenged

SYMPTOM_TEXT: On January 12, 2016 I went to MD and was given the required vaccinations for a missionary trip. Before going, I had heard that yellow fever vaccinations can sometimes cause a few days of flu-like symptoms that typically last no longer than about three days. I was 70 years old at the time and unaware of the information below from the "Precautions" section of the CDC website which I found after my reaction. "Age greater than or equal to 60 years is a precaution for yellow fever vaccination, particularly if this is the first dose of the yellow fever vaccine given. An analysis of adverse events passively reported to the Vaccine Adverse Events Reporting System from 2000 through 2006 indicates that people aged greater than or equal to 60 years are at increased risk for any serious adverse event after vaccination, compared with younger people. The rate of serious adverse events in people aged greater than or equal to 60 years was 8.3 per 100,000 doses distributed, compared with 4.7 per 100,000 for all vaccine recipients." I developed my first symptoms on Saturday night, January 16 with chills, fever, night sweats and body aches much worse than with the flu. I rotated between TYLENOL and Ibuprofen for the fever and pain and felt better on Monday. However, my fever started climbing on Tuesday and by Wednesday evening I was seriously ill. I saw my local doctor first thing the next morning (Thursday, January 21) and was admitted to the local hospital. I was given IV's for dehydration, TYLENOL for fever, Tramadol for pain, and something for nausea. My doctor also gave me ROCEPHIN by IV to try to keep me from getting pneumonia while unable to be up and out of bed. I became so weak that I could hardly do anything and eating just seemed to take more effort than it was worth plus I had no appetite. Any activity or noise in the room exhausted me even if it was just other people talking. I asked that I have no visitors. I was really sensitive to noise and light and lay for hours awake but with my eyes closed. After three nights in the hospital, my fever was not going as high and I was beginning to try to eat so the doctor sent me home on Sunday afternoon, January 31. By late Tuesday, February 2, my temperature was coming back up and my doctor was out of town so my wife and I went to the emergency room (about 80 miles from home and one of the closest major medical facilities in our area). Having no definitive test and no effective treatment for the yellow fever, the emergency room doctor just started doing tests to figure out what else might be wrong. He thought he heard something in my lungs and ordered an X-ray. That is when they discovered that I had pneumonia. They admitted me to the hospital and assigned me to a hospitalist. After a couple of nights in the hospital, they did another chest X-ray and said that the pneumonia was in both lower lobes of my lungs and worse than originally thought. Dr. said that it did not show up clearly on my X-ray when admitted due to dehydration. He also asked if I was eating, which I was starting to do, and told me that I was borderline malnourished when I first entered the hospital. While I as in hospital, Dr. rotated antibiotics by IV for the pneumonia in addition to giving another one by mouth at night. He gave me TYLENOL for the fever and something for pain. Even though I was still having fever every day, Dr. discharged me after six nights in the hospital and sent me home with a prescription for an antibiotic to be taken for 10 days after discharge. Even after finishing my antibiotic at home, my temperature still rose above normal every day. I made a follow-up visit to my family doctor on February 11, shortly after finishing my antibiotic at home. A chest X-ray showed my lungs to be clear and my blood work was good. There was nothing to do but live with the fever (and take TYLENOL for it), keep hydrated and rest. My temperature continued to come up every day until February 23. That means I ran fever from

I developed a slew of digestive, hormonal, and mood disorders since the administration of the Gardasil vaccines. I had no health issues prior to the vaccines and within a year of receiving them, I developed multiple food allergies, PCOS, OCD, anxiety, dysmennorhea, random episodes of lightheadedness and feeling like I am going to faint, and now I am dealing with possible infertility, since I am on an extremely restricted nutrient rich diet and have not been able to conceive a child in almost a year. I was given this vaccine against my will as an almost 18 year old, I objected strongly to it after hearing of others' reactions, and now the quality of my life is severely diminished. I have wasted thousands of my own money trying to get well and having to deal with adverse health issues as they come up.

This medically confirmed literature report (initial receipt 23-Feb-2016) concerns a 60-year old female patient who developed acute-onset massive proteinuria with NS (nephrotic syndrome) and severe AKI (acute kidney injury) soon after receiving the 2009 H1N1 influenza vaccine. The patient had medical history of bronchial asthma and there was no history of drug allergy. Her medications included montelukast, salbutamol and SERETIDE. She denied use of any other medications, including non-steroidal anti-inflammatory drugs and herbal medications. There was no history of diabetes, hypertension, hepatitis or blood transfusion. She denied smoking, alcohol or intravenous drug use. She was referred to the emergency room (ER) by her primary medical doctor (PMD) for evaluation of elevated serum creatinine level (10.3 mg/ dL). The patient was seen by her PMD one day before her ER visit for evaluation of worsening bilateral lower extremity edema. She had received the 2009 H1N1 influenza vaccine two weeks before her ER presentation. The patient developed fever, intermittent nausea and vomiting and lower extremity edema soon after being immunized with the influenza vaccine. She had refused influenza vaccination in the past as her father died from GB syndrome after receiving influenza vaccine. Review of systems was negative for sore throat, dyspnea, gross hematuria, arthralgias or rash. On physical examination, her blood pressure was elevated at 220/100 mm Hg and there was 3+ pitting edema of the lower extremities. She was afebrile in the ER. The rest of the examination was unremarkable. At the time of ER presentation, the serum creatinine was elevated at 9.93 mg/dL and blood urea nitrogen was 77 mg/dL. The serum creatinine checked three months before presentation to the ER was 0.9 mg/dL. The serum total protein was 7.8 g/dL and serum albumin was low (2.3 g/dL). Because of the high globulin fraction, serum immunofixation was performed, which revealed polyclonal gammopathy but no monoclonal immunoglobulin was seen. Repeat laboratory testing performed subsequently revealed a total protein level of 4.5 g/dL and serum albumin of 2.2 g/dL. Aspartate aminotransferase was mildly elevated (49 U/L). Other liver enzymes were within normal limits. Complete blood count was normal. Urinalysis was significant for 20-30 WBC/hpf, 10-20 RBC/hpf and 3+ proteinuria. Her random urine total protein to creatinine (TP/CR) ratio was significantly elevated at 22. A 24-h urine collection revealed 20.5 g of protein. A non-contrast computed tomography (CT) scan of the abdomen and pelvis in the ER revealed no hydronephrosis or peri-nephric inflammatory changes. Chest X-ray was normal. Workup for secondary causes of the NS and AKI revealed non-reactive hepatitis C virus antibody and hepatitis B surface antigen. The antinuclear antibody, anti-neutrophil cytoplasmic antibodies (ANCA), cryoglobulins, anti-glomerular basement membrane antibody and human immunodeficiency virus (HIV) antibody were all negative. The serum complement levels were normal. A CT scan-guided kidney biopsy was subsequently performed. Kidney biopsy findings: Eight glomeruli were identified on light microscopic examination of the kidney biopsy specimen. The glomeruli showed patent capillary loops and urinary spaces. The interstitium showed patchy edema and mild to moderate inflammatory cell infiltrate composed of mononuclear cells with many eosinophils. The arteries showed mild intimal sclerosis without vasculitis. Immunofluorescence showed scattered fine granular staining for IgG, C3, kappa and lambda light chains in the outer aspect of the glomerular capillary wall. Electron microscopy showed scattered electron dense deposits in the subepithelial and intramembranous locations. Extensive effacement of the epithelial cell foot processes was seen. The kidney biopsy findings were consistent with (stage 1) MN and AIN. Clinical follow-up: The patient was initially started on furosemide and metolazone for mana

SYMPTOM_TEXT: This medically confirmed literature report (initial receipt 23-Feb-2016) concerns a male patient. On an unknown date, the patient received an influenza vaccine (brand, batch number and route unspecified) for indication not provided. On an unknown date following vaccination, the patient developed GB syndrome from which he died. The outcome was reported as fatal. Linked to case: 2016059460 (same reporter). Reporter's Comments: Reporter comments: n/a. Sender's Comments: Company's evaluation and comment: Seriousness criterion/criteria: Fatal outcome. Listedness: Unlisted. Brand of Influenza vaccine not provided. Assessment according to the CSL Inactivated Influenza Virus Vaccine CCDS and the Afluria Product Information, GBS is unlisted due to the fatal outcome. Company Causality: Unassessable. Temporal relationship could not be established. GBS is a known class effect of Influenza vaccine in general and is mediated by immune attack on peripheral nerve myelin. Risk factors include upper respiratory, infections, (40% of cases) and or preceding diarrheal illness due to campylobacter infection (20%). The outcome is usually complete recovery over weeks to months however fatal outcome is due to autonomic disturbances resulting in cardiac arrest being the most common cause, in 20-30% of deaths. Due to missing information causality is unassessable.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Based on additional information received on 26 February 2016, this case initially considered as non-serious was upgraded to serious due to seriousness criteria: disability. Initial unsolicited report received from a consumer on 18 January 2016. This case involves 72-year-old female patient who was vaccinated with a dose of Fluzone HD (batch number not reported) intramuscularly in the right deltoid on 18 October 2015. The patient's pre-existing physician diagnosed allergies, birth defects, medical conditions were not reported and she had no illness at time of vaccination. The patient's concomitant medications were not provided. On 24 October 2015, six days following the vaccination, the patient had experienced numbness, pins and needles feeling, burning type pain in her right leg from the knee to toes and foot drop on the right foot. The patient required ER/doctor visit. Laboratory data was not reported. The patient had received physical therapy as corrective treatment. The outcome of events was reported as not recovered. Follow up information received from a consumer on 26 February 2016 and additional information received on 03 March 2016. Batch number was updated as UI481AA. Pre-existing physician-diagnosed allergies, birth defects, and medical conditions was reported as scleroderma (crest), gastroesophageal reflux disease (GERD), Esophageal Cancer, hypothyroid. The patient did not experience any adverse event prior to vaccination. She did not receive any other vaccinations within 4 weeks prior to date of vaccination. Concomitant medications included Anastrozole 1 mg daily, Calcium 1200 mg daily with "vitamin D", Cyclobenzaprine 5 mg with at bed time, Prolia 60 mg for 6 month "for 6 MO", Furosemide 40 mg daily as needed, Levothyroxine 125 mcg daily, Omeprazole 40 mg daily, Ranitidine 150 mg daily at bed time, Tramadol 5 mg "as needed" pain, Temazepam 15 mg as needed for sleep, sucralfate four times a day. On 29 October 2015, 10 days following the vaccination, the patient had experienced numbness and foot drop. It was reported that, permanent disability resulted on 21 February 2016 and by the time of reporting, patient still had a problem. The patient had a doctor visit on 28 October 2015, she visited a neurologist on 30 Nov 2015, a neurosurgeon on 02 December 2015 and began physiotherapy. Laboratory data included brain MRI (On 02 November 2015), Spine MRI, lower extremity with Doppler, Ultrasound RT. On 10 December 2015, Electromyography was performed. The patient had not recovered from foot drop and numbness. List of documents held by sender: none. Sender's Comments: Foot drop is unlisted with INFLUENZA USP TRIVAL A-B HIGH DOSE SUBVIRION VACCINE whereas numbness, burning leg and tingling is listed. Time to onset seems to be compatible with a role of the vaccination. Complementary information regarding the patient's condition at the time of the events, medical history and investigations exploring alternative etiologies are needed to further assess the case.
OTHER_MEDS: ANASTROZOLE; CALCIUM;  CYCLOBENZAPRINE; PROLIA; FUROSEMIDE; LEVOTHYROXINE; OMEPRAZOLE; RANITIDINE; TRAMADOL; TEMAZEPAM; SUCRALFATE

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Upon internal review on 15-Jan-2016; information about suspect product has been amended. Influenza vaccine was added as an additional company suspect. Based upon the follow up information received from the patient via the patient support program on 17-Dec-2015, the reporter causality was updated from not associated to unknown and company causality was updated from associated to not associated. Based on the follow up information received on 24-Nov-2015 the reporter causality was updated from unknown to not associated and company causality was updated from not associated to associated. Initial information regarding a clinically sponsored solicited case was received on 08-Oct-2015 from a patient via a program. This case concerns an 82 years old male patient who experienced injection site bleeding, lightheaded, abdominal cramping/ stomach cramps, increased bowel movements, upset stomach and muscle pain and soreness on the same day, diarrhea after an unknown duration and face "broke out with red spots" after few months of receiving treatment with PRALUENT and all unspecified time after receiving influenza vaccine. The patient had medical history of heart disease, COPD and asthma. The patient had allergy to NEOSPORIN, iodine, IVP dye and ZYCLARA. Concomitant drugs included IMDUR, PLAVIX, Aspirin and atenolol, all for heart disease. On 24-Sep-2015, the patient received his first injection with alirocumab at a dose of 75 mg every other week subcutaneously (lot/batch number: 5F005AC and expiry date unspecified) for mixed hyperlipidemia, high cholesterol, raised LDL and intermediate coronary syndrome. After first injection, patient stated that he experienced bleeding at the injection site immediately after the injection (date: 24-Sep-2015; latency: same day), lightheaded for 2-3 hours after the injection, abdominal cramping and increased bowel movements for several days after the injection. On 24-Sep-2015 (same day), the patient experienced upset stomach and had muscle pain and soreness to some extent. Upon follow up, it was stated that the patient took alirocumab 03-Dec-2015 and then had influenza vaccine (route, form, dose, frequency, strength, lot/batch number, expiration date and indication not provided). He experienced stomach cramps and on an unknown date in Dec-2015, face "broke out with red spots" and diarrhea for 2 days. Previous alirocumab shot caused mild diarrhea (onset date and latency: unknown) since an unknown date in Dec-2015. Action taken: unknown for influenza vaccine and no action taken for alirocumab. It was not reported if any corrective treatment had been required. Outcome: unknown for abdominal cramping/stomach cramps and face "broke out with red spots", not recovered for muscle pain and soreness and Recovered for all other events. Reporter causality: with alirocumab: not associated for lightheaded, increased bowel movements, injection site bleeding, Unknown for abdominal cramping/stomach cramps, face "broke out with red spots" and diarrhea and not reported for muscle pain and soreness. With influenza vaccine: not reported. Company causality: with alirocumab: associated for injection site bleeding and not associated for all other events. With influenza vaccine: not associated. Additional information was received from the patient via the patient support program on 24-Nov-2015: Height and weight of the patient was added. Medical history, past drugs and allergy history added. Reporter causality was updated from unknown to not associated and company causality was updated from not associated to associated. Indication of alirocumab added as raised LDL. Therapy start date and event onset dates was updated from 23-Sep-2015 to 24-Sep-2015. Clinical course updated and text was updated accordingly. Additional information was received from the patient via the patient support program on 17-Dec-2015: Indications were updated. Event term was updated for abdominal cramping. New events of red blotches and diarrhea were added. Repo
OTHER_MEDS: ALIROCUMAB PREFILLED PEN; IMDUR; PLAVIX; ASPIRIN; ATENOLOL

SYMPTOM_TEXT: This is a literature report from a medical journal. This author reported similar events for four patients. This is the fourth of four reports. The authors report a cluster of cases of IPD (invasive pneumococcal disease) in previously healthy vaccinated children. After observing a cluster of IPD cases among children hospitalized at the authors' hospital queried the institution's database for children under the age of 18 years who presented during 2014 with positive blood, cerebrospinal fluid, or pleural fluid cultures. The authors abstracted demographic, clinical, and microbiological information including pneumococcal serotypes from the medical records. The institutional Review Board approved the study. Five previously healthy children without identifiable comorbidities or suspected immunodeficiencies were diagnosed with IPD between 26Oct2014 and 19Nov2014 based on culture results. Their cultures were forwarded to the hospital for subsequent serotyping. The average age of patients within this cluster was 3.64 years (0.62-5.58 years). Three patients were male. Four children had previously received appropriate immunizations with PCV-13. Three children were found to have serotype 19A (one of whole was unvaccinated, secondary to parental decision) and one child was found to have serotype 4. Both 19A and 4 were included in the PCV-13. The fifth child had serotype 17F, which was not included in PCV-13. S. pneumoniae was isolated from peripheral blood cultures in all cases. Four children presented with pneumonia, confirmed by consolidation on chest X-ray, and one presented with a unilateral infection involving the skin around the eye (preseptal cellulitis). All five pneumococcal isolates were susceptible to beta-lactams and macrolides. Children with bacteremic pneumonia were treated initially with either ampicillin (n=2) for 1-2 days, followed by amoxicillin for a total course of treatment of 10-14 days, respectively, or ceftriaxone (n=2, one of whom had a non-anaphylactic allergy to penicillin), for 1-2 days, followed by amoxicillin or cefpodoxime for 10-14 days, respectively. The patient with preseptal cellulitis received one dose of ampicillin/sulbactam followed with standard dose amoxicillin/clavulanate for 10 days. The patients recovered without complications, except for one child with serotype 4 pneumococcal pneumonia. This child developed empyema after discharge, but was successfully treated with video-assisted thoracoscopy and amoxicillin therapy. The authors report a cluster of IPD among five previously healthy children who presented in 2014. Four of these children had been appropriately vaccinated with PCV-13, therefore these cases represent breakthrough pneumococcal infections. Only one of these patients had a serotype that was not covered by the vaccine. This case refers to a child patient of an unspecified age, ethnicity and gender who received PCV-13 (unknown manufacturer) via an unspecified route of administration, on an unspecified date, at single dose. The patient experienced breakthrough pneumococcal infection, serotype 17F on an unspecified date with outcome of recovered. The patient underwent lab tests and procedures which included susceptibility test: susceptible to beta-lactams and macrolides, peripheral blood culture which detected S. pneumoniae, serotyping: serotype 17F and chest X-ray. Therapeutic measures were taken as a result of the event. Pfizer is the Marketing Authorization Holder of PCV-13 in the reporter's country. This may be a duplicate report if another Marketing Authorization Holder of PCV-13 has submitted the same report to the regulatory authorities.
LAB_DATA: Antimicrobial susceptibility test, susceptible to beta-lactams and macrolides; Blood culture, S. pneumoniae was isolated; Chest X-ray; Serology test, serotype 17F

SYMPTOM_TEXT: This case was reported in a literature article and described the occurrence of rhabdomyolysis in a patient who received Meningococcal B vaccine. On an unknown date, the patient received Meningococcal B vaccine at an unknown dose. On an unknown date, an unknown time after receiving Meningococcal B vaccine, the patient experienced rhabdomyolysis (serious criteria GSK medically significant). On an unknown date, the outcome of the rhabdomyolysis was recovered/resolved. The reporter considered the rhabdomyolysis to be possibly related to Meningococcal B vaccine. Additional information was provided: This case was reported in a literature article and described the occurrence of rhabdomyolysis in a patient of unspecified age and gender who was vaccinated with unspecified rMenB (manufacturer unknown). The patient was the part of vaccination campaign held from December 2013 to May 2014. Monitoring for serious adverse events (SAEs) was conducted from receipt of the first dose to 30 days after the second dose. SAEs were collected passively by phone, email, university clinic visits, and local hospital reports, and actively via questionnaires prior to the second dose and electronic surveys 30 days after the second dose. No information on the patient's medical or family history or concurrent condition was provided. No information on patient's concomitant medication was provided. On an unspecified date between December 2013 and May 2014, the patient received either one or two doses of unspecified rMenB vaccine (administration route and site unspecified; dosages unknown; batch number not provided). On an unspecified date between December 2013 and May 2014, an unknown period after vaccination with unspecified rMenB vaccine, the patient had rhabdomyolysis. Treatment was unknown. The outcome was recovered. The authors commented that the rhabdomyolysis was possibly related to unspecified rMenB. The authors stated that "We described the first use of an unlicensed MenB vaccine to successfully control two institutional outbreaks. Safety monitoring demonstrated no concerning or unexpected patterns of SAEs and supports the sue of rMenB in response to future MenB outbreaks. Until a licensed MenB vaccine is available, prompt multi-agency coordination to facilitate the IND process should be established when a MenB outbreak is suspected." This is 1 of the 2 valid cases in the article. The article is not available for regulatory submission due to copyright restrictions.

This case was reported in a literature article and described the occurrence of gastroenteritis in a 2-month-old female subject who received Rotavirus vaccine. On an unknown date, 5 days after receiving Rotavirus vaccine, the subject developed gastroenteritis. Serious criteria included hospitalization. Additional event(s) included Escherichia urinary tract infection with serious criteria of hospitalization and GSK medically significant. The outcome of gastroenteritis was recovered/resolved. The outcome(s) of the additional event(s) included Escherichia urinary tract infection (recovered/resolved). The investigator considered that there was a reasonable possibility that the gastroenteritis and Escherichia urinary tract infection may have been caused by Rotavirus vaccine. Additional information was provided: This case was reported in a literature article and it described the concurrence of gastroenteritis and urinary infection in a 2-month-old female who had received ROTARIX (GlaxoSmithKline). The patient was deemed to be a healthy infant by the authors and had received the vaccine as part of a clinical study with the following exclusion criteria: significant history of gastrointestinal disease or other serious medical conditions, history of immunodeficiency, known sensitivity to any vaccine components, previous receipt of a rotavirus vaccine, acute illness at the time of or in the previous 48 hours before vaccine administration (axillary temperature higher than 100.2 deg F, more than 3 looser-than normal stools or any episodes of vomiting), participation in another study involving an experimental agent, birth before 37 weeks of gestation, receipt of blood and/or blood products (including immunoglobulin) within 4 weeks before vaccine administration or receipt of any live vaccine within the previous 30 days or an inactivated vaccine within the previous 14 days. No further information on the patient's concurrent medical conditions, medical and family history or concomitant medication was provided. On an unspecified date between March 2011 and September 2013, the patient received a dose of ROTARIX. Dosage unknown; administration route and site unspecified; batch number was not provided. On an unspecified date, 5 days after the vaccination, the patient was admitted to hospital with gastroenteritis. She was also diagnosed with Escherichia coli urinary tract infection. Patient was discharged home after 48 hours. This was a serious case as the patient required hospitalisation. Treatment was unknown. Outcome of the gastroenteritis was recovery without sequelae according to the authors. Outcome of the urinary tract infection was unspecified at the time of reporting. The authors commented that her admission was believed to be associated with the vaccine. The authors concluded that "mixed rotavirus vaccine schedules are safe and non-inferior in immune responses when compared with those in which a single formulation of licensed rotavirus vaccines is administered alone."

This case was reported by a consumer via patient support programs and described the occurrence of vaccination failure in a 78-year-old male patient who received Influenza vaccine. Co-suspect products included ADVAIR Diskus inhalation powder for asthma and emphysema. The patient's past medical history included pneumonia. Concurrent medical conditions included arthralgia multiple (airplane flying accident), emphysema (taking ADVAIR) and asthma (taking ADVAIR). Concomitant products included amlodipine, FLONASE, SINGULAIR, NAPROSYN, PROAIR HFA, Aspirin (Baby) and prednisone. In October 2015, the patient received influenza vaccine (intramuscular). In April 2001, the patient started ADVAIR Diskus (inhaled) 1 puff(s) once daily. In October 2015, an unknown time after receiving influenza vaccine and ADVAIR Diskus, the patient experienced underdose. In November 2015, the patient experienced vaccination failure (serious criteria GSK medically significant), influenza, shivering, difficulty breathing, weight loss, unable to eat, tiredness, diarrhea and vomiting. ADVAIR Diskus was continued with no change. On an unknown date, the outcome of the vaccination failure and underdose were unknown and the outcome of the influenza, shivering, difficulty breathing, weight loss, unable to eat, diarrhea and vomiting were recovered/resolved and the outcome of the tiredness was not recovered/not resolved.
